<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Australia-Protest     09-06 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Australia-Protest,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Activists Say U.S. Navy Turned Water Hoses On Anti-Nuke Protesters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three anti-nuclear protesters were
arrested for trying to cling to the hull of a U.S. Navy frigate,
and activists charged Tuesday that crew members turned high-powered
water hoses on the demonstrators.
   The protesters, who were in rubber dinghies,, were charged with
disorderly conduct after the incident Monday.
   They tried to hang onto the hull of the USS Brewton, which was
moored near Albany off the southern coast of Western Australia.
   Cmdr. Kraig Kennedy, the Brewton's commander, said hoses were
turned on the protesters because they planned to deface the vessel
with spray paint. Earlier, the three attached a banner to the ship.
   Kennedy said the action may have been ``heavy-handed'' but that
every precaution was taken to prevent injury.
   Jo Vallentine, a member of Parliament and an activist in the
Party for Nuclear Disarmament, demanded an apology, saying one
protester was treated at a hospital for an eye injury and facial
bruises.
   `I believe it is the U.S. Navy that should be charged with
disorderly conduct,'' she told reporters after a meeting with
Kennedy.
</TEXT>
