<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 0019EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PrimariesRdp     09-06 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Primaries Rdp,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warmup for Hecht-Bryan Battle in Nevada; Florida Voters Narrow
Senate Field</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Nevada voters were expected to set the stage today for
Democratic Gov. Dick Bryan's drive to oust Republican Sen. Chic
Hecht, while six Florida Democrats and two Republicans fought over
the seat of retiring Sen. Lawton Chiles.
   Hecht and Bryan faced only token opposition in today's
primaries, and for months they have been attacking each other.
Hecht, who is seeking his second term, has criticized the governor
as too pro-labor. Bryan, in the middle of his second term, has
charged Hecht with lacking credibility and being ineffective.
   A poll taken in August for the gaming industry showed Bryan with
a 14-point lead over Hecht, who six years ago narrowly defeated
Democratic Sen. Howard Cannon after the incumbent was implicated in
a Teamsters union scandal. Hecht has stopped releasing his own poll
results but said he is closing the gap and considers the race a
toss-up.
   Hecht, whose voting record is extremely conservative, has become
known for his occasional verbal miscues, once referring to a
``nuclear suppository'' when he meant ``repository.'' A recent
survey of Senate administrative assistants ranked him as the least
effective senator in Washington.
   Hecht's only primary opponent is Larry Scheffler, 38-year-old
owner of a graphics business in Henderson who said he would press
for reprocessing nuclear waste brought to Nevada so that only
low-level, less radioactive waste would remain.
   Bryan's opponents in the Democratic primary are Manford ``Cave
Rock Manny'' Beals, Patrick Fitzpatrick, and Larry Kepler.
   In Florida, a two-man Republican primary matched Rep. Connie
Mack III, grandson of the legendary Philadelphia A's baseball
manager, against former U.S. Attorney Robert Merkle, who
successfully prosecuted Colombian cocaine kingpin Carlos Lehder
Rivas.
   Merkle entered the race late, in June, and Mack was heavily
favored in pre-election polls after outspending his rival by about
$2.2 million to $100,000.
   President Reagan and former Marine Lt. Col. Oliver North made
appearances for Mack, who has one of the most conservative records
in Congress.
   Merkle was frustrated by Mack's refusal to debate, and
emphasized that point by carrying around a life-size replica of
Mack he called ``Cardboard Connie.''
   ``If he debates me, he knows the jig's up,'' said Merkle. ``He'd
be forced to discuss issues. ... People would see the lights are on
but nobody's home.''
   Mack said Merkle wasn't ``a viable candidate,'' and that there
was no reason ``to have been drawn into his campaign. My feeling
was that we should continue with delivery of the message we started
with in October, talking about the importance of freedom, free
markets, less taxes, freedom as an objective of foreign policy.''
   For the Democrats, state Insurance Commissioner Bill Gunter
appeared to hold a wide lead, but not wide enough to win a majority
and avoid an Oct. 4 runoff with the second-place finisher.
   Others in the race were Reps. Dan Mica and Kenneth ``Buddy''
McKay, state Sen. Patricia Frank, former Republican Gov. Claude
Kirk and former Senate postal clerk Fred Rader.
   Gunter, who lost to Paula Hawkins in the 1980 Senate race,
raised $1 million within six weeks of announcing, and opponents
noted he took at least $160,000 from the insurance industry he
regulates. MacKay campaign manager Greg Farmer called Gunter's
department ``a saga of sleaze.''
   The early Democratic frontrunner, former Gov. Reubin Askew, quit
the race in May, saying running for office had become too expensive.
   Democrats acknowledge that their crowded field and likely runoff
may hurt their prospects in November.
   ``I don't think it'll be an easy race, but I think it's
winnable,'' said State Democratic Chairman Charles Whitehead.
</TEXT>
