<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 0029EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     09-06 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miss Arkansas, a blue-eyed blonde
singer, has the best chances of winning the 1989 Miss America
title, says a retired statistics professor.
   Patti Thorn, 23, has a 7-1 chance over the 50 other contestants
vying for the crown Saturday, said George L. Miller, of Bellevue,
Wash.
   For the past 10 years _ to the displeasure of pageant officials
_ Miller has entered facts and figures about the contestants into
his home computer and calculated their odds based on past winners
and finalists.
   Miller's statistics gained credibility in 1980 when he correctly
predicted Cheryl Prewitt would take the title.
   But he has not been successful every year. Most recently, Miller
picked Kellye Cash as Miss America 1987, but did not even have last
year's winner, Kaye Lani Rae Rafko, in his top 10.
   ``She was a dancer who was a nurse and those are both zero
categories on my list,'' he said Monday.
   To make his predictions, Miller, who retired from Northern
Illinois University in 1984, uses such factors as height, weight,
hair and eye color, academic major and talent. His computer
analysis further breaks down talent.
   ``If one is doing an acrobatic dance, that would be better than
an interpretive dance,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A day at the office for George Keeney is
spent carefully watching over his ``pets'' _ a barrel of
cockroaches, containers of cenipedes and jars of maggots.
   Keeney, 29, is an entomologist responsible for making sure
science classes at Ohio State University don't run short of things
that crawl and creep.
   ``We're kicking into high gear now that the students are coming
back,'' he said. ``One professor wanted 1,000 female German
cockroaches for one class last year. That's tedious work.''
   Most of Keeney's bugs are destined for dissection. Some will be
sprayed with chemicals in toxicology tests. Others will simply be
watched so students can study their behavior.
   Flies and cockroaches are high on the science professors'
most-wanted list. Keeney raises cockroaches by the barrelful.
   A few, like an unusual Central American ant that inflicts a
powerful sting, are being studied for possible use in fighting
illnesses.
   Keeney has two African millipedes. They look like foot-long hot
dogs standing on a thousand toothpick legs. Actually, they do not
have a thousand legs. Keeney counted them. They have 370.
   Centipedes have 54 legs.
   ``We're not doing any research with them right now,'' Keeney
said, picking up a handful of the insects. ``They're more or less
pets.''
</TEXT>
