<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Olympics     09-06 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Olympics,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Olympic Medalists Will Collect Cash in Seoul</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviets athletes who win gold medals at the Seoul
Olympics will be awarded the equivalent of $19,000 for their
efforts, the head of the Soviet Olympic Committee says.
   Marat Gramov announced the new policy at a news conference
Monday and denied such payments conflict with the purely amateur
status Soviet athletes purportedly possess.
   He said those on the 550-member Soviet team in Seoul who win
gold medals will be paid 12,000 rubles ($19,047). Silver medalists
will receive 5,000 rubles, and bronze medalists will collect 3,000
rubles.
   Those are handsome sums in a country where the average monthly
wage for a factory worker is around 200 rubles.
   According to Mikhail Dmitrieyev, deputy foreign editor of the
daily newspaper Sovietsky Sport, the sums earmarked for Seoul
medalists will be the largest ever paid to Soviet victors in a
Summer Games.
   ``If they received $100 in the past, it was considered a large
sum,'' Dmitrieyev said in a telephone interview, referring to
payments made to Soviet participants in the 1976 Montreal and 1980
Moscow games.
   The Soviet Union did not take part in the 1984 Olympics, held in
Los Angeles. According to Dmitrieyev, Soviet winners at the 1988
Calgary Winter Olympics also received large sums to reward them for
good performance.
   Gramov noted that 15 percent of the prize money paid to Soviet
medalists will be in foreign currency.
   That is important because the Soviet ruble, which is not
convertible into foreign currency, is useless abroad and cannot buy
the sort of Western consumer goods that many Soviets covet.
</TEXT>
