<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Wildfires 2ndLd-Writethru a0682 09-06 1057</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wildfires, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0682,1084</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yellowstone Area Fires Threaten Towns, High Wind Expected</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 1st to UPDATE with quote. Subs 17th
graf pvs `Also inside' to UPDATE acreage. Subs 21st graf pvs `About
30' to UPDATE with new Idaho fire. Subs 23rd graf `The weather' to
UPDATE Dry Fork acreage. Inserts one graf after 26th graf `Oregon's
largest' to UPDATE with Washington governor activating Guard.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XYS1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COOKE CITY, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire trucks from as far away as Nevada
took position in two smoke-filled Montana towns Monday and
residents here waited to see if a backfire would burn fast enough
to protect them from a wind-driven forest fire.
   ``First it starts snowing ash. Then it starts raining fire,''
said fire information officer Pat Kaunert as he stood in a
65-foot-wide fire break bulldozed through the forest.
   Top federal officials said that blaze and 12 other fires in and
around Yellowstone National Park had burned 900,000 acres as of
Monday.
   Gary Cargill, chief federal forester for the Rocky Mountains,
warned that an additional 300,000 acres may be consumed this week,
despite the efforts of 9,000 firefighters.
   And Cargill warned that 20 to 30 mph southwesterly wind is
expected to arrive in the region Tuesday with a weather front.
   Protection of life and property are the top priorities, he said
at a news conference in Bozeman. ``Containment of further acreage
is just not in the cards.''
   He said many of the nation's best firefighters ``are being
whipped day after day'' by the Yellowstone fires.
   Evacuation orders for Cooke City and a town three miles west,
Silver Gate, were issued Sunday morning. By Monday night, about 30
of the approximately 150 residents in the two towns remained, said
Bob Fry, an emergency services official.
   ``Some of them are staying around because they want to see what
the fire does,'' Fry said. ``They're mostly packed up, though, and
we're trying to push them out.''
   A backfire had been set by firefighters as a shield against the
approaching Storm Creek fire Sunday just a half-mile from Silver
Gate.
   Firefighters wanted to establish a two-mile buffer of charred
forest between Silver Gate and the 61,300-acre Storm Creek fire.
But by Monday, the backfire had burned only a half-mile swath, said
fire information officer Chris Comstock.
   ``With an 18 to 20 mph wind behind the fire, that line wouldn't
stop it. You'd just stand there in the line and watch it go over
your head,'' he said.
   And if the backfire hadn't gone far enough, the wind would blow
embers from the backfire itself into residential areas, endangering
the town it was meant to protect.
   To prepare for that possibility, fire trucks rolled into
positions around the two towns. About 75 trucks were called in from
as far as Nevada to protect buildings, Comstock said.
   ``We're here till they tell us to get out of Dodge,'' said Ty
Ripley, manning a fire truck from the eastern Montana town of
Glendive, 400 miles away.
   Comstock said firefighters also were worried that the Storm
Creek fire and three other major fires in and around Yellowstone
have created their own wind circulation, ``almost like a whirlpool
of wind,'' around the Yellowstone Basin.
   That circular wind pattern may encourage the fires to reach out
toward each other, which could create a huge ring of flame that
would eat its way inward through unburned forests, Comstock said.
   Also inside Yellowstone, firefighters worried that the expected
wind would blow the 141,900-acre North Fork fire back toward the
complex of visitor facilities around Old Faithful Geyser.
   But Steve Iobst, a fire information officer, said a lack of
vegetation in the Old Faithful area would make it easy to protect
the development.
   On the western side of the park, which is largely in Wyoming,
fire officials were confident they could protect West Yellowstone,
Mont., a community of 750 people, from an advancing lobe of the
North Fork fire just 2{ miles away Monday.
   ``Everything is based on what these winds do to us in a couple
of days,'' said Brian Avery, a senior Forest Service fire oficial,
referring to the anticipated southwesterly wind.
   About 30 miles to the west in the Targhee National Forest, about
55 firefighters battled a new 25-acre blaze believed caused by
humans. The fire burned to within 50 yards of half dozen summer
homes near Macks Inn, Idaho, but the winds pushed the flames in the
opposite direction, fire commander Wayne Bushnell said.
   In the northern Rockies, officials warned that an approaching
weather front could drive existing blazes past fire lines and cause
fires already brought under control to flare up again.
   The weather predictions prompted Forest Service officials to
begin work on an evacuation plan for permanent and summer
residences south of Fortine, in northwestern Montana. The Dry Fork
fire there has scorched 12,300 acres.
   ``Right now, we've got our fingers crossed that this wind isn't
going to be that harsh,'' said fire information officer Dick Guth.
That fire is considered about 60 percent contained.
   Elsewhere, calmer wind and slightly lower temperatures Monday
helped firefighters grapple with blazes that charred nearly 21,000
acres of southern California brush.
   Oregon's largest fire of the season was nearly contained at just
under 57,000 acres in the rugged Hell's Canyon National Recreation
Area.
   Washington Gov. Booth Gardner activated the National Guard to
help provide support and transportation for hundreds of
firefighters.
   Containment of Washington's largest fire, the 12,500-acre White
Mountain Complex in Ferry County, was at least five days away,
officials said Monday, but it had stopped moving toward the town of
Republic.
   In Utah, air tankers and fire crews scrambled Monday to stop a
runaway brush fire moving toward the northern Utah community of
Paradise, authorities said.
   ``Right now they've got a problem,'' said Kathy Jo Pollock,
Interagency Fire Center spokeswoman. ``They've got a 250-acre fire
heading for the town. It just broke out a little while ago.''
   The fire was the latest in a series of fires raging on Utah's
tinder-dry landscape Monday. Air tankers that had been used for a
5,400-acre brush fire near Salt Lake City were diverted to the fire
near Paradise, a community of about 500 residents between Ogden and
Logan in the Wasatch National Forest.
   Forests also burned in Idaho.
</TEXT>
