<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 0126EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-IndigentPrograms     09-06 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Indigent Programs,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Average Cost of Lawyer for Poor Defendant Now $223</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department says it now costs an
average of $223 to provide legal representation for a poor criminal
defendant, and the number requiring such services has risen sharply
since 1982.
   The Bureau of Justice Statistics said Monday the $223 cost, the
average in 1986, is up from $196 per case in 1982. The caseload
rose to nearly 4.5 million, up about 40 percent from the 3.2
million cases four years earlier, the bureau said in a report.
   The 50 states and Washington, D.C., spent a combined $991
million for indigent defendants in 1986, compared to $625 million
in 1982 _ an increase of 60 percent. The programs are financed by
state, county and local governments in each state.
   The rights of poor criminal defendants to legal representation
were spelled out in a number of Supreme Court rulings beginning in
1932.
   One case was the landmark Gideon vs. Wainright in 1963, when the
court extended the right to counsel in state courts to all indigent
defendants charged with a felony.
   Some states have expanded the program to include representation
for proceedings involving parole, probation, parental rights, civil
commitment and post-conviction matters.
   The department said Arkansas spent the least for indigent
defendants _ an average of 69 cents per state resident. The
District of Columbia spent the most, $29 per capita.
   The average per capita expenditure nationwide was $4.11 in 1986,
up from $2.76 in 1982.
   When average costs per indigent case were computed, Arkansas
again was last, spending $63 per case in 1986. New Jersey was
first, spending an average of $540.
   There are three basic programs used to provide the legal
services.
   Assigned counsel programs feature case-by-case appointments of
lawyers; in contract programs, the government contracts with
individual lawyers, law firms or local bar associations to provide
services for a given period; and in public defender programs, a
salaried staff is hired to provide legal services.
   The report was an update to a 1982 study on indigent defendants.
Since the initial study, the report said, there was a movement from
county to state financing; an increase in rates of compensation
paid to private lawyers, and expanded use of contracts for
providing representation to the poor.
   Here are the total state-by-state expenditures (including
Washington, D.C.) in 1986, in millions; the per capita expenditure
in actual dollars; and the state's ranking in per capita spending:
   Alabama, $6.1 million, $1.52, 44; Alaska, $6.8 million, $12.91,
2; Arizona $16.2 million, $4.89, 10; Arkansas, $1.6 million, 69
cents, 51; California, $251.5 million, $9.32, 3; Colorado, $12.1
million, $3.71, 21; Connecticut, $9.2 million, $2.90, 25; Delaware,
$2.7 million, $4.34, 14; District of Columbia, $18 million, $28.90,
1; Florida, $82.1 million, $7.03, 5.
   Georgia, $8.3 million, $1.36, 47; Hawaii, $4.3 million, $4.13,
18; Idaho, $2.6 million, $2.62, 28; Illinois, $33.1 million, $2.87,
26; Indiana, $10.9 million, $1.99, 37; Iowa, $11.5 million, $4.05,
20; Kansas, $4.2 million, $1.73, 41; Kentucky, $7.6 million, $2.06,
36; Louisiana, $10.8 million, $2.41, 34; Maine, $1.9 million,
$1.67, 42.
   Maryland, $20 million, $4.49, 13; Massachusetts, $20.7 million,
$3.56, 22; Michigan, $43.6 million, $4.77, 11; Minnesota, $14.1
million, $3.36, 24; Mississippi, $2.9 million, $1.11, 50; Missouri,
$6.7 million, $1.33, 49; Montana, $4.2 million, $5.15, 8; Nebraska,
$4.3 million, $2.71, 27; Nevada, $6.3 million, $6.63, 6.
   New Hampshire, $4.3 million, $4.22, 16; New Jersey, $31 million,
$4.07, 19; New Mexico, $6.2 million, $4.25, 15; New York, $111.6
million, $6.28, 7; North Carolina, $16.4 million, $2.60, 29; North
Dakota, $1.2 million, $1.81, 39; Ohio, $26.5 million, $2.47, 32;
Oklahoma, $4.4 million, $1.36, 48.
   Oregon, $22.4 million, $8.31, 4; Pennsylvania, $28.6 million,
$2.41, 33; Rhode Island, $2 million, $2.14, 35; South Carolina,
$4.6 million, $1.39, 46; South Dakota, $1.7 million, $2.52, 31;
Tennessee, $7.7 million, $1.62, 43; Texas, $32.8 million, $1.97,
38; Utah, $2.3 million, $1.40, 45; Vermont, $2.7 million, $5.13, 9;
Virginia, $10.1 million, $1.75, 40; Washington, $21.1 million,
$4.75, 12; West Virginia, $4.8 million, $2.53, 30; Wisconsin, $20
million, $4.19, 17; Wyoming, $1.7 million, $3.45, 23.
