<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 0133EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Congress-Environment     09-06 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Environment,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Time Running Out on Environmental Bills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress has left itself about a month to
solve major environmental problems that have eluded solution in the
1980s _ redoubling the battle against urban air pollution and
launching an attack on acid rain.
   Lawmakers return to town Wednesday, shooting for an early
October adjournment. As the House and Senate enter the home
stretch, clean air legislation is barely out of the starting gate.
   Neither chamber has even scheduled debate on the Clean Air Act
revisions that are being watched closely by some 100 cities and
metropolitan areas that failed to meet last December's deadline for
bringing ozone and carbon monoxide levels within national health
standards.
   A comprehensive package to control urban smog, acid rain and
airborne toxic chemicals was ready for Senate debate last November,
but it has been stalled by a variety of opponents, most notably
Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.
   The package's principal sponsor, Sen. George Mitchell, D-Maine,
has been trying to negotiate floor time with Byrd. Mitchell has
said that if necessary, he will offer his air bill as an amendment
to must-pass legislation.
   In the House, serious closed-door negotiations among leaders of
the Energy and Commerce Committee didn't begin until this summer,
leaving little time to get a complicated proposal ready for the
floor.
   Any package produced by Congress would most likely give cities
more time to clean up their air but also require tougher actions to
combat pollution, from local driving restrictions to stricter
emissions standards for vehicles.
   Debate, a good bit of it in scientific terms, centers on how
much more time will be granted and just what corrective steps will
be required. A complicating factor is that the nation has already
employed the measures that can bring large and quick reductions in
pollution.
   Acid rain control is simpler scientifically but far more
complicated economically and geographically.
   Acid rain, a byproduct of coal-burning factories and power
plants, is a major concern of the East, which is downwind from the
industrial Midwest. Just who pays to clean up Midwestern emissions
is a major question, with many Western lawmakers cool to a national
subsidy for Midwestern cleanup costs.
   Byrd not only has power plants in his state that would have to
reduce their emissions, his state has huge deposits of high sulfur
coal that could lose its market to cleaner burning coal from other
states under an acid rain control bill.
   Congress has a fallback option if it fails to produce clean air
legislation. It can, as it did last December, pass another stopgap
bill that would prevent the Environmental Protection Agency from
taking action against areas not meeting the standards.
   The environment surfaced as an issue last week in the
presidential race between Republican George Bush and Democrat
Michael Dukakis. Bush claimed to be highly committed to a cleaner
environment, although the record of the Reagan-Bush administration
has been given dismal marks by environmental groups.
   The clean air fight is at the top of the
environment-conservation agenda for the 100th Congress, but other
issues are vying for attention in the closing weeks of the
election-year session.
   One that might not take much time is the early 1987 request by
the Reagan administration and the oil industry to allow petroleum
exploration in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge on Alaska's
north coast.
   The Senate Energy and House Merchant Marine and Fisheries
committees have endorsed drilling bills, but the House Interior
Committee, where the environmental lobby has more clout, is sitting
on the House bill.
   Likely to emerge from Capitol Hill after a four-year struggle is
a renewal of the Endangered Species Act authorizing a 50 percent
increase in program spending in the early 1990s.
   Congress is also ready to pass a $9.8 billion fiscal 1989
spending bill for the Interior Department and other land and
resource agencies. It is drawing veto threats because it would
delay spending for clean-coal technology research and bar oil
leasing off portions of the coasts of California, Massachusetts and
Florida.
   House and Senate negotiators are putting the finishing touches
on legislation that would encourage the use of less-polluting
methanol, ethanol and natural gas as alternatives to imported
petroleum for powering vehicles.
   Awaiting Senate action are House-passed bills that would
reorganize the National Park Service to make its director
independent of political appointees in the Interior Department; cut
back on commercial timbering in the Tongass National Forest in
Alaska; and prevent a shopping center from being built adjacent to
the Manassas National Battlefield Park in northern Virginia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
