<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen     09-06 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says Time to Spread Prosperity to All Americans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd
Bentsen is stepping up his attacks on the Republicans while
hammering home the Democratic theme that the U.S. economy can do
better and distribute the benefits more fairly.
   ``I think you'll see a more aggressive campaign,'' Bentsen told
reporters on Monday. He then went on to criticized Vice President
George Bush as someone who gets his economic advice at
``Disneyland.''
   Bentsen was visiting a job training program today in
Lawrenceville, Ga., where people are taught to make computer
circuit boards. He later planned to visit Virginia Polytechnic
Institute in Blacksburg, Va., before returning this evening to
Washington.
   The visits appeared to be aimed directly at Republican positions
_ GOP vice presidential nominee Dan Quayle's sponsorship of a jobs
training bill and George Bush's statement that he wanted to be
``the education president.''
   Beginning his fall campaign on Labor Day in his native Texas,
Bentsen attacked Bush and Quayle as operating ``on autopilot'' when
the nation needs to compete more aggressively in world markets.
   Echoing Democratic presidential nominee Mike Dukakis, he said
ideology is not the issue.
   ``The Republicans like to talk about left and right. But this
election is not about moving left or right,'' he said. ``It is
about standing still with George Bush or moving forward with Mike
Dukakis.''
   Bentsen, speaking to a partisan Democratic rally in Beaumont,
ridiculed Bush's statement that the Republicans would create 30
million new jobs, noting there were only 6 million people out of
work.
   ``I understand George Bush is out at Disneyland today. I think
he's out there talking to his economist,'' he said.
   Bentsen told reporters traveling with him that he expected to
take Texas and win the national election, but he acknowledged the
Democrats were revising their tactics.
   ``You can't keep taking the kind of attacks that we saw,'' such
as Bush's repeated suggestions that Dukakis was unpatriotic.
   The Texas senator's events on Labor Day were boastfully
patriotic. His speech in Beaumont was given standing before a huge
American flag, and when he met Dukakis for a picnic in St. Louis
later in the day, the thousands of spectators had been handed
little flags.
   Bentsen's trip to Atlanta was his first campaign appearance in
Georgia since he received the vice presidential nomination at the
Democratic National Convention in July. Bentsen had planned to
visit Atlanta on his last campaign trip, but was forced to cancel
when his campaign plane was grounded.
   Bentsen's spokesman, Mike McCurry, acknowledged that the
Democrats were behind in the polls in both Georgia and Virginia but
said with help from state Democratic officials they think there is
a chance to reverse that by election day.
</TEXT>
