<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Belgium-Spy     09-06 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Belgium-Spy,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Belgian Colonel Accused of Spying for Soviet Bloc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Bwelgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says it arrested a
54-year-old Belgian air force colonel on suspicion of spying for an
East European nation for profit, and that the suspect had confessed.
   Defense Minister Guy Coeme announced Monday that the suspect,
Col. Guy Binet, had access to documents of the Belgian army and the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization and was believed to have started
spying for a Soviet bloc country two years ago. He did not identify
the country.
   ``At first sight it does not seem that the documents that he
might have passed on are of a nature to destabilize the NATO
strategy or apparently have extremely important implications for
the national defense,'' Coeme told reporters.
   He said Binet was arrested Saturday and had confessed. But he
did not say what Binet had told investigators or where the suspect
was being held.
   Coeme said it appeared that Binet was driven by profit rather
than ideological reasons.
   ``He worked on his own and in direct contact with the foreign
power,'' the minister said, and apparently received tens of
thousands of dollars for the information he provided.
   A search of Binet's house yielded material ``that certainly had
to be used for espionage'' including a foreign-made suitcase with a
secret compartment and special photographic material, Coeme said.
   ``We have a list of documents that were sought by the foreign
power,'' he added. `` We do not know whether these documents have
been provided but the documents concerned the Belgian army and NATO
strategy.''
   Binet was two years away from retirement.
   He was charged with treason and ``infractions against the
external security of the state'' according to Coeme. If convicted
Binet could be sentenced to life in prison.
   Coeme said NATO authorities had been informed of the arrest.
   Binet worked for the air force purchasing department and had
access to files on the U.S. F-16 jet fighter and contracts for the
acquisition of helicopters for the Belgian army.
   Coeme said military authorities began investigating Binet a year
ago after the colonel ``aroused suspicion.'' He did not elaborate.
   Binet was questioned Friday and arrested Saturday, the minister
said.
   He said the case could lead to diplomatic problems between
Belgium and the unidentified East European nation.
</TEXT>
