<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Demonstration     09-06 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Demonstration,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Police Hauls Aways Protesters Remembering `Red Terror'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramilitary police, some carrying truncheons,
broke up a demonstration and arrested protesters marking the 70th
anniversary of the launching of a Bolshevik campaign to stifle
political opposition.
   At least 100 police officers, occasionally aided by civilian
auxiliary police, also detained some pedestrians who shouted that
the arrests were ``a disgrace.''
   Monday's demonstration was on the 70th anniversary of the ``Red
Terror,'' the Bolshevik campaign that decreed ``class enemies''
should be put in concentration camps and political opponents shot.
   The demonstration in downtown Pushkin Square was called by the
Democratic Union, an unofficial political group.
   Reporters saw five people arrested and put into buses. Tass, the
official news agency, said 17 members of the Democratic Union were
detained and a court would decide punishment.
   Yuri Mityunov, a spokesman for the Democratic Union, said none
of the members had been in touch with him by late Monday, and
interpreted that to mean they still were in jail.
   During the demonstration, police hauled away an elderly woman
and arrested a man after he put a black ribbon over his mouth,
apparently to symbolize that authorities prevented freedom of
speech.
   It was not clear whether the man or the woman belonged to the
Democratic Union.
   More than 100 people gathered around the woman as she spoke of
being jailed and sent to internal exile years ago.
   When a police officer yelled ``Disperse!'' a column of about 50
policemen forced the crowd aside and grabbed the woman.
   The Democratic Union called the demonstration to remember the
``Red Terror,'' which began with the Sept. 5, 1918 decree against
opponents.
   That started government repression of political dissidents, the
Democratic Union said in a statement, and serves to show that only
a multiparty system and pluralistic economy can safeguard human
rights.
   On Aug. 21, the Democratic Union tried to demonstrate in Pushkin
Square against the Soviet-led invasion of Czechsolovakia 20 years
earlier. Police broke up the rally, arresting more than 100 people.
   Protesters said later they were beaten at the police station.
   A dozen police officers carried rubber truncheons Monday but did
not appear to use them on demonstrators.
   Tass said the program the Democratic Union calls the ``Red
Terror'' was necessary and all revolutionary regimes use such
measures to protect themselves from ``external and internal
enemies.''
</TEXT>
