<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Iran-Politics     09-06 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Iran-Politics,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Musavi Quits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hussein Musavi resigned Monday after
seven years as Iran's prime minister, but will remain as a
caretaker premier until a successor is named, the official Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
   The agency on Tuesday quoted Tehran's Jomhuri Eslami daily,
which printed the full text of Musavi's letter of resignation to
President Ali Khamenei.
   In that letter, Musavi, 44, said he wanted to step down
primarily because he believed as many as eight of his Cabinet
members will fail to win a vote of confidence in the Majlis, Iran's
270-seat Parliament.
   The letter apparently did not specify why he believed that, but
But Musavi said his administration would not be able to function
with eight vacant Cabinet posts.
   Musavi did not identify the Cabinet members, who have been at
their posts since he carried out minor shuffles following two-stage
parliamentary elections in April and May.
   After that balloting, Musavi, a radical who has sought major
economic reforms in the face of bitter opposition from conservative
clerics, said he planned only minor changes in his cabinet.
   Jomhuri Eslami did not say whether Khamenei had accepted
Musavi's resignation, but IRNA said the president had apparently
done so.
</TEXT>
