<HEAD>Dollar Loses Ground Against Yen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with closing Nikkei, dollar;
PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, Cancer treatment-related ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar lost ground against the Japanese yen,
while share prices fell on the Tokyo Stock Exchange Tuesday.
   The dollar, which opened at 136.25 yen, 0.22 yen higher than
Monday's close of 136.03, finished trading at 135.60 yen, down 0.43
yen, after moving in a range of 135.40-136.25 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which shed
146.67 points Monday, finished at 27,320.51. Although the market's
main index gained 107.90 points early in the morning, share prices
fell 21.07 points, or 0.08 percent, by the end of the day.
   Cancer treatment-related issues led a market rebound early in
the morning session, but share prices could not maintain the surge
because the market lacks energy, Yoshio Shimoyama of Nikko
securities said.
   Issues related to cancer treatment rose following newspaper
reports Tuesday morning of a discovery by Japanese researchers
differentiating human DNA that could normalize cancer cells.
   ``Some of the external factors around the stock market, such as
the dollar-yen rate, are getting better, but the market still has
domestic problems including concerns about insider trading,''
Shimoyama said.
   ``Players are mainly individual investors, and the trading was
thin because institutional investors were staying away,'' he added.
   On the foreign exchange, dealers said trading was cautious with
investors in a wait-and-see mood.
   They said most participants remained on the sidelines concerned
about what will happen to the New York market after its three-day
holiday.
</TEXT>
