<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 0344EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Swaziland     09-06 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Swaziland,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kingdom Marks 20 Years Of Independence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MBABANE, Swaziland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ruled by the world's youngest monarch,
tiny Swaziland marked 20 years of independence today as a nation
rich in tradition and largely free of the turbulence that plagues
its neighbors.
   Wedged between South Africa and Mozambique, this kingdom of
rolling hills and lush valleys has spent the past two decades
pursuing both Western-style modernization and preservation of
age-old customs.
   Progress means a new Coca-Cola bottling plant in the capital of
Mbabane, video cassette recorders in the expanding shops and luxury
tourist hotels.
   Tradition, meanwhile, calls for regular celebrations with
singing and dancing by bare-breasted maidens in tribute to
20-year-old spear-wielding King Mswati III and his mother, known as
the Great She Elephant.
   For these festive occasions, including a nine-hour independence
celebration planned today at the country's main stadium, both men
and women appear in traditional red, orange and yellow skirts, with
long strands of beads and feathers in their hair.
   The men carry animal skin shields, the women wear beehive
hairnets.
   The baby-faced king, who already has four wives, was barely four
months old when his nation received independence from Britain on
Sept. 6, 1968.
   Two years ago, he replaced his father, the late King Sobhuza II,
who ruled for 62 years and had at least 68 sons.
   Economically, landlocked Swaziland remains an agricultural
nation heavily dependent on South Africa, which borders it on three
sides.
   Thousands of Swazi men work in South Africa's mines and the vast
majority of Swaziland's imports reach the country via its powerful
neighbor.
   A handful of foreign firms that disinvested from South Africa _
such as Coca-Cola _ have moved their plants to Swaziland. Another
approach has been for firms in South Africa to falsely label their
goods as ``Made in Swaziland'' to evade embargoes against South
Africa.
   Canada has received ``Made in Swaziland'' wine, even though
there are no vineyards in Swaziland. Citrus produce amounting to
four times Swaziland's annual output has turned up with Swazi
labels in the Middle East.
   Swaziland's eastern neighbor, Mozambique, offers access to the
Indian Ocean and alternatives to South Africa transport routes. But
Mozambique's main contribution at present is an unwelcome one _
more than 100,000 refugees who have fled into Swaziland from famine
and civil war in their country.
   Swaziland, half the size of Belgium, has two refugee centers
designed to hold just a few thousand people.
   Aside from the refugees, who swell the country's population by
about 15 percent, Swaziland is ethnically homogenous and has
avoided the inter-tribal strife that has plagued many other African
countries.
   The relatively few indidents of political violence in recent
years generally have involved anti-apartheid activists and
guerrillas from South Africa, who on occasion have been targets of
cross-border raids and kidnappings by South African agents.
   The king and the royal family have the final say on all major
matters. But most day-to-day business is left in the hands of the
Cabinet, Parliament and the bureaucracy, which conduct the
political affairs with a distinctive Swazi touch.
   When the parliamentary electoral college was selected last
November, members were chosen by voters who passed through cattle
gates next to the candidate of their choice.
   When retired white farmer Rex Baxter and his wife arrived to
vote, policemen grabbed him, placed him at a gate and told him he
had been chosen as a candidate. While being whisked away for
week-long private consultations with the other winners, Baxter
shouted to his wife to bring his heart tablets and cigarettes from
home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880906-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 0356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Canada-Natives     09-06 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Natives,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Signs Historic Pact To Give Indians Arctic Tract</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Dollar figures U.S.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   RAE-EDZO, Northwest Territories (AP) _ Two native groups in the
Arctic will become the largest non-government landholders in North
America under a historic agreement signed by Prime Minister Brian
Mulroney.
   The long-delayed agreement, signed in this tiny community 200
miles south of the Arctic Circle on the shores of Great Slave Lake,
will give the Denes and Metis Indian nations nearly 4,000 square
miles of land and special rights to an area the size of Oklahoma.
   Mulroney said the signing marked a ``day of justice'' and
heralds ``new economic and political development'' for the north.
But native leaders say many specifics must be negotiated before a
final pact is signed in two years.
   Monday's agreement gives about 15,000 natives of the Dene and
Metis Indian nations ownership and oil and mineral rights to about
3,850 square miles of the rocky bush land bordering the Arctic
Ocean.
   It would also give them special rights and interests _ including
a voice in wildlife, forestry and land management _ for a nearly
70,000 square miles area.
   The agreement, which followed 15 years of negotiations, includes
a $405 million cash settlement that would be paid out over 20 years
beginning in 1990 _ the year negotiators hope to have a final
settlement.
   ``This agreement of principle, when carried forward to its final
form, will establish a new, stronger and healthier relationship
between the people of this area and the governments which serve
them,'' said Mulroney, who was welcomed with the beat of drums and
a ceremonial prayer chant.
   He added that the agreement marks ``real progress'' in the Dene
quest for self-determination.
   But the chief of the Dene nation warned that Ottawa and native
leaders must still negotiate issues such as aboriginal title and
self-government.
   ``We will be seeking changes before we reach the final
agreement,'' Bill Erasmus told about 1,000 Dogrib Indians on the
steps of the village's Roman Catholic church.
   The Dogribs are the largest of seven groups making up the Dene
nation.
   Ottawa said the Dene handed over their aboriginal rights when
they signed 1899 and 1921 treaties.
   But the Dene contend they never gave up their aboriginal rights
and, under Monday's agreement, are handing over some of their land
in return for financial compensation and the guarantee of hunting
and fishing rights.
   Mike Paulette, president of the Northwest Territories Metis
Association, said he was sure ``we can now negotiate a satisfactory
deal within the next two years.''
   Mulroney's visit to Rae-Edzo, 65 miles northwest of the
territorial capital of Yellowknife, marked his first trip to the
Northwest Territories since his Conservatives gained power four
years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
