<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Politics 1stLd-Writethru a0460 09-06 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Politics, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0460,0669</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Party Kicks Off Election Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to MOVE up Peres vowing to return occupied
land in return for peace. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``The Palestinians
...''
^By DAN IZENBERG</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres kicked off
the Labor Party's election campaign by calling on Palestinians to
end their uprising and start a peace dialogue with Israel.
   Peres also vowed to return occupied territory in exchange for
peace, saying such a move would assure a stronger Israel with a
clear Jewish majority.
   ``We shall rid ourselves of Gaza, we shall rid ourselves of
areas densely populated by Arabs,'' Peres told a crowd of 3,000
supporters Monday night in a concert hall.
   Peres called on Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip to end their 9-month-old rebellion and negotiate with Israel.
   ``We do not wish to oppress them, humiliate them or deport them.
The road is open before them, instead of fighting, there can be
dialogue,'' Peres said.
   ``The Palestinians will come (to negotiate) because a military
option does not exist for them and they still do not have a
political option of their own,'' Peres added and was wildly
applauded.
   The Palestinian revolt is the major campaign issue in the Nov. 1
elections, billed as the most crucial in Israel's 40-year history.
At least 258 Palestinians and four Israelis have died in the
unrest, which began Dec. 8.
   In its new platform, the left-leaning Labor Party calls for the
first time for direct talks with Palestinians and ``leaves the door
open for'' dialogue with the PLO, said Peres aide Yossi Beilin.
   Labor ``will be willing to hold a dialogue with Palestinian
people or agents who recognize Israel, oppose terror,'' and accept
two U.N. resolutions which implicitly recognize the Jewish state,
the platform says.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization is now banned in Israel as
a terrorist organization.
   Labor's platform supports relinqushing parts of the West Bank
and Gaza for peace. The territories are home to about 1.5 million
Palestinians and about 60,000 Jewish settlers.
   However, Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin made it clear that
Israel would not yield all the land captured in the 1967 Middle
East war.
   ``Defensible borders cannot be the pre-1967 borders,'' Rabin
told the rally. ``We will not return to those lines, not even for
peace.''
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's rival Likud Bloc objects to
relinquishing territory to the Arabs and to talks with the PLO. But
it favors a peace dialogue with other Palestinians on the basis of
the 1978 U.S.-brokered Camp David Accord, which preceded Israel's
1979 peace treaty with Egypt.
   The Camp David Agreement calls for five years of Palestinian
self-rule in the occupied territories as an interim solution.
   On July 31, King Hussein of Jordan announced he was cutting
administrative ties with the occupied lands and yielding
responsibility for their affairs to the PLO.
   Peres said he still believed a peace settlement with Jordan is
possible.
   ``We shall invite Jordan and we shall invite the Palestinians,''
to peace talks, he said. ``The Jordanians will come because when we
talk peace, Jordan will not turn away.''
   Speaker after speaker attacked the Likud, setting the stage for
what promises to be a vitriolic election campaign.
   ``We have 55 days (until election day) to confront the coalition
of annexationists, a right wing which has become more extreme,''
said Peres. ``It is a coalition based on fear, a coalition which
spreads fear of peace.''
   While party leaders raised their arms, clenched their fists and
promised victory, many spectators appeared doubtful.
   Recent public opinion polls indicate that the rightist parties
led by the Likud have a slight edge over the liberal coalition
headed by Labor.
   Likud and Labor have maintained a tenuous coalition since 1984
because neither party won a majority that year in the 120-seat
Knesset, Israel's parliament.
</TEXT>
