<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Amnesty-Cuba     09-06 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty-Cuba,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amnesty: Human Rights Improved In Cuba, But Critics Still Jailed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The communist leaders of Cuba continue to imprison
citizens who speak out against them, but have also taken
significant steps toward improving human rights, Amnesty
International says in a report today.
   Cuba's recent release of large numbers of political prisoners,
improvement of prison conditions and limiting of the scope of the
death penalty were welcomed by the international human rights
organization.
   However, laws that have been used to stifle opposition and jail
``prisoners of conscience'' remain in force and seriously threaten
government critics, it said.
   The report was written after a three-member team led by Amnesty
Secretary-General Ian Martin visited Cuba in March for the first
time since 1977.
   The group repeated its longstanding appeal to Cuba for the
unconditional release of prisoners of conscience, people jailed for
their political or religious beliefs. Many recently released
prisoners have been forced to leave Cuba, it said.
   Most political prisoners were charged with ``enemy propaganda''
after writing or saying things the government disapproved of,
sometimes in private letters sent abroad or to foreign embassies in
Havana, Amnesty said.
   It said others were convicted of trying to leave Cuba without
permission or of insulting behavior toward state officials.
   The group believes others were sentenced for politically related
criminal offenses ``where there is reason to believe that they may
have been convicted solely on account of their peaceful opposition
to the Cuban government,'' the report said.
   Amnesty urged the Havana government to speed up a promised
review of hundreds of political prisoners and expressed concern
about their ability to obtain a proper defense and trial.
   It said the ``steady pace'' of recent releases of political
prisoners made it difficult to estimate how many are still held in
Cuba.
   As of early August, about 250 prisoners were being held for
crimes against state security and an unknown number _ believed to
be in the hundreds _ were held under other sections of Cuba's penal
code used to restrict basic rights, particularly the
internationally recognized right to leave one's country, Amnesty
said.
   The Amnesty team met senior Cuban security and legal officials,
visited two prisons holding political prisoners and interviewed
dozens of prisoners in private, the report said.
   It said political inmates in the two prisons, Combinado del Este
and Boniato, were in the past reported to have been beaten, kept in
poor conditions, given inadequate food and denied medical treatment.
   It said Cuban authorities told the visitors they were trying to
improve the worst parts of these prisons. The report noted that
improvements in physical conditions and the prison regime appear to
have been introduced in the last eight months.
   However, Amnesty said prisoners do not feel confident of getting
a fair hearing about complaints and fear retaliation.
   Amnesty said use of the death penalty appears to have been
reduced considerably since the early 1980s.
   It quoted Cuba's justice minister as saying that although 216
people were executed between 1959 and 1987, the number executed
since 1984 is 11, all for common crimes rather than security crimes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
