<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 0557EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrisonMoms     09-06 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Moms,0745</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moms, Children Reunited in Campout Behind Prison Gates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRI COLBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DWIGHT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wearing a yellow poncho in the steady rain,
10-year-old Margaret Nathaniel helped her mother stock their gray
tent with camping supplies: sleeping bags, thin mattresses and a
cooler.
   Outside the tent, beneath a cluster of sturdy oak trees, they
had a clear view of the 12-foot fence, topped with a spiral of
barbed wire, that surrounded them and the rest of the Dwight
Correctional Center, Illinois' only prison for women.
   But inside, at the start of an overnight campout for inmates and
their children, they could ignore the fence, be alone and, if only
for a few hours, do the things that mothers and daughters do.
   ``It gives me pleasure today to sleep with her, to comb her
hair, to wash her,'' said Margaret's mother, Cathy Nathaniel, a
convicted murderer.
   The campout on the last weekend of August was the last of three
held over the summer at Dwight, located some 75 miles southwest of
Chicago. About 80 children and 36 inmates took part in the program,
funded by a federal grant, said Warden Jane Huch.
   The children arrived on a Saturday morning, stayed overnight in
tents with their mothers and left the next day. Volleyball, crafts,
a play performed by the prison drama club and an evening bonfire
helped fill their time.
   The overnight visit gave Sheryl Decker, 37, a chance to have
some ``girl talk'' with her 17-year-old daughter, Debbie, but it
didn't completely ease the pain of separation.
   ``When we look at each other and I know she's got to go beyond
that fence, you know it hurts, and we know it for a minute but then
we shrug it off and we go on,'' Ms. Decker said. ``We kind of play
and get it up out of our system. But it's coming.''
   For Ms. Decker and Ms. Nathaniel, separation from their children
is the hardest part of imprisonment.
   ``That is the punishment, that's it,'' said Ms. Nathaniel, who
hopes to be paroled in 4{ years.
   But the visits help.
   Imprisonment means missing experiences that other mothers and
daughters share, said Ms. Decker, who hopes to be paroled in three
years from an 18-year term for armed violence.
   ``You go to sleep at night and you wake up and it's to the same
thing every day,'' she said. ``It's not like being with your child
and raising them and teaching them the facts of life, going through
their first dating experience ... finding her first love.''
   Ordinary visits can last from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m. on a weekday or
until 7 p.m. on weekends, but Ms. Decker said it's not enough.
   ``You really don't have time to really talk about the most
important parts of a daughter-and-mother relationship,'' she said.
   Ms. Decker has been in prison for six years, since her daughter
was 11. At first Debbie lived with foster parents, then at a
children's home. Now she lives alone in the central Illinois town
of Paris as she begins her senior year in high school.
   She cries as she describes life without her mother, whom she
calls her best friend.
   ``You know how you get up for school and your mom always tells
you you look nice or you go to prom and they're there,'' she says,
haltingly, adding that for her, ``they're not there.''
   Luz Ferro, 26, has been in Dwight on a drug-dealing conviction
for nearly half of her 4-year-old daughter's life.
   Ms. Ferro says her daughter, Karina, who is living with her
sister-in-law in Waukegan, is too young to fully understand why
they have to be separated.
   ``Today she saw this little tent. She said, ``Oh Mama, this is
wonderful,' and I said `Yes, honey, we're going to be sleeping here
tonight.'
   ``And she said, `What about tomorrow night?' and I said `No,
you've got to go back home.'
   ``She said, `Why Mommy, why do I have to go back? Why can't I
stay here and we can sleep in the tent?'''
   That's when Ms. Ferro tried to explain punishment and what it
means.
   ``I tell her ... they punished me because I did something wrong
and the punishment is I have to stay away from you,'' she said.
``That's the punishment.''
</TEXT>
