<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gulf-Vincennes     09-06 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Vincennes,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Cruiser's Postpones Departure After Reported Government
Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The scheduled pullout of the missile
cruiser Vincennes from the Persian Gulf region has been postponed
because at least one Arab government objected to its departure,
U.S. military sources said.
   The 9,600-ton cruiser was to have ended its patrol duties with
the U.S. Joint Task Force Middle East on Sunday and was earlier
reported to have left.
   In reducing the force from 27 to 26 ships, the Vincennes would
have represented the first cutback by the United States since the
Aug. 20 cease-fire in the Iraq-Iran war.
   The military sources, insisting on anonymity, on Monday said the
Vincennes was remaining on station in the Arabian Sea, possibly for
another five days.
   The change of orders was based on diplomatic rather than
military considerations, and ``came from a much higher level than
the Navy in the gulf,'' said one source. That source, speaking on
condition of anonymity, also said the Pentagon decision not to
replace the cruiser still stood.
   U.S. military and diplomatic sources said they could not
identify the Arab state that raised objections to the Vincennes
leaving the region.
   The Vincennes, one of the Navy's powerful ``Aegis'' cruisers, is
winding up a tour that was marred by its mistaken downing of an
Iranian jetliner on July 3, killing all 290 people aboard.
   The Vincennes, which carries a crew of 385, left its home port
at San Diego in late April and entered the gulf on May 27,
conducting air surveillance in the Strait of Hormuz and southern
gulf.
</TEXT>
