<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     09-06 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against most major foreign
currencies in thin early European trading today. Gold prices were
mixed.
   Foreign exchange dealers said they were waiting for American
markets to reopen and provide fresh direction. American financial
institutions were closed Monday for the Labor Day holiday.
   ``The market is likely to remain relatively dead until the U.S.
opens,'' said one trader in Frankfurt, West Germany.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.43 yen to a closing 135.60. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 135.68 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.8532 West German marks, down from 1.8555
   _1.5605 Swiss francs, down from 1.5625
   _6.3045 French francs, down from 6.3124
   _2.0939 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0957
   _1,382.75 Italian lire, up from 1,380.50
   _1.2335 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2338
   In London, the dollar fell more than 1 cent against the British
pound. One pound cost $1.6965 today compared with $1.6860 late
Monday.
   Gold prices were steady in sluggish London trading today.
Bullion dealers said there was little incentive to push the
precious metal one way or the other.
   Gold opened in London at a bid $426.80 a troy ounce, down from
$427.50 bid late Monday. At midmorning today, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $427.65.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $427.70, up slightly from $427.50
bid late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 23 cents to close at a bid
$429.15.
   Silver was unchanged at $6.50 a troy ounce in London.
</TEXT>
