<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Deaths     09-06 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deaths,0287</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Gert Froebe</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   German actor Gert Froebe, a gifted
comic who became famous as the gold-craving criminal in the 1964
James Bond film ``Goldfinger,'' died of a heart attack Monday. He
was 75.
   Described by critics as Germany's version of American Danny
Kaye, Froebe played in nearly 100 films, including roles in the
1961 U.S. production ``The Longest Day,'' and the British-produced
``The Magnificent Men and Their Flying Machines,'' filmed in 1964.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Joseph Swing</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honorary South African Consul Joseph Swing, a
target of weekly anti-apartheid demonstrations for the past four
years, died Sunday. He was 68.
   Swing, a native of Washington, D.C., spent 20 years as a Foreign
Service officer with the State Department, some in South Africa,
and 17 years with the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
   In 1981, he was authorized by the South African ambassador to
open a local office for tourist promotion, visa applications and
work on business deals between U.S. and South African firms. The
unpaid job provided only reimbursement for office expenses.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Sam White</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Australian journalist Sam White, the Paris
correspondent for London's Evening Standard newspaper for more than
40 years, died Sunday in a Paris clinic where he was receiving
treatment for respiratory problems. He was 77.
   During World War II, White reported for Australia's Sydney Daily
Telegraph. He covered in the 1944 invasion of Normandy and entered
Paris with the U.S. Army. After the war, White returned to
Austrialia briefly but soon came back to Europe. He began working
for the Evening Standard in 1947. White continued his weekly column
until shortly before his death.
</TEXT>
