<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 0911EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Burma     09-06 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Ministry Workers Resign From Party En Masse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All 187 Foreign Ministry workers who
belonged to Burma's ruling party resigned from the party and
employees of 16 diplomatic missions have expressed support for the
formation of an interim government, ministry sources said today.
   A statement from ministry employees said the workers decided
Monday to resign from the Burma Socialist Program Party, which
protesters blame for 26 years of repression and ruinous economic
policies.
   Ministry sources said that with the exception of the
ambassadors, employees at 16 of the 26 foreign missions have
supported demands for formation of an interim government to lead
Burma to democracy.
   The statement appealed for support from foreign missions: ``We
have now reached a stage where the government should comply
forthwith with the people's wishes. Any responsible government
would have done so long ago.
   ``Procrastination in any form by the government, either by
resorting to irrelevant legal procedures or by various maneuvers,
tactics, (and) ruses designed to retain the reins of power would
inevitably bring about immense suffering to the people, together
with the ultimate threat of ... strife.''
   ``We must prevent such an outcome at all costs so those
schoolchildren, students and martyrs who have valiantly given up
their lives in this historic struggle would not have died in
vain,'' it said.
   Many government departments have stated opposition to the
government; some have held street demonstrations. This has crippled
President Maung Maung's administration, which faces the threat of
nationwide demonstrations Thursday unless it yields to demands for
an interim government.
   Lawlessness spread to the capital today as looters stripped
three government warehouses. Authorities made no attempt to
intervene.
   Sources said hundreds of people carried away bags of rice from a
warehouse in western Rangoon. In brisk business near the warehouse,
they sold the rice to merchants for 100 kyats, or 17 cents per
165-pound bag _ a quarter of the normal price.
   Nearby, looters took frozen fish, trays and equipment from a
Fisheries Department warehouse and another group stole provisions
and office equipment from a Food and Beverages Corp. warehouse near
Rangoon University.
   Residents of the Rangoon suburb of South Okkalapa earlier
reported at least 20 people died in a clash at a biscuit factory
between looters and members of a neighborhood committee.
   The government says the party leadership will meet Monday to
consider organizing a referendum on one-party rule. Some diplomats
speculate the chaos is being orchestrated to create an excuse for
the party to re-establish itself or for military intervention.
   On Monday, opposition leaders Aung San Suu Kyi and former
Defense Minister Tin Oo threw their support to a demand by one
student group that an interim government be formed by Wednesday
night or protests will follow Thursday.
   Burma's turmoil mounted after students rioted last September to
protest economic policies and then led broader-based street
protests in March and June.
   Street riots flared anew after Ne Win resigned July 23 following
26 years in power and the party chose Sein Lwin to succeed him.
   Government radio said at least 112 people died in Rangoon in
rioting against Sein Lwin, who resigned after 17 days in power.
   Demonstrations have been largely peaceful since Maung Maung took
office Aug. 19 as the first civilian leader in 26 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
