<DOCNO> AP880906-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 0931EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SeattleBlackout     09-06 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Seattle Blackout,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seattle Blackout Ended, Utility Crews Turn to Preventing
Recurrence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With power restored in a 50-block downtown area
after a four-day blackout, crews are checking for wiring similar to
the kind that contributed to the city-owned utility's worst outage.
   The precise cause of the fire that resulted in the outage
Wednesday remained undetermined. Power to all but one building in
the city's retail, financial and hotel core was restored by Sunday
evening.
   Seattle City Light officials attributed the severity of the
blackout to the melting of an aluminum, direct-current supply cable
for overhead electrical trolley bus lines in an underground vault
that also contained six of the utility's 13,000-volt feeder cables.
   During the height of the blackout, officials estimated that 90
percent of all businesses were closed in the area, which included
an estimated 130 restaurants, 55 shops in the popular Pike Place
Market, the Bon Marche department store, the 875-room Westin Hotel
and uncounted other hotels, food stores and taverns.
   City Light officials said they had no estimate of the utility's
losses and the costs of restoring power. There was no cost estimate
available for losses sustained by the utility's customers.
   Scott Forslund, a utility spokesman, said it might be several
days before power is restored to the last building without service,
a parking garage near the vault, because its low-voltage supply
lines were destroyed in the same fire that wrecked the feeder
cables.
   The fire began in low-voltage utility lines between transformers
in the vault and individual buildings, said City Light assistant
superintendent Jerry Garman.
   As the system heated, power to the high-voltage feeder cables
should have been cut by ``current limiters,'' but the transit cable
melted, and its molten aluminum cut the high-voltage cables before
power could be shut off to all but two of them.
   ``When aluminum melts, it's just like adding gasoline'' to a
fire, City Light spokesman Hugh McIntosh said.
   ``It took what would have been a minor inconvenience and turned
it into a major event,'' Garman said. ``It's like we had eight or
nine welding torches going at the same time.''
   City Light crews will check other locations with similar
combinations of utility and Metro cables to try to prevent a
similar outage, Garman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
