<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 0940EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Rocket     09-06 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Rocket,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Launches Experimental Rocket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan today conducted a 62-second test launch of a
rocket that is expected to pave the way for lifting larger payloads
into space, the National Space Development Agency said.
   The 47-foot TR-1 rocket was launched at 8 a.m. from the
Tanegashima Space Center on Tanegashima island in southern Japan,
said agency spokesman Yoshinari Ueda. The rocket dropped into the
sea more than a minute after it was launched. He said the two solid
rocket boosters attached to the rocket's main body were separated
47.7 seconds after the liftoff.
   A part of the rocket that collected flight and technical data
was recovered by a boat about 60 miles south of Tanegashima, Ueda
said.
   The TR-1 test rocket was jointly developed by Nissan Motor
Corp., Kawasaki Heavy Industries Ltd. and NEC Corp. and cost $5.3
million to manufacture and launch, according to Ueda.
   Japan's next generation of rockets, the H-2, will be able to
carry a 2-ton payload and is to be launched in 1991, Ueda said.
Japanese companies now limit rocket payloads to 1,200 pounds.
   Today's experimental launch is one of three Japan plans to
conduct before 1991 to gather further data for the development of
the H-2 rocket, Ueda said.
</TEXT>
