<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1001EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSReport     09-06 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Report,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agency Deleted Criticisms From Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The national Centers for Disease Control deleted
all criticisms of its efforts to fight AIDS among minorities before
making public its report on the subject, The Atlanta Constitution
reported today.
   CDC Director James O. Mason acknowledged that parts of the
analysis were condensed from 16 pages to two pages after they were
reviewed by CDC officials, but the newspaper quoted him as refusing
to say why the agency deleted critical sections of the report. The
newspaper cited government records as its source but did not
elaborate.
   Mason said the CDC has not yet developed an overall strategy to
fight AIDS among blacks and Hispanics, who account for more than 40
percent of the victims of the disease.
   ``If we were to craft a specific, forward-looking game plan, we
would involve them in crafting it,'' he said.
   The CDC paid a private consultant $12,000 for an analysis of its
efforts to fight acquired immune deficiency syndrome among blacks
and Hispanics.
   Among other things, the consultant's report said CDC had no
``cohesive plan of action'' to prevent AIDS among minorities and is
unaware of how much of the money given to local health departments
for minority AIDS programs actually reached minority populations.
   The report also said the agency does not have information about
the ``knowledge, attitudes and behaviors'' of minority populations.
   Mason said the consultant's study was not intended to be used by
the CDC to provide an overall picture of its efforts to prevent and
control AIDS among minorities. He said it was designed to provide
him with information to present at a conference of minority health
workers and to summarize CDC grants to minority AIDS programs.
   Surgeon General C. Everett Koop has said the only way to control
AIDS is by educating high-risk segments of the population. The CDC
estimates that among blacks and Hispanics there are 200,000
infected homosexual and bisexual men, 200,000 infected heterosexual
drug users, 100,000 infected women and 15,000 infected children and
infants.
</TEXT>
