<HEAD>With PM-Wildfires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIMAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire near an aquatic park offering
``five million gallons and tons of fun'' destroyed eight cars and
burned about 10 acres of brush before it was extinguished,
authorities said.
   The fire ignited brush in a section of Los Angeles County's
Bonnelli Park, said county fire Capt. Garry Oversby. It was not
immediately known whether Monday's blaze began in a vehicle or in
the vegetation, he said, but the flames leaped from car to car. No
one was injured.
   ``Raging Waters is 44 acres, five million gallons and tons of
fun for everyone,'' a tape-recorded message at the park, about 25
miles northeast of Los Angeles, proclaimed.
   Unfortunately, the aquatic park's currents couldn't be tapped to
douse the blaze, which broke out less than a mile away in an area
used to handle overflow parking, fire officials said.
   Firefighters had trouble because there were no hydrants in the
parking lot, said County fire Inspector John Lenihan. Water was
rerouted from hydrants outside the lot and the blaze was
extinguished 2{ hours after it was reported. Damage was estimated
at $50,000, he said.
   The park, crowded because of the Labor Day holiday, was not
evacuated, said Kent Lemasters, Raging Waters vice president and
general manager.
  
