<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reagan'sReturn 1stHold-for-ReleaseLd-Writethru a0504
09-06 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan's Return, 1st Hold-for-Release Ld-Writethru, a0504,740</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 3:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Nebraska School `Model for Society'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 9th graf pvs, Later in, to CORRECT 75,000 convention
delegates to 7,500.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   HASTINGS, Neb. (AP)- President Reagan, heading back to the White
House after a three-week California vacation, today saluted a
privately supported communications school in a college that runs on
a balanced budget as ``a model for our society to follow.''
   Dedicating the C.J. and Marie Gray Communications Arts Center at
Hastings College, Reagan said the school's students will be
entering a profession that ``at times does not seem to appreciate
the simpler virtues.''
   In a speech at the dedication of the communications facility,
Reagan said, ``I'm told that Hastings College operates on a
balanced budget.''
   ``And the Gray Center itself has raised all its funds in the
private sector, not looking toward the government for a special leg
up or a free lunch,'' he said. ``That kind of self-reliance is
inspiring and a model for our society to follow.''
   ``It's a philosophy I hope the students who come here to learn
will carry with them when they leave to ply their skills elsewhere
in a profession that at times does not seem to appreciate the
simpler virtues,'' the president said.
   The center was built with the help of a $1 million grant from
former Reagan campaign official Bob Gray. A Hastings native, Gray
is a Washington public relations executive who was director of
communications for Reagan's 1980 campaign for the White House.
   The center is named for Gray's parents, Marie Gray and the late
Garold C.J. Gray. The elder Gray was an electrical engineer and his
wife was a house mother at the college.
   Reagan was also attending a closed fund-raising reception for
Nebraska's appointed Republican Sen. David Karnes at Grand Island,
Neb. Karnes is seeking election against Bob Kerrey, the state's
popular former Democratic governor.
   Later in the day, the president was speaking to about 7,500
delegates at an American Legion convention in Louisville, Ky., on
his way back to Washington for the first time since George Bush was
nominated to succeed him.
   Bush and his Democratic opponent, Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis, will speak to the legionnaires later in the week.
   In the coming weeks, Reagan faces a new round of negotiation
with Congress on the thorny issue of aid to Nicaraguan rebels and a
busy round of campaigning for Bush and other Republican candidates.
   On Wednesday, his first day back at work, the president has
scheduled a meeting with Republican congressional leaders.
   While the agenda has not been announced, the legislative
calendar includes aid to the Contra rebels in Nicaragua, a landmark
free trade agreement with Canada, 11 appropriations bills, welfare
legislation, and confirmation of Reagan's nominations of Nicholas
Brady as secretary of the treasury and Lauro Cavazos as secretary
of education. Also hanging are backlogs of judicial and diplomatic
nominations Reagan hopes to see confirmed before he leaves office
4{ months from now.
   ``Contra aid is certainly one of the issues we have to deal with
right off the bat,'' said White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   The Senate has passed a bill which the administration termed
minimally acceptable and the House, the biggest hurdle for Contra
aid in the past, has not acted.
   When asked whether the administration wanted to change the bill
to include military as well as humanitarian aid, Fitzwater declined
to answer, saying, ``It's to be a negotiated process.''
   Another administration official, speaking on condition he not be
identified, said, ``The only way to get the right kind of Contra
aid is to let Congress do it. The more we come out for things,
sometimes the more it doesn't help the process.''
   In addition to his legislative battles, the president is
expected to make about two political trips a week until the
election, appearing on behalf of Senate and House candidates, but
also pushing for the election of his vice president to succeed him.
   Reagan left Washington on August 14 to speak at the Republican
National Convention in New Orleans. He flew to California on August
16 and has spent the time since at his 688-acre ranch north of here
and in Los Angeles.
   Since taking office in 1981, the president has spent 335 days at
the ranch. He is expected to return for a few days around
Thanksgiving.
   Officials say Reagan may go to the United Nations at the end of
September, as he usually does, but Fitzwater said no foreign travel
is planned before his term ends on Jan. 20.
</TEXT>
