<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iraq-Kurds     09-06 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iraq-Kurds,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Offers Amnesty for Kurdish Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq's ruling Revolutionary Command
Council today announced a ``general and comprehensive'' amnesty for
Kurdish rebels in an apparent effort to counter allegations its
forces are using poison gas against the tribesmen.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, reported
the council said the rebels, whether in Iraq or abroad, had 30 days
to turn themselves in to be pardoned but would then be allowed to
leave the country.
   Those ``who have obligations abroad, such as jobs or attending
school, would be allowed to leave,'' the news agency quoted the
announcement as saying. ``Their exit is guaranteed.''
   Baghdad's move came as Kurdish guerrillas reported fierce
fighting in northeast Iraq where they said 60,000 troops, with
tanks, fighter-bombers and helicopter gunships, were advancing into
the rebel strongholds.
   The rebels are seeking autonomy in their mountainous region,
where about 20 million Kurds live in the area where Syria, Iraq,
Iran and Turkey converge.
   The decree, addressed to ``the glorious Iraqi nation,'' singled
out the Kurds but contained no reference to the Kurds' demand for
an autonomous homeland.
   Iraq's estimated 3.5 million Kurds, about one-fifth of the
country's population, have been fighting on and off for 50 years
for independence.
   However, the Iraqi news agency said the amnesty did not extend
to ``the traitor,'' Jalal Talabani, leader of the Patriotic Union
of Kurdistan, and Massoud Barzani, leader of the Kurdish Democratic
Party.
   Talabani and Barzani joined forces with Iran during the Persian
Gulf war against Iraq. Their organizations have long been outlawed
by Iraq.
   Spokesmen for the two Kurdish parties claim the Iraqis have
repeatedly used outlawed chemical weapons against undefended
villages in recent days, killing at least 1,900 civilians and
wounding 5,000.
   Iraq has dnied using chemical weapons against the Kurds,
although it has admitted using them against Iranian forces during
the eight-year gulf war before fighting stopped when a United
Nations-sponsored cease-fire took effect Aug. 20.
   The Iraqi decree said all Kurdish prisoners would be pardoned
and ``released immediately ... except those convicted or wanted on
other charges.'' The Revolutionary Command Council statement said
the amnesty was based on the Islamic principle of pardoning
wrongdoers and ``giving them a chance to repent, even the most
devious and cursed.''
   Officials in Turkey say about 90,000 Kurds have fled across the
mountainous border since the Iraqi offensive began last last month.
   But Turkey's foreign minister, Mesut Yilmaz, said Monday that
the heavy influx of Kurds fleeing from Iraq has ceased because
Iraqi troops who had been battling the Kurds are blocking mountain
passes to Turkey.
   In Geneva, Iran has asked the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees to provide aid for several thousand Kurdish refugees
fleeing the army offensive in Iraq, a U.N. refugee official said
today.
   Iran says 2,000 Iraqi Kurds streamed across the border into West
Azerbaijan province in recent days, and another 600 families are
heading toward the region, said the U.N. spokeswoman, Judith Kumin.
</TEXT>
