<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Czech-Dubcek     09-06 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Czech-Dubcek,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dubcek To Go Abroad For First Time Since Prague Spring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Communist Party chief
Alxander Dubcek, who led the ``Prague Spring'' reform movement of
1968, is to travel abroad for the first time in 18 years to visit
Italy, a government spokesman said today.
   He said Dubcek was issued a visa to go to Italy, where the
University of Bologna is to award him an honorary degree in
political science on Nov. 12 for ``his role in defending democratic
principles and personal liberties.''
   Dubcek, 66, a retired forestry worker, was ousted after the 1968
Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia and was expelled from the
Communist Party in 1970. He has not traveled abroad since then.
   Government spokesman Dusan Rovensky told The Associated Press
that Dubcek applied for a visa for himself and his wife Maria on
July 25 and the permit was issued three weeks later.
   When he did not pick up the documents, Dubcek was asked to do so
in a written Aug. 25 message from the authorities, Rovensky said.
He said Dubcek's wife came to pick up the travel papers Monday. The
Dubceks live in Bratislava, capital of the eastern region of
Slovakia.
   The party's monthly Novy Mysl said last month that the former
Communist leader and his followers were responsible for the
``crisis'' of August 1968, when the country was ``on the brink of
civil war.''
   On Aug. 20-21, 1968, Soviet and Warsaw Pact tanks moved into
Czechoslovakia to crush the liberal reforms introduced by Dubcek in
what is known as the ``Prague Spring.''
   Dubcek has in recent months given interviews to Western news
media in which he called for his own rehabilitation and for the
implementation in Czechoslovakia of reforms similar to those
supported by Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
