<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel     09-06 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Troops Isolate Occupied West Bank Town, Set Up Makeshift
Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops isolated an occupied West Bank
town today, setting up makeshift army bases, cutting telephone
lines and arresting dozens of Palestinians suspected of inciting
riots, the army and Arab witnesses said.
   During today's operation in Qalqilya, 55 miles north of
Jerusalem, troops discovered stashes of knives, hatchets, clubs,
and underground leaflets outlawed by Israeli authorities, an army
spokesman said.
   Jewish settlers have claimed Palestinians from Qalqilya are key
instigators of firebomb and stone-throwing attacks and complained
they scattered nails on West Bank roads.
   An army spokesman said troops today imposed a pre-dawn curfew
and closed all roads to the town of about 10,000 because the army
planned to carry out an ``operation of several stages.'' He
declined to elaborate.
   In all, five West Bank towns and refugee camps were under curfew
today, confining some 40,000 people to their homes.
   Arab taxi drivers turned back at army roadblocks reported seeing
four helicopters flying overhead and dozens of army vehicles, some
pulling mobile homes that were apparently being used as makeshift
army bases.
   They said troops knocked down a wall separating a playground and
high school and were pitching tents on the grounds.
   Police conducted an overnight arrest campaign in Arab east
Jerusalem, taking 13 Arabs into custody, a spokesman said.
   Security forces also arrested four West Bank Palestinians Monday
night, including two journalists who work for pro-PLO newspapers.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres began the Labor Party's election
campaign with a vow to return occupied territory in exchange for
peace. He said such a move would assure a stronger Israel with a
clear Jewish majority.
   ``We shall rid ourselves of Gaza, we shall rid ourselves of
areas densely populated by Arabs,'' Peres told 3,000 supporters
Monday night in Tel Aviv. ``We shall remain many Jews on much land,
not a Jewish minority with an impossible burden of territories.''
   Peres also called on Palestinians to end the Arab uprising and
start peace talks with Israel.
   Since the uprising began Dec. 8 in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
258 Palestinians have been killed. Four Israelis have died. The
territories were occupied by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war.
   The army, meanwhile, issued orders barring troops from hurling
tear gas into enclosed spaces following an Israeli medical
investigation last May showing the practice endangers human lives.
   The new policy followed charges from Palestinian and
international human rights groups that the gas was being improperly
thrown into closed quarters despite manufacturers specifications
that it be used only in open spaces.
   In a report last month, the London-based human rights group,
Amnesty International said at least seven Palestinians had died as
a result of the improper use of tear gas. The United Nations puts
the number of deaths from tear gassing at 13 since the uprising
began Dec. 8.
   An American tear gas manufacturer, TransTechnology Corp. of
Sherman Oaks, Calif., in May suspended its sale of the riot-control
substance to Israel.
   The army has denied any Palestinians died as a result of tear
gas, contending Amnesty International consulted biased sources.
</TEXT>
