<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HighwaySniper     09-06 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Highway Sniper,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High-Rise Sniper Shoots At Cops, Injures 3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sniper fired ``a rain of pellets'' from a
high-rise apartment building today, slightly injuring three police
officers and closing a busy Manhattan highway, authorities said.
   Police said they had pinpointed an 11th-floor apartment as the
source of the shots and sent hostage negotiators to talk to a
disgruntled tenant, but the man did not respond.
   Deputy Inspector James Fogerty said the man apparently had a
complaint against the building management.
   The incident began about 6 a.m. when police responded to reports
of shots being fired in the vicinity of the building. The officers
stationed themselves along the FDR Drive beside the East River near
the Brooklyn Bridge.
   Police did not describe the type of weapon used, but First
Deputy Commissioner Richard Condon said ``a rain of pellets'' fell
on the officers.
   Scores of emergency service officers, highway and patrol
officers rushed to the scene, cordoning off a four-block area.
   The busy FDR Drive, a main conduit into Manhattan from Brooklyn,
Queens and the Bronx, was closed in both directions in the area.
   Three pellets superficially wounded three officers. A fourth
struck an officer but did not pierce his skin.
   Fogerty described the man only as being Asian and said he
believes he has two children. Police called for an interpreter who
speaks Mandarin Chinese.
   Fogerty said the man refused to open his door, but police could
hear voices inside the apartment. Police also tried to call the man
but believe his phone may have been disconnected.
   Officers lowered a video camera from the 12th floor to look into
the apartment's windows. Authorities said they could see no people
but spotted furniture barricading the front door.
   Victoria Parker, who lives on the building's 18th floor, said
the man believed to be firig the shots recently moved in and had a
reputation for having a bad temper. ``He gets into it with
management and the tenants,'' she said.
</TEXT>
