<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis 3rdLd-Writethru a0528 09-06 0906</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0528,910</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Bush Out Of Touch With Average Americans</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with more on demonstation, inserting 4 grafs after
9th graf pvs, Supporters of</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis today criticized George Bush for
saying U.S. auto plants could use the abilities of Soviet
mechanics, and he accused the Reagan administration of ``trying to
break unions and pit management against labor.''
   Last fall on a trip to Europe, Bush said he'd been told in a
meeting of NATO ministers that 350 Soviet tanks had recently
completed maneuvers without a breakdown.
   ``Hey, when the mechanics who keep those tanks running run out
of work in the Soviet Union, send them to Detroit because we could
use that kind of ability,'' Bush said at the time. Later, he
apologized to U.S. autoworkers, adding, ``Hey give me a break; I
didn't mean anything by it.''
   Dukakis, in a meeting today with hundreds of Polish-Americans
and others at a banquet hall outside Chicago, praised the Polish
workers' union Solidarity while taking aim at Reagan administration
labor policies.
   ``They don't understand that Solidarity isn't just a beautiful
word in Polish; it's also a beautiful word in English,'' Dukakis
said. ``That's why they've spent the last seven years trying to
break unions and pit management againstqbor.''
   The Democratic nominee chided Bush for the vice president's
remarks about Soviet mechanics.
   ``I agree we have to pay attention to quality _ from the
assembly lines to the executive suites,'' Dukakis said. ``But do
you really believe we in America have anything to learn from a
society where workers have no rights, consumers have no choices and
even Mr. Gorbachev admits their economy is a shambles? Those
Republicans in Washington love to blame American workers first.''
   Dukakis' speech was interrupted for about 15 minutes by
demonstrators, who shouted, ``What about abortion?'' and ``Abortion
is murder.''
   Supporters of the candidate chanted back, ``We want Mike.''
Several of the demonstrators were removed from the room by people
in the crowd, and Dukakis proceeded with his remarks. His position
on abortion is that he is personally opposed to it but believes a
pregnant woman has the right to make her own decision.
   There was scuffling, but police said there were no arrests.
   One of the demonstrators, Richard Freeman, said several
anti-abortion groups met a week ago and decided to organize
protests. ``If Dukakis is within 300 miles of a pro-life activist,
we're going to go out and greet him,'' he said.
   As Freeman spoke to reporters he was jostled by other people in
the crowd, one of whom ripped his jacket.
   One spectator obviously upset by the demonstators, Marion Reis,
said he opposes abortion and has donated money to pro-life groups.
He said he would make no further donations, adding, ``I think
they're full of hate, not full of love.''
   Dukakis was also to meet in Illinois today with state Democratic
leaders, but Jesse Jackson was not included.
   Jackson was very upset over the omission, the latest in a series
of what he has perceived as slights by the Dukakis campaign, said a
source close to the former presidential candidate.
   Another confidant said Jackson has expressed concern about his
contacts with the Dukakis campaign, and ``whether or not he's going
to be able to do what he could and should do for the ticket.''
   Both sources spoke on condition they not be identified by name.
   In Illinois, Dukakis' state press secretary Judy Erwin said
Jackson was not included in the meetings because he is regarded as
a national leader and today's meetings were to focus on the
Illinois state campaign.
   Dukakis' remarks today about Bush marked a continuation of the
effort Dukakis has made in the past week to portray his Republican
rival as out of touch with average Americans.
   From Illinois Dukakis was heading to another key industrial
state, Ohio, after marking the traditional Labor Day kickoff of the
fall campaign Monday with appearances in Pennsylvania, Michigan and
Missouri.
   While Dukakis campaigned, his top campaign aides were to resume
discussions with the Bush camp on a fall debate schedule.
   After an appearance in St. Louis on Monday, Dukakis sized up the
final nine weeks of his contest with Bush as a ``tough, competitive
race'' he believes will swing on which candidate that low- and
moderate-income Americans believe is most qualified to direct the
nation's economy.
   Dukakis said he hoped to keep the focus on substantive issues
but said it has become clear in recent weeks that Republicans are
more intent on attacking him personally.
   ``If they want a tough, aggressive campaign, I'm happy to give
it to them,'' Dukakis said. ``The signs are good and we're raring
to go.''
   At all of his Monday stops and again today Dukakis criticized
Bush for calling last month's rise in national unemployment
``statistically irrelevant,'' portraying the vice president as the
standard bearer of the rich and insensitive to the needs of working
Americans.
   ``I don't think he really understands average Americans very
well,'' Dukakis said in a meeting with local reporters in St.
Louis. ``I don't think he really understands what average families
are going through these days.''
   The Massachusetts governor, repeatedly invoking the theme
``bring prosperity home,'' said the Reagan-Bush legacy will leave
families working harder than eight years ago to pay their bills,
with millions unable to afford new homes or college educations for
their children.
</TEXT>
