<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru,, a0478,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadian Air Mass Chills Parts of Plains, Northeast</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to update with record lows, heavy Fla.
rain, picking up at the 7th graf previous, beginning ``Today's
forecast.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures dipped to record lows at nearly 30 cities today
from the Plains to New England and as far south as Arkansas when
Canadian air surged southward, and heavy rain caused flooding in
parts of northern Florida.
   Temperatures dipped into the 40s as far south as Tennessee and a
few spots in Minnesota and North Dakota reported lows at freezing
or lower with a reading of 31 degrees at Hibbing, Minn.
Indianapolis tied its coldest temperature for so early in the fall
at 44 degrees, a record that has stood since 1885.
   Most of the record lows were in the 40s, with some in the 50s in
Tennessee and Arkansas, but records were in the 30s in parts of
Missouri, Iowa, Minnesota, Wisconsin and upstate New York.
   High wind and almost 6 inches swept much of Florida for the
second day today, flooding streets and highways, knocking out
power, blowing down trees and threatening some low-lying coastal
areas with erosion.
   Gainesville reported 5.83 inches of rain in a 24-hour period
ending at 8 a.m., and the National Weather Service said nearly 4
inches of that fell in the last six hours of the reporting period.
   Minor flooding was reported throughout west-central Florida, and
above-normal tides and minor coastal erosion were expected from
Cedar Key to Venice, the weather service said.
   Wind gusts to 40 mph were reported at Tampa International
Airport, and the weather service said gusts of more than 60 mph had
been reported but not confirmed.
   Savannah, Ga., and Charleston, S.C., received just over
two-thirds of an inch of rain in the six hours ended at 2 a.m. EDT.
   The sky remained smoky over Wyoming, southern Montana and Idaho
because of forest fires, reducing visibility to as little as 3
miles in some locations Monday.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms over
southern Georgia and the Florida peninsula, and scattered showers
along the coasts of North Carolina and Washington state. Mostly
sunny skies were predicted for most other regions.
   Highs were forecast to be in the 50s in northern Maine; in the
60s from northern New England to the Great Lakes, the Ohio Valley
and the upper Mississippi Valley, and along the Northwest coast; in
the 90s in central and northwest Texas, the central and southern
Plateau, parts of Colorado, western Wyoming, central Montana and
southern Florida; and between 100 and 110 degrees in the desert
Southwest and inland California valleys. Highs elsewhere were
expected to be in the 70s and 80s.
   At 3 a.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 35 degrees at Hibbing,
Minn., to 87 at Yuma, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 61 fair; Boston 55 fair; Buffalo 46 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 69 cloudy; Cincinnati 48 fair; Cleveland 50 partly
cloudy; Detroit 47 fair; Miami 83 partly cloudy; New York 56 fair;
Philadelphia 54 fair; Pittsburgh 45 fair; Portland, Maine 47 fair;
Washington 61 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 48 fair; Chicago 50 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
66 fair; Denver 55 fair; Des Moines 49 fair; Indianapolis 46 fair;
Kansas City 51 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 49 fair; Nashville 56
fair; New Orleans 73 fair; St. Louis 54 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 62 fair; Anchorage 50 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 83 fair; Los Angeles 69 fair; Phoenix 86 fair; San Diego 74
fair; San Francisco 56 fair; Seattle 59 foggy.
   _Canada: Montreal 45 fair; Toronto 41 fair.
</TEXT>
