<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Trial     09-06 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Trial,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Leader Finally Gets To Testify In Treason Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent black union leader
accused of leading an attempted political takeover of a black
township took the witness stand Tuesday for the first time in his
year-old treason trial.
   Moses Mayekiso, head of the country's largest metalworkers
union, and four co-defendants are charged with seeking to usurp
state authority and install their anti-apartheid civic group as an
alternative government in Alexandra.
   The 39-year-old activist, whose release has been demanded by
many international labor groups, testified about his impoverished
childhood and experiences as an illegal migrant worker after he
moved to the Johannesburg area in the early 1970s.
   ``White people lived in civilized places, but next door in
Alexandra, black people lived in a place where pigs would live,''
said Mayekiso, who will continue his testimony Wednesday.
   Once a squalid slum wedged amidst white Johannesburg suburbs,
Alexandra has been upgraded extensively by the government since
Mayekiso's arrest in June 1986.
   The trial has attracted international attention because of
Mayekiso's position as general secretary of the National Union of
Metalworkers of South Africa and because many activists view the
prosecution as an attempt to stifle legitimate, peaceful opposition
activity.
   The government alleges that the defendants organized rent and
consumer boycotts, sought to undermine the security forces, and
established ``people's courts'' in 1985-86, the height of
nationwide black unrest.
   Alexandra was one of the most militant black townships at the
time, and dozens of people were killed in clashes with security
forces.
   In the past two years, the government has sought to restore
control by detaining or restricting leaders of Mayekiso's Alexandra
Action Committee while undertaking a $45 million redevlopment
program in which sewage, electricity and paved streets are being
provided to most of the 100,000 residents.
   Many of the state witnesses who testified during the early
stages of the treason trial were businessmen who said they suffered
from boycotts enforced by the action committee.
   Under cross-examination, some of these witnesses said the local
crime rate dropped when young supporters of the action committee
began an anti-crime campaign.
   Another highly publicized court case reaches a critical stage
Wednesday when lawyers for the Sharpeville Six appear before the
Appeal Court to challenge the dismissal of a motion to reopen the
murder trial of their black clients.
   The five men and one woman have been sentenced to hang for their
roles in the 1984 mob killing of a black town councilor. There have
been an extensive worldwide campaign appealing to President P.W.
Botha to grant clemency.
   In June, a lower court judge rejected a defense motion to reopen
the trial to consider new evidence.
   At Wednesday's hearing in Bloemfontein, the defense lawyers will
be asking the Appeal Court _ South Africa's highest court _ to
allow a full appeal of the judge's decision.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
