<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthKorea     09-06 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissidents Demand Release Of Political Prisoners Before Olympics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident groups called Tuesday for
the release of about 700 political prisoners before the Olympics
and charged the Games were being used to enforce dictatorial rule.
   The 16 groups issued an appeal to the ``peace lovers'' of the
161 nations taking part in the Olympics to help obtain the release
of all political prisoners before the Games begin Sept. 17.
   Kim Kun-tae, a top dissident, told a news conference attended by
80 other dissidents that the Olympics are being used to cement
military rule. He charged the Games will be a mockery if any
political prisoners remain behind bars.
   ``The Seoul Olympics ... is not an event to pursue global peace
but to forcibly reinforce the dictatorship and legitimize
violence,'' the groups said in a joint statement.
   The South Korean government says all political prisoners have
been released except for dissidents convicted of violent crimes or
communism. Hundreds of political prisoners were freed over the past
year.
   Kim, who was released from prison in June, said 370 people are
serving sentences for opposing the government and more than 300
others are awaiting trial on political charges.
   The government says there about 250 dissidents serving criminal
sentences or awaiting trial on such charges.
   The dissidents also denounced communist North Korea's exclusion
from the Olympics and called for reunification of the divided
Korean peninsula. They said the Games were being used to make the
division permanent.
   North Korea has said it will boycott the Olympics because its
demand to co-host the Games was turned down. The International
Olympic Committee said the Games are awarded to a single city and
could not be shared.
   The dissidents also charged the Olympics were being staged by
the government of President Roh Tae-woo to enhance its prestige and
cement authoritarian rule.
   ``The dehumanizing torture and terror will not cease and at this
very moment, under the euphemism of `peace during the Olympics,'
more people will be arrested,'' the groups said in a statement.
   They urged other nations to help them fight the government.
   ``We ask for your full-fledged support in our difficult fight
for national sovereignty, democracy and reunification and
resistance to Roh's military dictatorial regime,'' the statement
said.
   The dissidents also demanded withdrawal of the 42,000 U.S.
troops based in South Korea under a mutual defense treaty.
   Roh, a former general who won presidential elections in
Decmeber, has introduced broad democratic reforms and dismantled
authoritarian controls imposed by former President Chun Doo-hwan.
   Dissident groups contend the government is a front for continued
authoritarian rule by the military and there has been no democratic
progress. The dissidents and radical anti-government students have
little or no public support and Roh's popularity has been growing.
   Most Koreans want the Olympics to be a major success. The Games
are seen as a way to propel the nation into the forefront of newly
developed nations and continue its rapid industrial development.
   In another development, South Korea has temporarily halted
foreign adoption of its babies to avoid possible controversy during
the Olympics.
   The government has not officially confirmed the ban, but
adoption agencies acknowledged they were asked to stop sending
babies overseas for adoption for two months before and during the
Olympics. South Korea sends about 7,000 children abroad annually
for adoption in the United States and Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
