<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1346EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Carlucci     09-06 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Carlucci,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Wants To Launch American Satellites Aboard Its Rockets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese officials on Tuesday asked Defense
Secretary Frank C. Carlucci to press the Reagan administration to
allow American satellites to be shipped to China and launched into
space aboard its missiles.
   Carlucci, who is visiting China for the first time, met for more
than three hours Tuesday with National Defense Minister Qin Jiwei.
He also held talks with other officials, including Premier Li Peng
and Vice Premier Wu Xueqian.
   A Senior Defense Department official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said Carlucci also discussed U.S. concerns over Chinese
arms sales to nations in the Middle East _ a sore point in
Sino-American relations.
   The Reagan Administration is considering whether to grant
licenses to export U.S.-made satellites to China, where they would
be launched aboard the so-called Long March boosters.
   Two companies have applied for such export licenses _ Hughes
Aircraft Co. and Asiasat, a Hong Kong-based company that purchased
Hughes satellites, according to Don O'Neal, director of
communications for the Hughes Space and Communications Group, based
in El Secundo, Calif.
   ``There are rumors (the launches from China) may be as much as
50 percent cheaper'' than the French or American shuttle programs,
O'Neal said on Tuesday. He said he could not speculate on the exact
costs of Chinese launches.
   The U.S. shuttle program was sidelined by the explosion aboard
the Challenger in Jan. 28, 1986 in which all seven people aboard
were killed.
   O'Neal said Hughes is applying for a licence for two of
telecommunications satellites bought by the Australian company
Aussat. He said the satellites are owned by Hughes until they are
launched under a ``delivery in orbit'' contract with the Australian
company, which has chosen China as the launch site.
   Hughes has received no response to its license application,
which was made in July, according to O'Neal.
   Asiasat owns a Hughes-made Westar 6 satellite that was launched
by the U.S. shuttle in 1984 but failed to reach its proper orbit.
It was recovered by the shuttle in 1985, O'Neal said, will be
refurbished in the United States. Asiasat must have a U.S. license
to export it to China so it can be launched again.
   The State Department recommended the licenses be approved, but
the Commerce Department and some Republican congressmen say
allowing China to launch U.S. satellites will undercut U.S.
companies developing the same service.
   On the arms issue, the United States has strongly urged China to
curtail sales of Silkworm anti-ship missiles to Iran and voiced
concern over the recent sale of ballistic missiles to Saudi Arabia.
China denied selling arms to Iran.
   Deputy Chief of Staff Xu Xin told reporters Tuesday that China
has not sold its M-9 medium range missiles to Syria, as reported by
foreign news agencies.
   On Wednesday, Carlucci is to meet with senior Chinese leader
Deng Xiaoping.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
