<HEAD>Man Threatening Suicide Ties Up Rush-Hour Traffic</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with police saying they pushed man off
overpass, other details. Also removes BRF designation. No Pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man threatening to commit suicide by
jumping from an overpass over the busy Hollywood Freeway tied up
rush-hour traffic today for 90 minutes before he was pushed off
onto an airbag, authorities said.
   Clarence Hunter, believed to be in his 50s, began threatening to
jump from the Alameda Street overpass about 4:20 a.m., according to
California Highway Patrol Officer Dwight McDonald.
   Police pushed Hunter off the overpass after he began moving back
and forth on the bridge, police Lt. Les Lutz said. ``He was
becoming less communicative and was making more threats to jump.''
   While police awaited their crisis negotiator, the Fire
Department inflated an air bag and moved it into place on the
southbound lanes of the freeway. When Hunter then threatened to set
his shirt on fire, officers pushed him off the bridge, Lutz said.
   ``We assisted him. We pushed him out the bridge onto the airbag
to prevent him from setting his shirt on fire. He was not
injured,'' Lutz said.
   Hunter was taken to Los Angeles County-USC Medical Center for
observation.
   The incident created a huge traffic jam during the morning rush
hour, backing up the freeway in both directions until about 6:20
a.m., McDonald said.
   A check of Hunter's background revealed he had attempted to jump
from a Glendale Freeway overpass last month, Lutz said.
   Glendale police Sgt. Bill Fishback said Hunter was on the Holly
Drive overpass for 2{ hours Aug. 24 before being rescued.
</TEXT>
