<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Sunia     09-06 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sunia,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Samoan Delegate Resigns From House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fofo I.F. Sunia, the non-voting delegate from
American Samoa, officially resigned from the House on Tuesday a
month after his guilty plea in a payroll padding scheme.
   The resignation of Sunia, a four-term Democrat, came a day
before the House ethics committee planned to hold a disciplinary
hearing against him and a staff accomplice, former administrative
assistant Matthew Iuli.
   The resignation ended the ethics panel's jurisdiction over
Sunia, since it can only discipline current members and employees
of the House.
   Sunia and Iuli admitted in U.S. district court Aug. 3 that they
ran a scheme to defraud the government of more than $130,000. Iuli
resigned last week.
   The two men pleaded guilty to placing 14 ghost employees on
Sunia's congressional payroll between 1983 and 1986.
   Federal investigators found that the ``employees''' payroll
checks were deposited into Iuli's bank account or Sunia's
re-election fund.
   The U.S. attorney's office said Sunia and Iuli used the money to
entertain constituents, pay election and campaign expenses and make
house and car loan payments.
   Sentencing is scheduled for Oct. 4. The maximum penalty for each
man is five years in prison and a $250,000 fine.
   Gov. A.P. Lutali of American Samoa has said that candidates'
names will appear on the November ballot twice, once to fill
Sunia's unexpired term and a second time for a full two-year term
in the 101st Congress that begins in January.
</TEXT>
