<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Morningside     09-06 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Morningside,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Relic Of 1968 Campus Violence Finally To Be Rehabilitated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 20 years after Columbia University
began building a gymnasium, a project abandoned after violent
demonstrations rocked the campus in 1968, the empty foundation hole
will be turned into a park pond.
   Stopping construction of the gym was one of the aims of the
uprising, in which university buildings were taken over by campus
radicals who called the project racist. Others complained it took
away part of Morningside Park.
   New York City's Parks Department plans to put $12 million into
rehabilitating the park in the next 10 years. Columbia is
contributing $500,000 to the project, said spokesman Fred Knubel.
   The now-overgrown hole will become a pond, said Parks
Commissioner Henry Stern.
   While opposition to the Vietnam War and mistrust of institutions
in general also fueled the campus revolt, protesters called the gym
a perfect example of racism practiced by white, elite Columbia
against its neighbors in poor, black Harlem.
   Columbia designed the $12 million gym to be shared with the
black community, saying it would not only provide recreation but
also bring law-abiding residents back to a park taken over by
muggers.
   The protesters, however, harped on the two entrances planned for
the gym _ one for students on the Morningside Heights campus atop
the park's scarp, the other for the community at the building's
base in the valley below.
   Columbia's argument that the lower entrance would spare users a
long, steep climb through the park was largely overwhelmed by the
symbolism of upper and lower entrances.
   Other opposition came from conservationists, who objected to the
gym taking away two acres in the central section of the 31-acre
park.
   The issue of whether it is safe to use the park remains. Another
institution bordering Morningside, the Cathedral of St. John the
Divine, organized a ``reclaim-the-park'' program Saturday. It
consisted of a march and music and art programs to get people back
into the park and ``push the pushers out.''
   Stern called it a good idea, but said the park was lightly used
because ``mostly it's a slope and it needs rehabilitation.''
   He said ball fields in the flat areas would be fixed up, new
lighting installed and a new path cut with ``shorter steps that
will make it easier, simpler and safer to go up and across the
park.''
</TEXT>
