<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No, Lisa Pupo doesn't need a husband, a
boyfriend or even a date. But more than 56,800 football fans may
think so.
   At Sunday afternoon's National Football League game between the
Dallas Cowboys and the Pittsburgh Steelers, an airplane flew over
Three Rivers Stadium with a banner reading, ``LISA PUPO _ 30 _
SINGLE.'' The banner included Miss Pupo's home telephone number.
   ``It was a prank, and a pretty smooth one, by my law partners,''
Miss Pupo said later.
   She said partners Mike Burns and David White ``were so nice''
last week in offering her the law firm's tickets to the season
opener. So she invited her parents and two friends, including her
boyfriend, Pat Lenihas.
   ``I must have gotten 200 phone calls. I got calls even before
the game was over,'' she said.
   ``I highly recommend it for someone who really is looking for a
date,'' she said. ``I got marriage proposals, a couple of perverted
calls, a lot of pretty sincere callers and even a woman who wanted
to know why I would do such a thing.''
   She promised to retaliate against her partners. She told The
Pittsburgh Press that Burns, for example, ``is very good looking
and real rich.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSFIELD, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ruth Schoonover's birthday had its ups
and downs.
   The parachutist from Orono celebrated her 30th on Monday with 30
jumps from a plane.
   Alternately jumping, re-rigging, and taking off to jump again,
Schoonover spent the afternoon and early evening performing the
feat at the Pittsfield airport.
   At one point in the day she reached a turnaround rate of eight
jumps an hour, dropping about 3,000 feet at a time.
   On her final approach, she said, ``After this one, I'll really
be 30.''
