<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0436,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede LOS ANGELES</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Tries to Overcome Dukakis Edge in Key States</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOP 13 grafs new with Bush's comments to jeering shipyard
workers; picks up 2nd graf pvs, `The Republican.' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential nominee George Bush
told a group of jeering shipyard workers today that ``the Democrats
are trying to mislead you'' and promised that if he is elected he
would provide more jobs for Americans.
   ``Listen to this one now,'' Bush told a group of about 250
workers who booed loudly as the vice president spoke at an iron
works. ``I know the truth sometimes hurts.''
   The crowd chanted, ``Union Buster,'' but Bush contined to speak
in a loud voice, telling the workers, ``The Democrats are trying to
mislead you. Things aren't going to get worse unless they get
elected.''
   It was the most hostile audience the GOP nominee has encountered
since winning the nomination last month. Bush conceded that Oregon
is a state where he is trailing Democratic rival Michael Dukakis.
   Speaking with reporters aboard Air Force II en route from Los
Angeles, Bush accused Dukakis of waging a negative campaign.
   ``He has to tear down. He has to make everything negative to be
elected. I don't have to be responding to him,'' the vice president
said.
   At the Northwest Marine shipyard, Bush toured a Navy oil
refueling boat and then spoke to a group of iron workers alongside
the ship, stressing the jobs theme and his claim that the Reagan
administration has helped to create more than 17 million new jobs
   Many of the hard-hat workers carried anti-Bush signs that
accused him of being anti-union, including one that said, ``Union
Busting, Scab-Loving Bush.''
   Although Bush was booed and hooted during his speech, he did win
a few cheers from the audience when he told the group, ``I'm proud
to be part of an administration ... that decided we're not going to
wear the `kick me' signs anymore.''
   Bush said he thought the election was going to be ``a referendum
on the direction of America's future'' and said that his single
most important goal was ``that everybody who wants a job should
have a job ... a good job at good wages, he (Dukakis) may talk
about it but we delivered it.''
   He was to tour another plant in Everett, Wash.
   On a related matter, a Bush spokeswoman said campaign chairmen
for the two presidential candidates spoke this morning by telephone
and made ``some progress'' on a debate schedule.
   Alixe Glen said Dukakis campaign chairman Paul Brountas and Bush
chairman James Baker III will resume negotiations by phone on
Wednesday on dates and a format for the presidential debates.
   The Republican presidential nominee, at a Labor Day waterfront
rally in San Diego, accused Dukakis of a ``negative ideology
against weapons.''
   And, he said at the Navy base town, ``I wouldn't be surprised if
he thinks a naval exercise is something you find in `The Jane Fonda
Workout Book.'''
   Bush told the San Diego audience that the two central issues of
the campaign were ``jobs and peace ... and how to make new
breakthroughs in both areas.''
   Recent public opinion polls suggest Bush is three to seven
points behind Dukakis in California, which has 47 electoral votes.
Dukakis is also viewed as stronger in Oregon, and, to a lesser
degree, in Washington.
   Bush aides say polling done by the campaign is becoming
increasingly pivotal in determining the vice president's campaign
schedule.
   Many surveys suggest that the race, nationwide, is close to a
dead heat.
</TEXT>
