<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1440EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Prostitutes-Warehouse     09-06 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prostitutes-Warehouse,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salt-Filled Warehouse Has Become Haven for Homeless Boys, Paper
Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city will clear out homeless youths living
in a rat-infested salt warehouse and try to direct them to more
appropriate facilities, a Sanitation Department official said
Tuesday.
   ``We have had problems in the past keeping both homeless and
runaways from our facilities,'' said Vito Turso, chief spokesman
for the Sanitation Department. ``We chase them out. They come back.
We chase them out again. They come back again.''
   Turso's remarks came after the New York Post reported Tuesday
that dozens of homeless boys, some of whom work as prostitutes,
lived in the salt-filled warehouse and in an adjacent row of
broken-down garbage trucks in Manhattan.
   This time, Turso said, sanitation workers will be issued cards
with the telephone number of a runaway hot line to hand out. ``I
guess the answer to the problem is not to keep chasing them out to
nowhere but to chase them out to somewhere they can get help,'' he
said.
   Atop a garbage-strewn mountain of salt, which is used on city
streets in the winter, is a shantytown of mattresses and crates,
where the boys cook, eat, sleep and play, the Post said.
   The newspaper said some youths stay for weeks or months. Turso
maintained that the Sanitation Department chases away the youths
and clears out their mattresses whenever a new load of salt is
delivered, most recently three weeks ago.
   The newspaper reported that the youths walked in and out of the
rat-infested warehouse in plain view of sanitation workers. Said
Turso: ``The sanitation workers' job at that location is to report
and then to go out on assignment. It's not to be a security
officer.''
   Asked about the Department's police force, he said it did not
have patrols regularly assigned to the warehouse. But on the basis
of the report, Turso said, ``We've asked the supervisor to take a
look ... to see if there are people there and to encourage them to
leave.''
   Outreach groups estimate that 20,000 young people roam the
streets every year, and 80 percent to 90 percent of them live by
prostitution, the paper said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
