<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RareBat     09-06 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rare Bat,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mastiff Bat Returns to Wild, But Newborn Bat Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORAL GABLES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rare Florida mastiff bat, the first
one seen in the state in a decade, was found near death on an
office balcony but has recovered and escaped to the wild, a
biologist said.
   Wildlife biologist Frank Mazzotti said, however, the offspring
the round-eared brown bat bore on Labor Day died at birth.
   ``I don't think the death of the (baby bat) changes the
significance of what has happened,'' Mazzotti said. ``Not only is
the bat still in south Florida, but you have a reproductive
population.''
   Mazzotti and fellow bat hunter Mark Robson had been scouring
Florida since June trying to determine if the species still
survived in the state. They had alerted residents to watch out for
the bat.
   On Aug. 30, the bat was found by an office worker on the
tenth-floor balcony of the Turbana Corp. headquarters here.
   The worker took it inside and gave it the nickname of P.L.,
which she declined to explain. She called a veterinarian, who took
the bat.
   A routine X-ray Friday found the bat was pregnant. The bat was
in shock and dehydrated, her blood sugar and body temperature
extremely low.
   P.L. gave birth to a stillborn baby bat at the home of the
veterinarian who was nursing her back to health, Mazzotti said.
   The previously silent P.L. _ who was scheduled to be released
Monday _ became vocal and active after the birth, and soon wiggled
out of her cage to freedom.
   ``We can only hope she's OK out there somewhere,'' Robson said.
</TEXT>
