<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1512EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HomesickPanda     09-06 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homesick Panda,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zoo Closes Exhibit To Help Homesick Panda</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cincinnati Zoo officials are giving giant
panda Chia Chia five days off to see if he can overcome what they
believe is homesickness.
   Chia Chia went on display Friday at the start of a three-month
stopover on his move from the London Zoo to Mexico City. But the
zoo administrators closed the exhibit the same day because the
panda was staying in his den and acting strangely.
   ``At first, we thought it was jet lag, but it's taken much
longer than we expected,'' said Jo Gipps, curator of mammals with
the London Zoo, who traveled with Chia Chia. ``Homesick is exactly
the word for what's wrong.''
   Since Friday, the 290-pound panda has emerged periodically from
his den to eat bamboo for a few minutes, then quickly retreated
from public view. When keepers tried to lock the doors to his den
to keep him in view, the panda became agitated, pacing rapidly and
bumping the walls.
   ``He's normally quite extroverted. That's why we're concerned,''
said Neil Bemment, the panda's keeper.
   ``Animals are unpredictable. We're not going to push him,'' said
Edward Maruska, executive director of the Cincinnati Zoo. He and
officials from the London Zoo decided Chia Chia needed time alone
in his new surroundings.
   Zoo officials will meet Thursday to decide if the exhibit can
reopen Friday.
   Zookeepers built a platform for the panda Monday to make him
feel like he is at his old London Zoo home, Cincinnati Zoo
spokeswoman Barbara Brady said.
   ``He's getting better. He's looking a little better _ just a
little lonely,'' Ms. Brady said Tuesday.
   The delay means about 3,400 people with tickets to see Chia Chia
this week will have to exchange their tickets or get refunds.
Through Sunday afternoon, 81,000 people had bought tickets to see
the panda before he leaves Nov. 30.
   The 16-year-old panda, captured in China at the age of 2,
arrived in Cincinnati on Friday after a seven-hour road trip from
Chicago, following a 10-hour flight from London.
   Chia Chia is scheduled to become a permanent resident of Mexico
City's Chapultepec Zoo, where it is hoped he will breed. The
Mexican zoo has had success with its panda breeding program, while
Chia Chia's breeding partner at the London Zoo died in 1985.
</TEXT>
