<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Barainca-McAuliffeAward     09-06 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Barainca-McAuliffe Award,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Utah High School Teacher Wins McAuliffe Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school science teacher with a mock
Space Lab in his classroom to help students learn about space
travel has been selected winner of the third Christa McAuliffe
Award for Aerospace Education.
   John Barainca, a teacher at Salt Lake City's Brighton High
School, will be presented the award by the Air Force Association on
Sept. 19 in Arlington, Va. The award is named for Christa
McAuliffe, the teacher killed in the 1986 Challenger disaster.
   The Air Force Association selected Barainca, a teacher for 16
years, from more than 1,000 national candidates. He was to be
honored locally at a dinner Tuesday night.
   Barainca was one of two Utah teachers selected as the state's
candidates for NASA's Teacher in Space program _ the program that
ultimately selected McAuliffe for the ill-fated space shuttle
launch in which she and six astronauts died on Jan. 28, 1986.
   At 52, Barainca said he sees his own chances of space travel
waning, but ``I may get into space through these kids.''
   To illustrate his lessons, he uses a Star Lab to dramatize life
in space. Students shut themselves inside the mock spacecraft that
occupies one corner of the classroom and spend up to five days
there re-enacting a space mission.
   ``He teaches in a way that is off the path of other teachers.
It's off the path of textbooks and into actual experience,'' said
Pete Fesler, one of Barainca's students.
   The award's previous winners were a high school teacher from
Fort Wayne, Ind., and an elementary school teacher from Portland,
Ore.
</TEXT>
