<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1618EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bills-Glasses     09-06 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bills-Glasses,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NY No Longer Only State To Prohibit Over-The-Counter Eyeglass
Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York will no longer be the only state in
the nation to prohibit the sale of non-prescription magnifying
eyeglasses under a bill Gov. Mario Cuomo signed into law Tuesday.
   Sponsors said the measure will slash the cost of glasses for
reading or magnifying objects at close range.
   Lobbying on the bill, which takes effect in 90 days, had been
intense in the Legislature, with consumer groups and eyeglass
manufacturers pushing for its approval and some state optometrists
and opticians advocating its defeat.
   Both houses of the Legislature approved it last month.
   Obtaining magnifying eyeglasses with a prescription costs $60 to
$120, according to the American Association of Retired Persons.
Buying them without a doctor's involvement cuts the price to $12 to
$15, said the sponsors, state Sen. Joseph Bruno and Assemblyman
Richard Gottfried.
   New York became the last state in the country to prohibit
over-the-counter sales of the glasses in June, when Rhode Island
Gov. Edward DiPrete legalized sales in his state.
   ``This clearly shows the absurdity of New York's position and
why it should change,'' said Morton Getman, a lobbyist on behalf of
the nation's largest manufacturer of magnifying glasses,
Magnivision of Miami. ``It's now 49 to 1.''
   New York state's Medical Society opposed the measure for years
but this year said it would go along with the bill after it was
amended to require that all reading glasses carry a tag advising
people to get their eyes checked regularly.
   Jan Dorman, executive director of the Albany-based state
Optometric Association, said approval of the bill would represent
``bad public health policy.''
   Dorman said magnifying glasses can mask serious medical
conditions including glaucoma and detached retinas, problems that
health care professionals are trained to detect.
</TEXT>
