<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PresidentialDebates     09-06 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Debates,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presidential Campaigns Agree on Number of Debates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential candidates George Bush and Michael
Dukakis will face each other in two televised debates and their
running mates will square off once, Dukakis campaign chairman Paul
Brountas said Tuesday.
   After weeks of negotiations, the Dukakis campaign said it is
willing to accept the Bush campaign's offer of two presidential
debates _ one fewer than Dukakis had sought _ as well as one
encounter between vice presidential candidates Dan Quayle and Lloyd
Bentsen.
   ``I've told them we could live with two presidential and one
vice presidential debates,'' said Brountas, who accompanied
Democrat Dukakis on a campaign trip to Illinois.
   ``We still have not reached an agreement on timing and format,''
he added.
   Brountas and Bush campaign chairman James A. Baker III, who
talked by telephone for about 25 minutes Tuesday, planned to
continue their talks on Wednesday, said Mark Goodin, a spokesman
for Bush.
   The two sides hope to reach a final agreement on dates for the
debates and on whether the format will be open or on specific
topics.
   Baker has said that GOP nominee Bush is willing to debate
Dukakis any time between Sept. 25 and Oct. 17.
   The Dukakis campaign wanted the first debate to be on foreign
policy and national security issues, but that was rejected by the
Bush campaign last week.
   On Tuesday, while on a campaign stop in Portland, Ore., Bush
said of Dukakis, ``I have respect for him as a debater.'' He said
Dukakis was ``far better than I am'' in debating.
</TEXT>
