<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1628EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PigChase     09-06 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pig Chase,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police, Neighbors Chase Stray Pigs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police and several neighbors found themselves
in an impromptu pig roundup when about five runaway porkers took to
the streets near here.
   ``We were sitting on our porch, quietly drinking coffee when my
wife said, `Will you look at that,''' said Drew Schwartz.
   ``There were four or five pigs walking down the middle of the
road, shoulder-to-shoulder. It was like they were out for a morning
stroll,'' he said. ``I ran out in the street because there were
cars coming. I got them out of the road.''
   Schwartz added, ``We have a bad curve right there where cars
come around at 40 miles an hour and if they would have hit a pig,
pork chops everywhere.''
   He went to his neighbor's door in Conewago Township, which is in
southeastern Pennsylvania, to ask the man if he knew who owned the
pigs. The pigs went to a garage.
   His wife called police, who asked neighbors if they knew who
owned the pigs. Schwartz ran around to the back of another
neighbor's backyard when he discovered another five pigs.
   ``It was crazy. ... We found a barn door open and a gate inside.
...I don't know if the pigs belonged there or not but it was a good
place to put them. That guy might come home and find ten new
pigs,'' he said.
   Police said the owner is David Rhen, but the officer on duty
could not say if that was the same man who owns the barn the pigs
were left in. Rhen could not be reached for comment.
   ``If you find out that it's not his pigs, give him my number,''
Schwartz said. ``I want some ham.''
</TEXT>
