<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ForestFires-Funds     09-06 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires-Funds,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forest Service May Raid Replanting Fund To Pay For Firefighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the western forest fire season just
entering its peak month, the U.S. Forest Service has already spent
$190 million battling this summer's blazes and may be forced again
to raid a key reforestation trust fund to pay for the effort.
   The agency tapped the same account to help pay last year's
firefighting costs. While Congress traditionally has bailed out the
Forest Service, an Oregon lawmaker said Tuesday the ``smoke and
mirrors'' budgeting could eventually jeopardize the replanting of
national forest lands that have been logged.
   ``It's time the Forest Service rises above the politics of the
Office of Management and the Budget in trying to create the
illusion that the deficit is being held down,'' said Democratic
Rep. Peter A. DeFazio.
   DeFazio said the Forest Service has known for six months that
western forest were tinder dry, but continued to use a
``short-sighted'' budget approach that requires Congress to step in
and appropriate additional funds.
   ``They continue to budget in a penny-wise and pound-foolish
way,'' said DeFazio.
   A Forest Service budget official said no decision has yet been
made on whether to borrow from the so-called Knutsen-Vanderberg
trust fund. ``It's a possibility,'' said Robert Gordon, an
assistant director of the agency.
   Money from the fund comes from fees timber operators pay when
they log national forests and is earmarked for reforestation
projects.
   Traditionally, the Forest Service's budget request includes a
``token'' amount for fighting fires. The agency will borrow from a
trust fund if more money is needed and then ask Congress for
additional funding to repay what was borrowed.
   An interior appropriations bill pending in Congress includes
$125 million for firefighting and DeFazio said that most of it will
be used to repay the trust fund from last year's borrowings.
   ``This whole things is incredibly frustrating,'' said DeFazio.
``They (the Forest Service) admit it's not in their best interest,
but they keep doing it.''
   Last year, the Forest Service spent $265 million to fight fires
that swept across about 800,000 acres in the Pacific Northwest and
California. Most of those blazes were in late August and September.
</TEXT>
