<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ArchbishopReturns     09-06 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Archbishop Returns,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cincinnati Archbishop Returns from Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Catholic Archbishop Daniel E. Pilarczyk of
Cincinnati returned to work Tuesday for the first time since he
suffered a ruptured brain artery in July.
   Pilarczyk, 54, who has governed the Archdiocese of Cincinnati
since 1982, spent a half day in his office, said the Rev. Ted
Kosse, spokesman for the archdiocese. It was his first day of
official duty since he suffered the aneurysm July 23 while
vacationing in Gatlinburg, Tenn.
   The archbishop underwent surgery July 25 at Cincinnati's Good
Samaritan Hospital, where neurosurgeons sealed the ruptured artery
and rerouted the brain's blood supply to avoid a possible fatal
recurrence. He was released from the hospital Aug. 11.
   An aneurysm is a sac formed in the wall of an artery and is
blamed on a congenital weakness in the arterial wall.
   Pilarczyk refused interviews Tuesday, but is to hold a news
conference Thursday.
   His doctors said Pilarczyk gave them approval to be the first in
Cincinnati to use an experimental drug, which doctors said may have
helped save his life by possibly preventing arterial spasms that
can occur even after surgery. The drug, called nicardipine, relaxes
the arterial wall and prevents spasms, doctors said.
   Pilarczyk is spiritual leader of about 550,000 Catholics in the
19-county archdiocese in southwestern Ohio. Auxiliary Bishop James
Garland governed the archdiocese during Pilarczyk's absence.
</TEXT>
