<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1636EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SchoolComputers     09-06 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Computers,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Students Not Benefitting From Spread of Schoolroom Computers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Computers are moving rapidly into American
classrooms, but too many minority and limited-English students
aren't reaping the benefits of the new educational technology, an
advisory group said in a report released Tuesday.
   U.S. schools have acquired nearly 2 million computers during
this decade, said the report by the Office of Technology
Assessment, a non-partisan agency that advises Congress on
technological matters.
   Whereas fewer than one school in five had a computer in 1981,
now all but 5 percent of schools have at least one, the agency said
in a 246-page report titled ``Power On! New Tools For Teaching and
Learning.''
   ``It has been a very important, useful investment,'' said report
director Linda Roberts. ``When students are using computers,
teachers are trained and the software is appropriate, there really
are advances in learning.''
   On the downside, the report found that the total number of
computers is equal to one for every 30 students; average access is
one hour a week, and it would cost $4 billion to reduce the
student-computer ratio to 3:1.
   ``In general, classrooms today resemble their ancestors of 50
and 100 years ago much more closely than than they do today's
assembly plants, scientific laboratories and operating rooms,'' it
said. ``Most schools do not have enough computers to make them a
central tool of instruction.''
   Exacerbating the access problem is the fact that computers tend
to be concentrated in affluent schools with smaller student bodies,
the report said.
   The agency report said black students, who generally attend
larger schools, have less computer access than white students and
``students with limited English proficiency have the lowest access
of all.''
   Other problems cited in the report include inadequate teacher
training, mediocre educational software and ``the absence of a
coordinated federal policy, limited and short-term funding, erratic
political support and disorganized research and development efforts
across agencies...''
   Only one-third of teachers have even 10 hours of computer
training, the agency found, and little of it focused on how to
teach with computers.
   And while there are 10,000 educational software products
available, OTA said, ``their quality could be much better...
Economic risks in the marketplace lead software publishers to play
it safe.''
   At the current rate of investment, Roberts said, ``the nation
can expect continuing experimentation in some schools, steady but
slow improvement in software and spotty access to the technology by
students.''
   Speeding up the process will require greater efforts by the
federal, state and local governments as well as the private sector,
she said.
   On the federal level, OTA recommended boosting the current $240
million investment in learning technology research, including
development of software; and encouraging school districts to buy
more hardware and software with money from Chapter 1 and Chapter 2,
federal programs for disadvantaged students and general education
spending by states.
   The agency's report was requested by the House Education and
Labor Committee. Committee chairman Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif.,
said in comments accompanying the report that increased federal
support for computers in the schools ``would be a good public
policy and a wise investment for the future.''
   Rep. Matthew Martinez, D-Calif., chairman of the panel's
subcommittee on employment opportunities, said minority and
limited-English students must be ensured equal access to computers.
   ``Access to these technologies is spelled M-O-N-E-Y, but the
schools our minority students attend are often overcrowded and
underfunded,'' Martinez said. ``Technology can narrow or widen
these differences. If we do not act... the classroom of tomorrow
may always be left for manana in many of our schools.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
