<1ST_LINE>r p AM-NebraskaSenate     09-06 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nebraska Senate,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Karnes Says He Didn't Mean His Remark About Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By J.L. SCHMIDT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. David Karnes drew boos from the crowd
and criticism from opponent Bob Kerrey when he told a crowds at the
Nebraska State Fair that ``We need fewer farmers at this point in
time.''
   ``I was perplexed when I heard all of the booing,'' Karnes said
Monday after the first of eight debates between himself and the
former one-term Democratic governor. ``I obviously don't support
that statement. We should be able to encourage people to look at
agriculture as an investment.''
   Karnes was speaking about increased agricultural technology when
he made the remark, to a standing-room-only audience of more than
2,000 people. He said later that he had misspoken and attributed it
to ``the heat of the debate.'' Karnes said what he meant by the
statement was that technology has allowed fewer farmers to do more
work.
   Kerrey, after the debate, called Karnes' statement ``a mistake''
in political judgment.
   ``It is to assume again that we've got to have fewer farmers. It
is to believe that there is nothing we can do to provide support
for the farmers we have now,'' Kerrey said.
   Another Karnes slip brought applause and cheers from Kerrey
supporters as the Republican rebutted Kerrey's criticism of a
diesel fuel tax amendment he sponsored.
   ``Mr. Kerrey, once you get to the United States Senate you'll
know the importance of putting people on record,'' Karnes said.
   Karnes spokesman Brent Bahler said of the candidate's verbal
fumbles: ``I'll be blunt. He is not as articulate as I would like
him to be.
   ``But people understand Senator Karnes is not a smooth talker
like his challenger. Sometimes his words get jumbled. But do we
want a senator that is a smooth talker or one who knows his stuff?''
   Karnes, who was appointed to the Senate after the death of
Democrat Edward Zorinsky, is seeking election to his first full
term.
</TEXT>
