<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0584 09-06 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0584,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede LAWRENCEVILLE, Ga.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bentsen Chides Bush for Late Conversion to Education Cause</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `And unlike,' with 5 grafs new to reflect
speech delivered; UPDATES with additional Bentsen comments and
presence of student protesters.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLACKSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen foraged for Southern votes on Tuesday by emphasizing
education and training to help meet foreign competition _ and
chiding Republican George Bush for a late conversion to the cause.
   ``If we want to retain our position of world leadership, America
must be able to compete for world markets,'' Bentsen said. ``We
must have the best-trained, most highly motivated workforce, the
best universities and the best teachers.''
   And unlike Bush, Bentsen said in a speech at the Virginia
Polytechnic Institute, Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis has been on the education bandwagon from the start.
   ``Mike Dukakis didn't just suddenly wake up one morning and
decide he wanted to be `the education president,''' Bentsen said,
alluding to Bush's claim to the description. ``Mike Dukakis and
Lloyd Bentsen have accepted a lifelong commitment to education.
   ``For eight years now we've watched the Reagan-Bush
administration trash educational opportunity across this country,''
Bentsen told a rowdy student audience packed into the college
auditorium.
   Following the speech, Bentsen moved outside for a rally before
several hundred more students, including a strong-voiced contingent
for Bush and some carrying signs that read, ``Duke buster,'' and
``Avoid the Lloyd.''
   Bentsen, interrupted in his remarks, looked at that group and
said, ``I met George Bush once before,'' alluding to his defeat of
Bush in a 1970 Texas Senate race. ``And I think Quayle season is
starting early this year.''
   Bentsen said college alone does not provide all of the nation's
important education as he started his day visiting a technical
training center in the Atlanta suburb of Lawrenceville.
   Bentsen handled a soldering iron and other tools, including a
microscope, to inspect the work. Afterward, he told reporters the
federal government could do more to provide ``seed money'' to
expand technical training.
   The Reagan administration has ``put all kinds of speed bumps in
the way to achieving education,'' Bentsen said. A Democratic
administration, he said, would promote programs such as the one at
the Gwinnett Technical Institute where he attended the class with
nine women learning to make electronic circuit boards.
   Bentsen also said he personally favored a longer school year for
U.S. children, citing figures from Europe and Japan. But he said
that issue would be decided at the state and local level, not by
the federal government.
   Polls show the Republican ticket leading in both Georgia and
Virginia, but Bentsen said he considered both states within range
for the Democrats, especially since they were receiving support
from locally-elected officials.
   Rep. Ed Jenkins, D-Ga., attended the session at Gwinnett with
Bentsen, and Virginia Gov. Gerald Baliles and former Gov. Charles
Robb, now a Senate candidate, were awaiting Bentsen at the college
in Blacksburg, Va.
   ``I think we'll get those Democrats who voted for Reagan coming
back to us,'' Bentsen told reporters, adding that polls backed up
his statement. ``To the extend we can bring them back, we're going
to do it.''
   Dukakis' support of gun control laws is one of the obstacles in
that effort. Bentsen, who usually opposes such measures, said he
had not yet decided whether to support an amendment now before the
Congress.
   Bentsen said the underlying concept in the amendment of a
waiting period for handgun purchases was appealing, since it would
provide a ``cooling off period'' for people wanting a gun for
emotional reasons. It also would give officials time to determine
if the purchaser was a criminal, he said.
   However, he said he had not studied how far the amendment
extended beyond that and was withholding any endorsement.
   The Texas senator was returning to Washington for a vote
Wednesday on a bill to help the textile industry _ also an
important issue in the South where many factories have been hurt by
foreign competition.
   Bentsen planned to resume campaigning Thursday, beginning in New
York and finishing the week in California, with a stop in Iowa en
route.
</TEXT>
