<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Lotto     09-06 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lotto,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Others Claim Prize Ticket, But Education is Real Winner, Officials
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The identity of Florida's $55.2 million
lottery winner remained a mystery Tuesday, but state officials
announced one sure victor: schoolchildren.
   Florida puts 35 percent of lottery sales to education, which now
equals $350 million in the lottery's first eight months. Officials
said the total is twice as much as earlier projections.
   Gov. Bob Martinez, who opposes the lottery, said Tuesday the
state broke $1 billion in sales during last week's record number of
ticket purchases, which contributed to the world's largest single
lottery jackpot.
   ``This record-breaking pace is exciting, both for the players
and public education in Florida,'' Martinez said. ``While the
lottery was never envisioned to meet all the funding needs of
education, it's good to know that the games are doing so much to
enhance our basic school program.''
   Meanwhile, lottery officials say they have heard from several
people who claim to have the winning ticket.
   The six winning numbers were picked in a drawing Saturday night,
and lottery officials determined by computer the next day that only
one ticket _ purchased by someone in Longwood in central Florida _
had the winning combination.
   A person claiming to represent Charles Hill, a school janitor in
the Panhandle town of Bristol, called the Lottery Department on
Tuesday and said Hill would come to Tallahassee Wednesday with the
winning ticket, said Lottery Secretary Rebecca Paul.
   ``We have no reason to believe that he does or that he doesn't
until he comes forward with the actual ticket and it goes through
our validation process we really don't know,'' Mrs. Paul said.
   ``We've talked to a whole bunch of people who say they have the
winning ticket,'' she said.
   At least three other people have called the department claiming
to have the winning ticket, according to Bernard Edwards, deputy
secretary of operations. Mrs. Paul said one of the callers
identified himself as a resident of Minnesota, and another caller
came from central Florida.
   ``We've had several dozen calls from folks saying `We have the
winning ticket _ what do we do?' without identifying themselves or
their city or anything else,'' Mrs. Paul said.
   Winners have 180 days to claim their prizes.
   One unknown _ the exact amount of the prize _ was determined,
Mrs. Paul said. The jackpot's final value was put at $55.2 million
Tuesday, which breaks down into 20 annual payments of $2.7 million
before taxes. Earlier, estimates put the record jackpot at $54
million.
</TEXT>
