<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RapidFire     09-06 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rapid Fire,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Washington Blaze Threatens Nation's Apple Basket</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wildfires Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ENTIAT, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   a fire in parched grass and pine exploded
in 24 hours from just 160 acres to more than 25,000 acres Tuesday,
sending firefighters fleeing and burning toward some of Washington
state's prime orchards.
   Fire bosses set up a command post in the tiny Columbia River
town of Entiat, while helicopters dipped huge buckets into the
river and then dumped water on the steep smoldering hillsides above
town.
   The town itself, on the opposite side of the Entiat River from
the fire, was in no immediate danger from the flames, which had
been blown to within an estimated half a mile of the community of
400 people.
   The Dinkelman fire's explosive growth overran at least one
bulldozer that could not move fast enough and a pickup that broke
down, said Art Tasker of the state Department of Natural Resources.
   No serious injuries were reported.
   ``It's extremely erratic and very, very volatile,'' Tasker said.
``There are gusty winds. It's very dry and very steep.
   ``I watched it move a half a mile in 10 minutes last night.''
   National Guard troops called out by Gov. Booth Gardner late
Monday were to handle kitchen and camp duties for about 600
firefighters.
   Intense heat in narrow Mills Canyon caused one home to burst
into flames, even though trails had been dug around the home and
firefighters had burned away excess vegetation, Tasker said.
   The fire, reported Sunday afternoon, was reported at just 500
acres as late as 4:30 p.m. Monday. But by 7:30 p.m. it was 3,000
acres, and by 4 a.m. Tuesday it was at least 20,000 acres.
   The fire was burning on steep hills covered with sage, grass,
pine, and some Douglas fir, and was beginning to butt up against
some orchards in Washington's premier fruit-growing region. The
burned territory was mostly U.S. Forest Service land, but also
included state land and Longview Fibre Co. property.
   ``It's an explosive kind of situation,'' DNR spokesman Rob
Harper said. ``If you look at the conditions out there, eastern
Washington is extremely dry. ... The wind is the final ingredient
that you need after you get the fire started.''
</TEXT>
