<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 2011EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Dukakis     09-06 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Dukakis,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says He's Not Upset at Dukakis; Aides Suggest Otherwise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson denied on Tuesday that he was
angry that Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis excluded
him from a meeting with Illinois party leaders. He said he hoped by
the end of the week to work out his role in the fall campaign.
   Jackson, in a telephone interview from his home in Chicago,
contradicted associates who charecterized him as upset by the
omission _ including one who said he was ``seething.''
   ``I just hate for people to be allowed to put words in my mouth
or give some adjective description of what my emotions are,'' he
said of the associates, who commented only on condition they not be
named.
   He said he spoke by telephone to Dukakis' campaign vice chairman
and confidant, John Sasso, Monday night and Tuesday morning and
they arranged to meet later this week to discuss Jackson's
participation in the campaign and the relationship and message of
the campaign to ``targeted groups'' such as Jackson's constituents
in the primary season.
   Asked if he would get a schedule of campaign appearances at this
meeting, the Democratic presidential runner-up said, ``I certainly
hope so.''
   He said they did not discuss the meeting Dukakis held outside
Jackson's home base of Chicago on Tuesday with state party leaders,
including Sen. Paul Simon, Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, and others.
   ``I didn't know anything about it other than the press
inquiries. So I have no comment to make,'' said Jackson.
   ``I'm working. I'm hopeful. I'm registering voters,'' he said.
   Dukakis' state press secretary Judy Erwin said the Tuesday
meeting was more for state leaders, and that Jackson was considered
a national leader.
   Jackson indicated he is anxious to get under way with his part
of the fall campaign, as he agreed to do just before the Democrats
nominated Dukakis at their Atlanta convention this summer.
   He declined to criticize Dukakis, despite a series of omissions
that some Jackson supporters have perceived as slights.
   ``If they don't want his help they ought to tell him,'' said one
top Jackson adviser, who asked not to be identified by name.
   Asked about the appearance that Dukakis has been slow to involve
him in the campaign, Jackson said, ``There are some decisions the
campaign has to make about how it will employ its volunteers,''
including people such as New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, Sen. Edward
Kennedy of Massachusetts and himself.
   ``I assume that's the kind of thing Sasso will be doing,'' he
added.
   ``The plans are incomplete. I hope they will be complete soon.
... hese areas dealing with campaign direction and priorities still
have to be worked out. I hope before this week is out that all of
the remaining areas will be resolved and we'll be on our way.''
   Dukakis campaign spokesman Leslie Dach denied any attempt to
slight Jackson and said the meeting with Sasso this week will
include discussion of ``how we can best work together, places
details, themes.''
   He said Jackson regularly talks to Dukakis and campaign
officials.
   Jackson said he wants to talk to Dukakis officials about
involving some of his supporters at the national policy level of
the campaign, and about targeting the Democratic message and
priorities.
   The most recently reported tension involved reports that the
Dukakis camp had conducted polling that found Jackson had high
negative ratings in some states where he beat Dukakis in the
primaries and that the Dukakis officials had indicated they did not
want Jackson campaigning in those states.
   While these reports came from sources close to Jackson and the
national Democratic Party, Jackson himself said he had received no
such direction.
   Asked if the subject of states he should stay away from was
discussed in a meeting he had with Dukakis campaign chairman Paul
Brountas and Democratic National Committee Chairman Paul Kirk two
weeks ago, Jackson said, ``I was not in any such meetings when
there was discussion over where and what the priority areas ought
to be.''
   Asked if the information was imparted through aides, as one
source stated, he said, ``I don't have anything in writing on
that.''
   ``I don't want to discuss it because I don't know very much
about it, but obvously I'm free to travel all over the country and
I will,'' he added.
   While some around Jackson have described him as annoyed and
upset at how the Dukakis campaign has treated him and his
constituents, Jackson publicly continues to tout the Dukakis ticket
in his speeches, and refused to make negative comments under
questioning.
</TEXT>
