<HEAD>Black Newspaper To Reject Government Ads Promoting Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with police seizing tape of Tutu
sermon, edits to conform. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police came to Archbishop
Desmond Tutu's residence Tuesday and seized a tape of a sermon in
which the clergyman defied a government ban and called for an
election boycott, Tutu's spokesman said.
   Meanwhile, the country's largest black-oriented daily newspaper
said Tuesday it will no longer carry government advertisements
promoting the local elections.
   The Sowetan, in a notice on its front page, said: ``It has
become impossible to justify carrying these advertisements when the
community we serve is barred from expressing its sentiments on the
elections.''
   Many blacks oppose participation in any local or regional
elections until the black majority is allowed to vote in national
elections.
   Tutu, whose sermon Sunday defied the government ban on calls for
an election boycott, had offered to provide police with a
transcript of his remarks.
   However, two plainclothes officers came to the Anglican
archbishop's official residence outside Cape Town, produced a
warrant and demanded a recording which Tutu's press aide, John
Allen, had made of the sermon.
   Allen, after consulting the church's legal advisers, gave police
the tape and a statement confirming the contents of the recording.
But Allen said he would not be prepared to give evidence if the
state tried to call him as a witness against Tutu.
   Allen, in a telephone interview, said police had called in
advance to say they were coming and did not ask to see Tutu, who
was meeting with church members.
   In his sermon at St. George's Cathedral in Cape Town, Tutu
deliberately defied state-of-emergency regulations by urging both
whites and blacks to boycott nationwide municipal elections
scheduled for Oct. 26.
   A pro-government newspaper, The Citizen, Tuesday quoted
unidentified government sources as saying action against Tutu was
likely. It quoted one source as saying failure to act against the
black archbishop would encourage other people to join in calling
for a boycott.
   Violation of the emergency regulations is punishable by up to 10
years in prison.
   The Oct. 26 elections will mark the first time that voters of
all races go to the polls on the same day. The white-controlled
government is depicting the elections as a major step toward
democracy and is spending hundreds of thousands of dollars on
advertising to encourage a large turnout.
   Tutu's comments angered Cape Town's mayor, Peter Muller, who
said they could jeopardize the election prospects of liberal
candidates.
   Because of Muller's criticism, Tutu decided not to attend a
ceremony Monday night at which a prominent mixed-race academic, Dr.
Richard van der Ross, become the first non-white to be awarded the
freedom of the city.
</TEXT>
