<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0676 09-06 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0676,0750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Clamps Down on West Bank Town</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-8 graf UPDATE number of arrests, with hardened
attribution. PICKS up 9th graf pvs, Reporters in ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Israeli troops sealed off a West
Bank town Tuesday, cutting telephone lines, arresting more than 150
Palestinians and assembling makeshift army bases in a new tactic
aimed at crushing the uprising.
   Underground leaders distributed a leaflet in the occupied
territories calling on Palestinians to attack Israeli targets with
``more firebombs and more stones, everywhere and anywhere.''
   A 17-year-old Palestinian, shot in the eye on Sunday during
clashes with troops, died of his wounds Tuesday, relatives said. An
Israeli soldier was hurt slightly when he kicked an old pipe that
contained explosives, the army said.
   The death brought to 259 the number of Palestinians killed since
the uprising began Dec. 8. Four Israelis have also died.
   Brig. Gen. Gabi Ofir, a West Bank army commander, said Tuesday's
pre-dawn raid on Qalqilya, backed by helicopters, was the largest
army operation in nine months of unrest.
   The army imposed a curfew on Qalqilya before dawn and soldiers
moved in through outlying orchards and fields, forming a human
chain around the town of 25,000. Troops closed all roads leading to
the city.
   Soldiers carried lists of suspected stone-throwers and arrested
more than 150 Palestinians, the army said.
   Israel television showed dozens of Palestinians, their hands
tied behind their backs, sitting in large open-sided tents. Troops
herded dozens of blindfolded detainees through a major street.
   Reporters in Qalqilya saw dozens of troops patrolling streets
and three Palestinian youths being held in a jeep with their hands
tied behind them.
   Singling out Qalqilya, which lies just inside the West Bank and
only three minutes by car from Tel Aviv's northern suburbs,
appeared to be the army's latest tactic for cracking down on
activist Palestinian towns. The move prompted concern among
Palestinians that other villages would be targeted.
   West Bank commander Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna said the operation
was planned for weeks and targeted Qalqilya because its residents
include key instigators of firebomb and stone-throwing attacks on
Jewish settlers and Israeli troops.
   Mitzna told Israel radio that ``the situation had become
intolerable, therefore we decided (to act) now.''
   Palestinian taxi drivers turned back at army roadblocks reported
seeing four helicopters flying overhead and dozens of army
vehicles, some pulling mobile homes normally used in makeshift army
bases.
   The witnesses said troops knocked down a wall separating a
playground and high school and were pitching tents on the grounds.
   ``It is the first time I've seen such activity. It is really
strange and we are worried other villages will be next,'' one Arab
taxi driver told The Associated Press on condition of anonymity.
   An army spokesman said troops discovered stashes of knives,
hatchets and clubs as well as outlawed underground leaflets in
Qalqilya.
   In the latest leaflet, underground leaders also called for three
general strikes in two weeks, including a strike Thursday to mark
the ninth month of the Palestinian uprising.
   The leaflet also highlighted a deepening split between Moslem
fundamentalists and uprising leaders who support the Palestine
Liberation Organization. It criticized the fundamentalists for
declaring alternative strike days and attacking shopkeepers who did
not comply.
   Abdel Karim Mahmoud Barud, 17, from the Gaza Strip refugee camp
Rafah, who was shot in the eye Sunday, died Tuesday at Tel Hashomer
Hospital near Tel Aviv, his relatives said.
   Hospital officials could not be reached for comment. The army
said it had no information on the death.
   Also Tuesday, troops shot and wounded four Palestinian
teen-agers while confronting stone-throwers in the West Bank town
of Nablus and the Gaza Strip's Nuseirat refugee camp, hospital
officials said. The army said it was checking the report.
   Near Nablus, an Israeli soldier was treated at the scene for
minor injuries and returned to his unit after a pipe bomb exploded.
   Newly released Israeli figures indicated the Palestinian
population growth in the Gaza Strip was fulfilling predictions that
Arabs could outnumber Jews in Israel and its occupied territories
by the year 2000.
   The figures put the annual population growth in the Gaza Strip
at 3.4 percent in 1986, one of the highest rates in the world. This
compares with an annual population growth of 1.3 percent inside
Israel.
</TEXT>
