<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 2017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WorldCourt-UN     09-06 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Court-UN,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Asks Major Powers To Accept World Court Jurisdiction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Javier Perez de Cuellar, the U.N.
secretary-general, asked the permanent Security Council members
Tuesday to unequivocally accept compulsory jurisdiction of the
World Court.
   Of the five, only Britain accepts the court's jurisdiction as
compulsory.
   France, China and the Soviet Union have filed no formal
declarations of acceptance, although that does not bar them from
appearing before the court.
   The United States severely curtailed its acceptance of court
jurisdiction in 1984, just before Nicaragua filed a complaint
against the Reagan administration, accusing it of aiding rebels
fighting the Managua government.
   Perez de Cuellar said Tuesday, ``Widespread acceptance of the
jurisdiction of the court as compulsory would, particularly if
taken by the permanent members of the Security Council, put to
maximum use the role of the court as a stabilizing factor in
international relations.''
   The U.N. chief spoke at a ceremony celebrating the 75th
anniversary of the Peace Palace, of which the World Court is the
major tenant. The court, officially known as the International
Court of Justice, is the U.N. judicial branch.
   Dutch Queen Beatrix, Premier Ruud Lubbers and World Court
President Jose-Maria Ruda of Argentina were among the dignitaries
attending.
   The U.S. government boycotted the last 17 months of Nicaragua's
case against it. The court ultimately condemned American support
for the rebels, known as Contras, and ordered an immediate halt to
such aid.
   In an apparent reference to that U.S. move, Perez de Cuellar
said, ``Other (nations) have, when their interests were at stake,
chosen not to take part in the court's proceedings or to ignore its
decisions, a development that gives rise to considerable concern.''
   Only 49 nations now accept the compulsory jurisdiction of the
World Court, which has no enforcement powers and depends on
voluntary adherence to its rulings by nations not recognizing its
authority unequivocally.
</TEXT>
