<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Arrest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0658,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Convicted Murderer Sought By FBI.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 1st graf, FBI says Kindler not on list of 10 most
wanted. PICKS up 2nd graf pvs Police Inspector ... with minor
editing below. ADDS four grafs with FBI comments.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAINT JOHN, New Brunswick (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Tuesday captured a
convicted murderer who escaped from a U.S. prison where he was
awaiting execution.
   Police Inspector Vic Hawkins said Joseph Kindler, 27, who beat a
man to death in Philadelphia in 1984, was arrested at work by Saint
John police.
   Hawkins would not say where Kindler worked because ``the people
there are terrified.''
   Police said they received a tip Monday from a local resident
that Kindler was in the city. He was arrested Tuesday morning
without incident and was remanded to the Saint John jail at an
afternoon court appearance.
   He will be held in Saint John until Quebec police take him back
on an outstanding warrant, according to Hawkins.
   He said Kindler was convicted of first-degree murder in 1984 but
escaped from a maximum-security prison.
   In 1986 he was arrested in Quebec and was being held for a
deportation hearing in Montreal when he escaped again.
   Kindler, who faces execution in the United States, slid down
bedsheets to get away from his 13th-floor cell in a detention
centre at Quebec's provincial police headquarters in Montreal.
   He had been living in the area of St-Jovite, Quebec, before he
disappeared last spring, Hawkins said.
   He said that in the 1984 murder Kindler bludgeoned a man to
death with a baseball bat.
   Hawkins said an FBI report stated, ``Kindler has been armed with
a handgun in the past and has stated he will never be taken alive.''
   It had been reported here that Kindler was on the FBI's list of
10 most wanted criminals, but FBI spokeswoman Melanie McElhinney
said in Washington that was not correct.
   She said Kindler ``was what we call an identification order
fugitive,'' and that classification is ``a step below the top'' 10
most wanted people.
   Criminals in that classificiation are considered to be ``very
dangerous individuals, usually wanted for murder, things like that,
very serious crimes,'' she added.
   Kindler had been the subject in one of the programs of the
television show ``America's Most Wanted.''
</TEXT>
