<HEAD>Food, Water Poisoning Kill Three Lebanese, Fell 150 Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Food and water poisoning killed three
people and hospitalized more than 150 in two separate incidents,
police said Tuesday.
   They said 53 victims were poisoned by eating meat sandwiches
late Monday at a restaurant in the northern port of Tripoli.
   ``Most of the 53 ... came in screaming from severe stomach
aches,'' said a nurse at a Tripoli hospital.
   ``Later they started fainting and than three died. There was
nothing we could do,'' she added, refusing to give her name.
   The owner of the restaurant on Tripoli's fashionable Azmi Street
was arrested.
   In south Lebanon, more than 100 people were hospitalized Tuesday
after drinking from an artesian well in the village of Rzai, 15
miles northeast of the ancient port city of Tyre, police reported.
   ``The poisoning is due to an overdose of chlorine used to purify
the well's water,'' said Dr. Raymond Saarour at Tyre's government
hospital.
   Sources at the Health Ministry in Beirut said medical and other
supplies would be sent to Tyre to help cope with the emergency.
