<1ST_LINE>r p AM-TexasAds     09-06 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texas Ads,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis-Bentsen Release Ads; Republicans Charge Issue `Phony'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dukakis-Bentsen campaign on Tuesday
gave a preview of of a television ad touting the Democrats' efforts
to win a plant closing notification law.
   Tom Cosgrove, Texas campaign director for the presidential
ticket of Michael Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen, said the Democrats'
commercial reflects an emphasis on ``the future of the economy in
this country.''
   The commercial, which starts airing Wednesday in Dallas, Houston
and San Antonio, said that Bentsen ``won the fight'' in the Senate
as sponsor of the law requiring 60 days' notice of a plant closing.
   A ``fact sheet'' handed out at the screening said GOP vice
presidential nominee Dan Quayle, an Indiana senator, had opposed
the plant closing notification bill.
   President Reagan first vetoed a trade bill that contained the
measure, then allowed a separate bill to become law without his
signature. The Democrats said Vice President George Bush also
opposed the legislation.
   Charlie Black, a senior adviser to the national GOP presidential
campaign and ``Texas-specific'' consultant, said the plant-closing
law is ``a phony issue.''
   ``Plant closing is a way of them continuing to duck the issues,
because they haven't presented anything about the economy that
would give people any hope that they could improve on the Reagan
performance or the future Bush performance,'' Black said.
</TEXT>
