<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-06 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sunshine Almost Everywhere Except The Sunshine State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sunshine prevailed across most of the nation Tuesday after an
unseasonably cool morning, but some rain continued in Florida,
southeast Georgia and coastal sections of the Carolinas.
   Flooding was a problem around Gainesville, Fla., and in parts of
western central Florida. Thunderstorms brought locally heavy rain
along a stationary front that extended through northern Florida.
   About 30 cities had record low temperatures Tuesday morning,
including Peoria, Ill., at 41 degrees; Nashville, Tenn., 51;
Phillips, Wis., 31; and Hibbing, Minn., 31.
   Other record lows for the date were Allentown, Pa., 42 degrees;
Binghamton, N.Y., 39; Burlington, Iowa, 44; Des Moines, Iowa, 42;
Dubuque, Iowa, 38; Eau Claire, Wis., 37; Evansville, Ind., 45;
Green Bay, Wis., 38; Kansas City, Mo., 48; Lexington, Ky., 45;
Mansfield, Ohio, 42; Mason City, Iowa, 39; Moline, Ill., 40;
Paducah, Ky., 43; St. Cloud, Minn., 35; St. joseph, Mo., 38; Terre
Haute, Ind., 43; Topeka, Kan., 41; Waterloo, Iowa, 35.
   A frost warning was posted for Wednesday morning for the
northern mountains of western Pennsylvania. Scattered frost also
was possible in rural areas of western New York.
   Cool weather continued Tuesday across most of the eastern half
of the nation, but warming took place in Texas and western portions
of the northern and central Plains. A few readings were near the 90
degree mark in Texas, Colorado and Montana.
   The western third of the nation had mostly 80s, but afternoon
temperatures were as low as the 50s and 60s in western Washington
and Oregon and along the northern California coast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Jamestown, N.Y., to 105 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
The nation's low Tuesday morning was 25 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   The forecast for Wednesday called for showers and thunderstorms
continuing along and ahead of a stationary front over the Carolina
coast, southeast Georgia and the Florida peninsula. Windy
conditions were expected to spread across the northern Rockies, the
northern and central Plains and the upper Mississippi Valley. Most
of the nation should have sunny skies.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 60s in New England,
New York, the central Appalachians and western Washington. Readings
in the 90s were predicted for the Plains from Texas to eastern
Wyoming and western South Dakota and for parts of western Colorado,
Utah, and southwest Oregon, and to near 105 in parts of Nevada,
interior valleys of California and the desert Southwest. The
remainder of the nation should have highs in the 70s and 80s.
</TEXT>
