<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1857EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland-Solidarity     09-06 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Solidarity,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Spokesman Rejects Legalizing Solidarity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Tuesday the promised
``round table'' talks with workers will begin this month but gave
no indication it would grant the main demand, legalizing Solidarity.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said supporters of the outlawed
free trade union movement should join existing official unions and
try to reshape them from within. The official union federation,
called OPZZ, said it would oppose allowing new unions into plants
where it is established.
   Solidarity founder Lech Walesa, who persuaded workers to stop
striking in return for the negotiations, declared ``Let them
talk,'' but also said such statements ``could destroy the round
table.''
   An OPZZ resolution said Premier Zbigniew Messner's government
should resign. Its leaders have said government officials should be
held personally accountable for economic problems that led to a
nationwide wave of strikes last month.
   Numerous signs in the official press and in speeches at a party
conference last month have pointed to changes in the government at
the next parliament session, which is expected this month. Such a
shakeup would not affect the Communist Party leadership, which
holds the real power.
   Urban said at his first news conference since the strikes ended
Saturday that talks with Walesa and other worker delegates will
start this month and include several dozen people.
   He said the government wants the meetings to begin as soon as
possible after preparatory work is finished, but also said they
will be canceled automatically if any more ``political'' strikes
occur.
   Talks will cover speeding economic reform, reaching a national
consensus for reform, improving living standards and democratizing
Poland, he said.
   Walesa talked supporters into ending the strikes last week after
getting a commitment from Interior Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak for
negotiations whose topics would include Solidarity.
   The first independent trade union in the Soviet bloc was born in
the labor turmoil of 1980 at the Lenin shipyard in Gdansk, where
Walesa works as an electrician. Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski's
government imposed martial law in December 1981 to suppress
Solidarity and outlawed it the next year.
   Asked about Solidarity's demand for a return to legal status,
Urban said that allowing two trade unions in one plant was
unacceptable.
   ``If followers of some tendency connected in the past with
Solidarity are a majority in a given plant, then they can either
join the (official) trade union, outnumbering it and directing it
where they wish, or form a coalition, a compromise body'' with the
official union.
   ``The existing legal rules offer a broad scope of
possibilities,'' he said, and Solidarity activists made a
``historical mistake'' in boycotting the new government unions
created in 1982 after Solidarity was outlawed.
   Urban said a pro-Solidarity union could be formed in a plant
where no union existed, but would not be permitted to use the name
Solidarity ``in the present legal situation.''
   Reached at home in Gdansk after Urban's news conference, Walesa
said: ``Let them talk. But they should remember that they could
destroy the round table by such irresponsible statements. This is
all I can say.''
   Solidarity activists say they want their own union, not
membership in the unions established by the government under
martial law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
