<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Lebanon,0107</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Fire Rocket At Militiamen</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab guerrillas fired a rocket on Tuesday at a
position manned by Israeli-backed militiamen in southern Lebanon,
igniting a fire but inflicting no casualties, Israel radio reported.
   It said the Soviet-designed Katyusha rocket struck a South
Lebanon Army militia position near Hasbaya in Israel's
self-declared security zone.
   Israel established the six- to 10-mile-wide zone north of its
border after withdrawing the bulk of its troops from Lebanon in
1985, ending a three-year occupation.
   About 1,000 Israeli troops and 1,500 fighters of the
predominantly Christian South Lebanon Army patrol the area.
