<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1917EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0621 09-06 1024</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0621,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Booed by Shipyard Workers</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 11 grafs new after 21st graf, `Over lunch,' to UPDATE
with Dukakis comment on Bush remark, vice president's reception in
Washington, Bush's remark to local broadcasters and newspapers.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, declaring
Republicans have provided good jobs at good wages, was angrily
booed and jeered Tuesday by hard-hat shipyard workers chanting,
``Union buster, union buster'' and ``Go home, George.''
   Bush encountered the hostile reaction from boilermakers,
pipefitters, laborers and electricians during a speech at the
Northwest Marine Iron Works.
   Trying to win votes in a state where he acknowledged he trailed
Democratic rival Michael Dukakis, Bush said, ``Do not gamble on
another liberal Democrat coming out of nowhere.''
   He told the crowd of several hundred, ``Don't listen to all this
Dukakis stuff. They're on the ropes and they've got to make all
this noise.''
   Bush appeared to have a smattering of support in the audience
and was able to win a few cheers when he said he supported the
death penalty for drug kingpins and for criminals who kill police
officers.
   The workers also applauded when Bush declared his opposition to
furlough programs for prison inmates.
   However, the audience was largely unfriendly. One prominent sign
read, ``Union busting, scab-loving Bush.'' Several people shouted
obscenities at Bush during his speech.
   The vice president said the Reagan administration had brought
the prime interest rate down from 21 percent and had slashed
inflation. He said, ``We're making progress for the working man and
women in this country.''
   He pledged anew never to raise taxes _ drawing some applause _
and urged the crowd to ``get that same pledge out of the
Democrats.''
   Opening a two-state swing _ taking him later to Everett in
Washington, another state where Bush said he was trailing _ he said
his goal was to provide a good job at a good wage for everyone who
wanted one.
   ``Good jobs at good wages'' is a main Dukakis campaign theme.
   When Bush credited the Reagan administration with providing 18
million new jobs over the past six years, the audience booed.
   ``I know the truth sometimes hurts,'' Bush said.
   At times he appeared combative and did not flinch from the
heated encounter. When tensions seemed high at one point, Bush said
``little drama'' and pulled out a 1950 union card showing that he
was a dues-paying member of the steelworkers then.
   ``The Democrats are trying to mislead you, predicting gloom and
doom,'' Bush said.
   ``It's quite simple: The other party won't get elected unless
things get worse, and things aren't going to get worse unless they
get elected.''
   Bush said Dukakis was looking for problems in America's
``new-found American strength.'' The ice president also said of
Dukakis, ``It's all a mistake, he'll tell you. Quick, before it's
too late, we'd better get serious, he'll tell you, and return to
the policies of Jimmy Carter.''
   ``We just cannot go back and lose the progress that we've made
in this country.''
   After his speech, Bush bought a sandwich from a lunch truck and
ate it during a meeting with some of the workers. One of them
challenged him to explain why his wages have gone from $13.36 to
$9.50 per hour during the Reagan administration.
   ``You're going through a competitive change,'' Bush said,
referring to the foreign challenge to U.S. shipyards.
   Over lunch, Bush appeared unperturbed by the crowd's reaction.
``All I need is 51 percent of the vote,'' he said.
   Dukakis, en route from a campaign appearance in Chicago to
Boston, said Bush's comments reflected an inability to comprehend
the needs of the average American.
   ``George Bush made it clear today that he really does not
understand the hopes and dreams and aspiration of millions and
millions of American workers across this country,'' Dukakis said.
``That's not an adequate answer to American workers.''
   Later in the day, Bush got a decidedly different welcome from an
audience at a non-union manufacturing plant in Washington.
   A crowd of about 500 people at the Fluke Manufacturing Co.,
which specializes in electronic instruments, gave the vice
president a warm, polite reception as he spoke about jobs and the
economy.
   ``Incomes are rising, unemployment is falling and I'll tell 'ya,
things are on the move in this country,'' he said.
   ``Some don't want us to believe that things are getting better
in this country,'' the vice president said. ``My opponent is one of
them, frankly.''
   Bush and his staff said they were not upset by the reception
earlier in Portland.
   ``You're talking to people you've got to convert. I think we
converted a few,'' said Craig Fuller, Bush's chief of staff.
   For his part, Bush told the lunchroom crowd of workers earlier,
``You don't let them rattle you. It's like being a baseball player
when you're out there, 3-and-2, the bases loaded, two runs behind
and somebody begins yelling out. You can't stop concentrating on
what you're doing.''
   In Everett, Bush used an interview with newspaper and broadcast
correspondents to urge both side in the race not to disrupt the
campaign.
   ``I'd like to use this forum right here to appeal to my
supporters and his to at least let people speak without harassing.
But when it happens you don't need to get all uptight about it and
act like you're being put upon because this is the way it works at
this level of politics,'' Bush said.
   On Air Force Two, carrying him to Portland from Los Angeles,
Bush accused Dukakis of running a negative campaign.
   ``He has to tear down. He has to make everything negative to be
elected. I don't have to be responding to him.''
   Bush said Dukakis' contention Tuesday that the Reagan
administration has been anti-union was a ``stupid charge.''
   Even though polls show that Bush has largely erased Dukakis'
once-large lead, Bush said, ``I'm campaigning as the underdog.
Being even is like being the underdog as far as I'm concerned.''
   Bush was next flying to Louisville, Ky, to make a speech
Wednesday before the American Legion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
