<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-SAfrica     09-06 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-SAfrica,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secretary-General To Visit South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar has accepted an invitation from President P.W. Botha to
visit South Africa, the United Nations said Tuesday.
   ``A mutually convenient time for the visit is being discussed,''
said U.N. spokeswoman Nadia Younes. ``When the visit materializes,
the secretary-general will use the opportunity to visit certain
other countries in the region.''
   Botha extended the invitation Aug. 1.
   The U.N. Security Council frequently condemns South Africa
because of its system of apartheid, under which the nation's 5
million whites control the country and the 26 million blacks have
no vote in national affairs.
   The announcement comes as South Africa is discussing plans for
withdrawal from neighboring South-West Africa, also known as
Namibia, in conjunction with Cuba's withdrawing its troops from
Angola.
   South Africa has withdrawn its troops from southern Angola,
where they had been supporting the guerrillas of the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola in UNITA's fight against
Angola's Marxist government.
   South Africa has said it will withdraw its troops from Namibia
on Nov. 1 as a first step of a Security Council plan for Namibia's
independence.
   Under the council plan, Namibia would achieve independence in
one year.
   A major stumbling block is South African insistence that the
Cubans leave Angola as quickly as South Africa withdraws from
Namibia.
   A new round of peace talks among South Africa, Cuba, Angola and
U.S. mediators is to be held this week in Brazzaville, Congo.
</TEXT>
