<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Non-Aligned     09-06 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Non-Aligned,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Non-Aligned Have Gloomy View of World Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, CYPRUS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ministers of nations that profess
non-alignment welcomed the world's improved political climate, but
were less optimistic Tuesday about its economic prospects.
   ``The international crisis still persists and a number of
economic and financial problems remain unresolved with prospects of
progress gloomy,'' spokesman Nicos Agathocleous said.
   A draft statement on the international economy will be presented
for approval to the four-day ministers' conference, which President
George Vassiliou of Cyprus will open Wednesday.
   Agathocleous said the draft statement emphasized that, though
there are political developments, particularly between the two
superpowers, offering new possibilities of strengthening
international cooperation, regrettably the same is not true about
the world economic situation.''
   A copy obtained by The Associated Press deals in detail with 30
issues, ranging from establishment of a new economic order to
foreign debt, world hunger, relations between rich and poor nations
and global economic cooperation.
   The draft ``expresses profound concern'' about lack of progress
on almost all issues covered.
   It says problems in the world economy and links between nations
make it ``all the more urgent that both the developed and the
developing countries engage in construtive dialogue.''
   This should be ``aimed at finding common solutions to the
problems currently confronting the international economy, including
the reform of the international monetary, financial and trading
systems in the interest of both the developed and the developing
countries,'' the draft declares.
   Another committee is considering a statement on 39 international
political issues, with emphasis on the Palestinian and South
African problems.
   Agathocleous said the 60-page political document, prepared by
Cyprus as the host country, is much shorter than drafts submitted
to previous conferences. Delegations from 92 out of non-aligned
movement's 101 members are to attend the four-day meting, including
70 foreign ministers.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization, which seeks to turn
sympathy for the 9-month-old Palestinian uprising in the
Israeli-occupied lands to its political advantage, is expected to
win wide support and possibly financial backing.
   That would give a significant boost to PLO chairman Yasser
Arafat's effort to form a provisional government for an independent
Palestinian state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
