<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Reagan 2ndLd-Writethru a0717 09-06 0875</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0717,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Assails Democrats' `Disneyland Defense Policy'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 21st graf pvs, bgng: ``Today I ...'' to
UPDATE with audience reaction, demonstrators.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan accused the Democratic
White House ticket Tuesday of harboring ``a Disneyland defense
policy'' that would strip the nation of its military strength and
threaten the advances he has made in arms control.
   Acting as George Bush's chief surrogate on the campaign trail,
Reagan used some of his harshest rhetoric in weeks to lambast the
vice president's opponents in an address to the 70th national
convention of the American Legion.
   The president entered the post-Labor Day election fray during a
stop en route to Washington following a three-week California
vacation.
   Reagan never mentioned Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis by name, but he made clear he thinks the Massachusetts
governor embodies the ``liberal ideology of decline and retreat''
and leads a party that has shown ``remarkable passivity'' and
``unbelievable indecision'' in defense matters while it controlled
the White House.
   In doing so, the president attempted to paint Dukakis as
inexperienced in world and military affairs, while hoping to woo
into Bush's corner those conservative Democrats who twice had voted
for his own ``peace through strength'' stand.
   Using a comic-book analogy to make his point, Reagan quipped,
``When it comes to defense, the liberal agenda hides behind heroic
rhetoric. But this liberal agenda is no Superman; it's no Clark
Kent; it's Jimmy Olson trying to impress his date.''
   He charged the Democrats with promoting a ``hit list'' of
cancellations and delays for the MX missile, the B-1 bomber, the
Trident submarine missile and two proposed carrier battle groups
for the Navy.
   ``To that they've added nearly every major new weapons system to
become prominent on the scene since the last liberal administration
went to its reward, including the Midgetman missile, the Stealth
bomber and our Strategic Defense Initiative,'' Reagan said.
   Dukakis, however, has said he supports the advanced D-5 Trident
missile and continued development of the Stealth bomber, so-called
because of its ability to escape radar detection.
   The president accused the Democrats of planning to start ``a
unilateral U.S. moratorium on underground nuclear testing and a ban
on flight testing of missiles.''
   Reagan said that while Bush's opponents have praised him for
reaching a treaty with the Soviets banning intermediate-range
nuclear weapons in Europe, they also ``opposed deploying the
missiles that made that treaty possible ....''
   ``They want to conclude more arms reduction treaties, but would
cancel or delay the weapons systems on which successful
negotiations will depend. ... They profess their devotion to NATO
but would diminish the role of the very nuclear forces that NATO
needs to deter the Soviets. Does that make any sense as military
strategy?'' Reagan asked.
   ``Yes, it comes down to this: After eight hard years of
rebuilding America's strength, do we really want to return to a
Disneyland defense policy _ with Mickey Mouse treatment of our men
and women in uniform, Goofy strategic plans and Donald Duck-like
lectures telling us that whatever goes wrong is our own
blankety-blank fault?'' Reagan asked.
   Reagan contended that even the Soviets might prefer his own
approach to that of any Democrat.
   ``Again and again around the world, our predecessors had shown
not the slightest grasp of the fundamentals of strategy and
national interest ... And it even came to be said that the Soviets
longed for strong, consistent leadership in the United States,
capable of making a deal and sticking to it,'' Reagan said.
   He derided Dukakis' proposals for boosting conventional forces,
which he has dubbed a ``conventional defense initiative,'' in
contrast to the president's anti-missile strategic defense program.
   Reagan contended a buildup of conventional forces is ``well
under way'' and that without the recent achievement of laser-guided
munitions, ``we would not have been able to stage our successful
strike against (Moammar) Gadhafi's Libya.''
   The president went on to boast how successful his policies have
been. ``And our reward is that from Afghanistan to the Persian Gulf
to Southern Africa, we are bringing peace to long-raging conflicts,
even as we frustrate Soviet aims,'' he contended.
   Reagan repeated his oft-used claim that he's ``not given up one
square inch of land to communism ... And yet today relations
between the United States and the Soviet Union are the best they've
been in decades.''
   He told his audience, composed of some 7,000 veterans and their
families, that he was proud of the military buildup he'd pledged to
achieve eight years ago.
   ``Today I stand before you to report, `Mission accomplished,'''
he said.
   The Legionnaires interrupted the president frequently with
applause. However, on the sidewalk outside the convention hall,
about two dozen demonstrators held up signs urging support for the
Equal Rights Amendment and opposing the president's policy of aid
to Nicaragua's Contra rebels.
   Before addressing the Legion, Reagan stopped briefing at
Nebraska's Hastings College, where he participated in dedication
ceremonies of a communications arts center.
   The center is named for the parents of public relations
executive Robert T. Gray, a former resident of Hastings and
long-time Reagan acquaintance who had served as the communications
director on the the president's 1980 White House campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
