<HEAD>Dukakis Drops In Poll In Neighboring Rhode Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate
Michael Dukakis' lead over Republican George Bush narrowed sharply
from May to August, according to results of a poll of potential
voters in Rhode Island released Tuesday.
   Most of the previous Dukakis supporters shifted to the undecided
column and Bush picked up little of that support, according to the
poll released by WJAR-TV and Alpha Research Associates Inc.
   Dukakis held a 49 percent lead to Bush's 32 percent when 509
registered voters were interviewed in August. But when those same
potential voters were interviewed in May, the governor of the
neighboring state of Massachusetts held a 58 percent lead to Bush's
31 percent, according to WJAR.
   At the same time, the percentage of those undecided increased
from 10 percent to 20 percent.
   The poll's margin of error was plus or minus 4.5 percentage
points.
</TEXT>
