<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Eastern     09-06 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Lawyers Await Court Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' unions will argue their case
against the carrier's elimination of 4,000 jobs in federal court
this month, but employees Tuesday began receiving pink slips.
   An Eastern spokeswoman said the post-Labor Day layoffs aren't as
dramatic as portrayed by union leaders. Karen Ceremsak said many
employees already have taken leaves of absences, early retirement
or quit.
   Attorneys for the Machinists union and Air Line Pilots
Association decided to first present their case against the layoffs
in the appellate court.
   The U.S. Court of Appeals in Washington on Tuesday told Eastern
to submit legal briefs on its position by Sept. 12. A union
response is due by Sept. 16, a reply from Eastern is due three days
later, and oral arguments in the case were scheduled for the
morning of Sept. 26, Ms. Ceremsak said.
   The same court last Friday night dissolved an order by U.S.
District Judge Barrington Parker in Washington, D.C. Parker had
allowed Eastern to cut 12 percent of its flights, including all
service for 14 cities, but not lay off the workers.
   The appellate court allowed Eastern to make the layoffs after
posting a $4.7 million bond to pay the employees if their jobs are
reinstated after the court holds a full hearing. The company says
the layoffs take effect Sept. 10.
   Charles Bryan, president of Eastern's Machinists union, has
blasted the timing of the layoffs.
   ``It is typical of (Texas Air Chairman) Frank Lorenzo's style,''
Bryan said. ``It's tragic for the employees to be faced with this
kind of uncertainty on Labor Day and at the start of the school
year.''
   But Ceremsak said, ``There's no good time for a furlough. We had
previously announced the furloughs July 22. It was the unions'
court action that delayed them.''
   She said of 1,000 flight attendant positions eliminated, nearly
400 flight attendants had taken leaves of absences that would last
from one to six months, about 100 had taken early retirement or
quit, and some 530 were furloughed.
   Of the 4,000 positions eliminated, 1,500 were non-union
employees including management and clerical workers. Some 1,000
Machinists workers, which include mechanics, baggage handlers and
ramp agents, will be laid off. Some of those workers will take
early retirement, Eastern officials expected.
   The layoffs also called for elimination of 500 pilots'
positions, but ALPA spokesman Ron Cole said no pilot layoffs were
expected because of tremendous backlogs of vacation time.
   The Miami-based carrier has said cutting labor costs is
necessary to make the company profitable again, but unions have
criticized the idea that scaling back will make the airline more
money.
   Eastern officials say they want to concentrate on their
traditionally strong Northeastern markets. But the unions contend
that Texas Air Corp., Eastern's parent company, is stripping the
Miami-based carrier's assets in favor of its non-union sister
carrier, Continental Airlines.
</TEXT>
