<1ST_LINE>r a AM-YonkersDeseg 2ndLd-Writethru a0665 09-06 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yonkers Deseg, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0665,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Efforts Continue To End Housing Impasse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 2nd graf pvs, `Mayor Nicholas ...,' to
UPDATE with mayor's comments on possibility of settlement; ADDS 4
grafs on city's ``doomsday'' budget.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials paid a $192,000 fine Tuesday
and, faced with million-dollar fines by the end of the week,
pressed their efforts to end an impasse over court-ordered housing
desegregation.
   Mayor Nicholas Wasicsko told reporters it was possible that at
least one of the four city councilmen blocking the housing plan may
be near backing down.
   But later he said the prospects for a quick settlement did not
appear good.
   ``I'm sorry to report that there hasn't been any significant
movement,'' he said. ``The court is standing firm but the
councilmen say they want some concessions before they comply. The
two sides are considerably far apart.''
   Wasicsko said Councilmen Nicholas Longo and Peter Chema met with
him and the city manager for 7{ hours Monday talking about services
that would have to be cut to meet mounting fines.
   He noted that Chema represents an area of the city ``that is
going to feel the brunt of the service cuts and tax increases very
acutely, and yet that is an area where no housing is to be built.''
It is the proposed placement of subsidized housing in middle-class
areas that fueled opposition to the plan.
   No meetings were scheduled Tuesday, but key figures in the
crisis of the state's fourth-largest city were in touch by
telephone.
   The mayor said he was in contact most of the day with City
Council members, with the federal judge in the case and aides to
Gov. Mario Cuomo in Albany.
   No breakthrough was reported from Monday's meetings.
   According to city Corporation Counsel Paul Pickelle, U.S.
District Judge Leonard Sand had said that if the City Council
approved a housing plan Tuesday, he would forgive the $192,000 in
fines accumulated over the weekend.
   Pickelle said there was ``a real financial incentive to reach a
compromise today.''
   But Yonkers spokesman Eric Schoen said 12 hours notice is
required before a legal meeting, and none was scheduled as of
Tuesday morning.
   At issue is Sand's order that the council approve measures to
promote the construction of 800 units of subsidized housing.
   Sand ruled in 1985 that the city was guilty of decades of
intentional segregation of its schools and public housing.
   The schools were desegregated under a plan approved by Sand, and
the City Council agreed in January to develop 1,000 units of
housing.
   But under pressure from people who don't want subsidized housing
in their middle-class neighborhoods, four councilmen recanted and
vowed to block the plan from going forward.
   Sand levied escalating fines against the city _ $100 for the
first day and doubling every day after that. He also fined the
recalcitrant councilmen.
   The penalties were stayed pending appeal. Last week, the U.S.
Supreme Court reinstated the fines against the city but continued
the stay against any punishment of the councilmen.
   If the fines continue mounting through the week, Yonkers would
owe $204,800 Wednesday. By Friday, the fines would reach $1 million
a day; the city would be bankrupt by Nov. 12, according to city
officials.
   Meanwhile Tuesday, the city announced details of a ``doomsday
budget'' made necessary by the fines.
   The plan forsees a gradual reduction in city services, such as
garbage collection, park maintenance and programs for senior
citizens, youths and the handicapped. Cuts would continue until
Thanksgiving, when all fire and police personnel would have been
laid off, garbage collection would end and the city would cease to
function.
   The mayor said that although formal cuts had not begun, 25
percent of Yonkers' scheduled garbage pickups were canceled Tuesday
because of a lack of diesel fuel as the city limits fuel purchases.
   ``The garbage is piling up today, the libraries will be closed
next week,'' the mayor said. ``It may take deep cuts in city
services to get the people of Yonkers to tell their councilmen that
they want this matter settled.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
