<HEAD>Two Americans, Liberian Charged with Treason</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to CORRECT defendant's name to Curtis
Elmer Williams, sted William Elmer Curtis, and UPDATE with comment
from his wife; PICKS up 5th graf pvs: Five members...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MONROVIA, Liberia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Liberia has charged two Americans with
treason for allegedly plotting to overthrow the government and kill
President Samuel K. Doe. One of the defendants is a former U.S.
Army sergeant.
   An indictment was returned Monday against the ex-serviceman,
James Henry Bush, 40, of Baltimore, and Curtis Elmer Williams, 45,
of Jersey City, N.J..
   Also charged in the indictment was Mike Jackson, a Liberian who
lived in exile in neighboring Ivory Coast until his arrest in July.
   The three are charged with illegally entering Liberia in July
with the intent of staging a coup and killing Doe.
   Williams' wife, Gwendolyn, said her husband was in the business
of importing cement to Liberia and planned no wrongdoing when he
traveled to the country.
   ``I feel that he's innocent because when he left here, he left
on business,'' Mrs. Williams, 30, told The Associated Press in a
telephone interview from her home in Jersey City. ``They happened
to be in the wrong place at the wrong time.''
   Williams' name was given as William Elmer Curtis, but Mrs.
Williams said that was an error.
   Five members of the purported coup plot were killed in a July 13
clash with Liberian security men, including Liberian Maj. Gen. J.
Nicholas Podier, Doe's former deputy and the plot's reported
mastermind, the indictment says.
   The document identifies the others killed as ex-soldier Humphrey
Moore and John Seekie, both Liberians. The indictment gave no
details on Seekie and said the other two dead men have not been
identified.
   The government said the coup plotters entered Liberia from the
Ivory Coast on July 10 near the village of Gbolay.
   They reportedly hid for three days in a forest, but were
discovered by security forces on July 13 and a firefight ensued.
   ``The three defendants were overpowered while Podier, Moore and
John Seekie and two others presently unknown were killed as a
result of the gunfire,'' the indictment said.
   Liberia was established in 1847 by former American slaves.
   Doe, then an army master sergeant, took power in an April 12,
1980 coup, overthrowing the government of William Tolbert and
killing the civilian leader.
</TEXT>
