<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoviceDriver     09-06 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Novice Driver,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Acquits Novice Driver In Traffic Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELYRIA, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Tuesday acquitted a teen-ager who
was in a fatal car accident during a driver education course and
criticized her instruction, which included the showing of a Richard
Pryor movie.
   Lorain County Juvenile Court Judge Henry Webber said Michelle
Moore, 18, of Elyria was innocent of vehicular homicide. He said
she was poorly trained and did not receive proper instruction at
the time of the accident.
   Miss Moore was 17 at the time of the Jan. 23 accident that
killed Donald Mussey, 75, of Elyria. She was taking a class from
the Pro Driving School of Elyria.
   She was in tears when the verdict was announced and hugged her
parents, Oliver and Arlene. ``We've been living with this for nine
months,'' Oliver Moore said. ``I'm so relieved it's hard to have
any words to say.''
   In his decision, Webber said, ``I find it sad that young people
paying good money to learn to drive would get to see a movie such
as `Jo Jo Dancer, (Your Life is Calling)' instead of instruction on
driving.''
   The judge said Ms. Moore hadn't been prepared to drive in poor
road conditions when her driver's education car slid on a snowy
road and crossed into the opposite lane, striking the car in which
Mussey was riding.
   Miss Moore had testified during her trial last month that the
movie was shown during her first driver education class. The movie
was inspired by the comedian's life, particularly events that
followed a 1980 incident in which he set himself on fire while
smoking cocaine.
   Classroom instructor James Myrick testified during the trial
that about 15 minutes of the Pryor movie was shown, but Miss Moore
said she saw about 45 minutes of the film before being pulled out
of class to practice maneuverability skills in a parking lot.
   Witnesses for Pro Driving School never explained why the movie
was shown.
   Paul St. Marie, the teen-ager's attorney, said the movie had no
place in a drivers' training class. ``It has no redeeming value
whatsoever as far as safe driving is concerned,'' he said. ``It was
clearly meant as entertainment.''
   Pro Driving School referred a call to attorney Gerald Smith of
Elyria, who said the accident wasn't the school's fault.
   ``You're going to have to learn to drive, and you're going to
have to do it on the highway,'' Smith said. ``So it's not a matter
of inadequate training.''
   Lorain County Prosecutor Greg White said he would review the
trial transcript and evidence to determine whether the driver's
education school or instructor would be criminally liable in
Mussey's death.
</TEXT>
