<1ST_LINE>u i AM-IRAInquest 1stLd-Writethru   09-06 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IRA Inquest, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0677,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Policeman Testifies IRA Guerrillas Were Shot 8 Times Each</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Critics of...' to CORRECT name of band to
Royal Anglian Regiment, sted Anglican; picks up 6th graf pvs: The
police...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three unarmed IRA guerrillas who were killed by
British soldiers in Gibraltar six months ago were shot at least
eight times each, a police photographer testified at an inquest
Tuesday.
   The testimony came at the opening of the inquest, which will
determine whether the deaths can be legally justified.
   Coroner Felix Pizzarello began the session by denying a motion
to eliminate the 11-member jury from the inquest on the grounds
that publicity about the killings had favored the British soldiers
who fired on the guerrillas.
   Mairead Farrell, Sean Savage and Daniel McCann, who the IRA has
admitted were on a mission at the time of their deaths, were shot
and killed by seven soldiers near a gas station in the British
colony of Gibraltar on March 6.
   Critics of British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
claim the killings were part of an unofficial ``shoot-to-kill''
policy against members of the Irish Republican Army. British
authorities said the three men were planning a car bomb attack at
the site where the Royal Anglian Regiment band accompanies a weekly
changing of the guard ceremony.
   The police photographer who testified Tuesday, Brian Reyes, said
that Farrell, Savage and McMann were each shot at least eight
times. He identified black-and-white photographs he took showing
the bullet entry and exit wounds.
   Reyes said Savage was hit with bullets in the head, hand, arms,
side and chest; McCann in the head, torso, thigh, stomach and
chest; and Farrell in the face, side and chest just below the heart.
   Patrick McGrory, a Belfast lawyer representing the families of
the dead, argued that the jurors should not participate in the
hearings because they would be influenced by British press coverage
of the shootings. He said reports favored the members of the
Special Air Service unit who did the shooting.
   The day after the slayings, British Foreign Secretary Sir
Geoffrey Howe told Parliament in London that the three IRA suspects
were unarmed.
   McGrory is expected to question witnesses who say the three men
were given no chance to surrender before the soldiers shot them.
   After the shooting, police found a rented car parked near the
area where the ceremony of the guards took place. Authorities said
they first believed it had been rigged as a car bomb. A second
rented car containing timing devices and wire was found on the
Spanish side of the border from Gibraltar.
   Two days after the shootings, Spanish police found a third car
packed with explosives in a garage in Marbella on the Spanish coast.
   If the inquest's jury decides the British soldiers acted in an
unlawful manner, the soldiers may be criminally indicted under
British law.
   Michael Hucker, who represents the soldiers referred to only as
``soldiers A to G,'' said his clients were prepared to testify at
the hearing, but only if reporters and the public are excluded and
their voices electronically altered. Pizzarello said the inquest,
which is taking place in the Supreme Court building, would last
about four weeks.
   The overwhelmingly Roman Catholic IRA seeks to oust British
troops from mainly Protestant Northern Ireland and to unite it with
the predominantly Catholic Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
