<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 2209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Mail     09-06 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Mail,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Escalating Postal Strike Puts More Than Letters in a Bind</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unemployment checks, last-minute college
placements and letters to the editor disappeared into mountains of
unsorted mail Tuesday as Britain's postal strike escalated.
   With the nationwide strike in its seventh day, 80 million
letters and parcels were held up in darkened post offices.
Deliveries in London were at a virtual halt. All 11,000 mailboxes
in the capital were sealed.
   Private couriers rejoiced, but postal customers scrambled to
find alternative ways to deliver their messages, money or bills.
   The government hired a private courier company to deliver
unemployment checks.
   The Times, Daily Telegraph and Independent invited readers to
send letters to the editor by Fax machine.
   ``Any system which relies on the post must be in difficulties at
a time like this,'' said Mike Hiscock, head of administration at
the Universities Central Council on Admissions.
   The council, an intermediary between universities and their
applicants, set up telephone banks to help match students rejected
elsewhere with schools that had openings.
   Hiscock estimated up to one-third of the annual 15,000
last-minute applications were caught in the backlog.
   The dispute over regional pay differences and the use of
temporary workers shut down 60 of the country's 80 main sorting
offices by Tuesday, said Sally Williams, a post office spokeswoman.
   The service has 180,000 workers.
   Ms. Williams said that 70,000 workers involved in sorting and
delivery stayed away, up from 48,000 Monday.
   About 15 million letters, compared with a daily 51 million, were
being delivered, she said. Earlier estimates said 100 million items
were backlogged, but Ms. Williams put the figure at 80 million.
   Talks on renewing negotiations continued between the Post Office
and the Union of Communication Workers but no details were
disclosed.
   TNT Express U.K., which claims to be Britain's largest courier,
said it has experienced a 400 percent increase in business since
the strike began Wednesday.
   Patience wore thin among postal consumers.
   ``Business has increased, but in some respects it's holding us
back,'' said Alan Dickinson, sales manager at a London store. ``We
can't complete deliveries until we get confirmation. We also can't
get invoices out, so we can't get paid.''
   ``Many firms are experiencing considerable disruption,
frustration and annoyance through this unnecessary strike,'' said
Ron Taylor, director general of the Association of British Chambers
of Commerce, which represents 65,000 businesses.
   A statement issued by three large mail order and direct
marketing groups demanded that the strike end.
</TEXT>
