<2ND_LINE>AM-Pontiac Fire,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Firefighter Killed, Three Hurt Battling Blaze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A burning building collapsed on
firefighters battling a suspicious fire Tuesday, killing one and
injuring three others, authorities said.
   The fire in two adjoining buildings broke out at 2:12 p.m.,
sending dense smoke throughout the downtown area for several hours.
One of the buildings was vacant and the other housed a clothing
store.
   It was the second major fire in the area in five days. On
Thursday, a fire destroyed three downtown buildings.
   The roof and second floor of one of the buildings collapsed at
4:30 p.m., trapping three firefighters. Two were removed within 20
minutes, but rescuers with power saws worked more than an hour to
reach the third.
   Firefighter Tracy Williamson, 23, was pronounced dead at Pontiac
Osteopathic Hospital, said Dr. Bob Aranosian, director of the
hospital's Emergency Trauma Center.
   Two firefighters were treated for smoke inhalation, and a fourth
firefighter was in serious but stable condition, Aranosian said.
   The cause of the fire was undetermined, but ``at any time like
this it would be considered a suspicious fire,'' said Assistant
Fire Chief Ronald Rayner.
