<1ST_LINE>r i AM-DutchPolitics     09-06 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dutch Politics,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Resigns Over Passport Snafu</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Willem van
Eekelen announced his resignation Tuesday after allegations that he
bungled the introduction of a new passport system.
   ``I have asked her majesty the queen (Beatrix) to allow me to
resign,'' van Eekelen told Parliament. His action marked the first
such resignation from Premier Ruud Lubbers' coalition government of
centrist Christian Democrats and rightist Liberals since it came to
power in 1982.
   Van Eekelen's decision came after a parliamentary inquiry
committee said earlier this month that he had mismanaged the
passport project during his 1982-1986 tenure as a deputy foreign
minister.
   ``A minister of defense should defend himself to the utmost but
also limit casualties,'' he told Parliament.
   There was no immediate indication who would succeed the
57-year-old defense minister.
   The overhaul of the passport system has been beset by
controversy since its announcement in 1982. The new document was
supposed to be more forgery proof than the current passport and
bring this nation into line with passport requirements set by the
European Economic Community.
   The parliamentary report said van Eekelen had granted the
documents to develop and produce new passports to a newly formed
conglomerate without seriously considering rival bids from other
companies.
   It contained no charges of corruption against van Eekelen who
was appointed defense minister after the 1986 general elections.
</TEXT>
