<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SniperShootings 2ndLd-Writethru a0640 09-06 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sniper Shootings, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0640,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Capture Sniper, Two Children Found Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with suspect dying at hospital,
14 officers injured, treated and released, and to show that
children shot in head and found covered with blankets and pillows;
picks up 4th graf pvs `First Deputy...; DELETES outdated grafs
11-12: `Three times ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police who had been held at bay for nine hours
Tuesday by a rain of shotgun pellets returned fire and mortally
wounded the sniper through his door, then found his two children
dead in their high-rise apartment.
   The siege left 14 officers injured, but all were treated and
released, officials at two hospitals said.
   Cho Mun Chu, 45, who was removed from his city-subsidized Lower
East Side apartment on a stretcher, died later at Bellevue
Hospital, said Sgt. John Clifford, a police spokesman.
   The bodies of 8-year-old Helen Chu and her 9-year-old brother
Warren Chu, were found with wounds to the head, covered with
blankets and pillows in the hallway of apartment, police said.
   They were shot with what was believed to be a long-barrel
shotgun filled with bird shot, said police spokesman Lt. Steven
Davis.
   The girl's death was believed to be the first time in the
15-year history of the elite police Hostage Negotiating Unit that a
hostage was lost during negotiations, said another police
spokesman, Sgt. Raymond O'Donnell.
   Police believe the boy was already dead when they arrived, but
the girl was seen alive by a police camara, Commissioner Benjamin
Ward said.
   Chu's wife, Hui Choy Chu, who also used the name Angela, was
believed to be in Taiwan, said O'Donnell.
   Ward said police were forced to shoot Chu in self-defense after
removing the door to his 11th-floor apartment from its hinges in an
attempt to bring the girl to safety.
   ``We waited until he fired point-blank _ one captain was hit,
four lieutenants were hit, and one police officer was hit by
pellets, and he was now firing point blank at the door,'' the
commissioner said.
   The officers returned two shots, hitting Chu twice in the chest,
Ward said.
   First Deputy Police Commissioner Richard Condon said earlier
that ``a rain of pellets'' descended on officers who arrived about
6 a.m. to investigate a report of shots fired.
   Scores of police then cordoned off a four-block area around the
building. The FDR Drive, a main highway along the East River into
Manhattan, was closed in both directions near the Brooklyn Bridge,
creating enormous traffic jams.
   For about a half-hour as the incident ended shortly after 3
p.m., the East River was closed to marine traffic between the
Williamsburg and Brooklyn bridges, said a Coast Guard spokesman,
Petty Officer Randy Midgett.
   Police attempts to communicate with the suspected sniper were
unsuccessful until a Cantonese-speaking detective was brought in to
act as interpreter.
   Condon said negotiations were difficult because the interpreter
and suspect were shouting through a door, which was locked and
barricaded by furniture.
   Police had said the man had made no threats against his family,
and in the course of negotiations had made no demands.
   ``He seems to have some kind of financial problems and family
problems and that seems to be what has set him off,'' Condon said.
   Victoria Parker, who lives on the 18th floor of the building,
said the man recently moved in and quickly gained a reputation for
having a bad temper. ``He gets into it with management and the
tenants,'' she said.
   Davis said Housing Authority police had been called to the
25-story building before because of problems with the man.
</TEXT>
