<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Space 6thLd-Writethru a0751 09-06 0972</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Space, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0751,752,755,1003</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: COMBINES urgent series, a0751, a0752, a0755, and restores
copy in a0742; CORRECTS spelling of Mohmand, adds details, edits to
conform and TRIM. Adds byline, LaserPhoto number.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY81</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two cosmonauts returned safely to Earth early
Wednesday after their descent was aborted twice because of a system
malfunction and their food and oxygen began to run out, the
official Soviet news agency reported.
   Tass reported that Abdul Ahad Mohmand, the first Afghan in
space, and his Soviet crewmate, Vladimir Lyakhov, touched down at
4:50 a.m. Moscow time (8:50 p.m. EDT Tuesday) in Soviet Central
Asia.
   ``Both cosmonauts feel fine after the landing,'' Tass said.
   The agency said their Soyuz TM-5 space capsule landed 99 miles
southeast of Dzhezkazgan, a town on the steppes of the republic of
Kazakhstan in Soviet Central Asia. The town is about 1,365 miles
southeast of Moscow.
   Soviet news reports earlier had said neither cosmonaut was in
immediate danger but that the situation soon could become critical.
   ``Accident! The engine worked 60 seconds and shut off. A
violation of the stabilization regime,'' Lyakhov told mission
control in an exchange reported by the government newspaper
Izvestia.
   Lyakhov, 47, is a military pilot who has flown in space twice
before, and Mohmand, 29, is an Afghan air force pilot.
   Lyakhov, Mohmand and Soviet doctor Valery Polyakov were launched
into space Aug. 29 and boarded the orbiting Mir space station two
days later. Polyakov remained aboard, but Lyakhov and Mohmand
undocked the Soyuz at 2:55 a.m. Moscow time (6:55 p.m. Monday EDT)
for the trip home.
   Polyakov stayed on the Mir to monitor the health of two other
cosmonauts who have been in space for more than eight months.
   James Oberg, a U.S. expert on the Soviet space program who is
familiar with the Soyuz TM-5 design, had said Tuesday that time was
running out.
   ``If they cannot make the burn tonight to push them back into
the atmosphere, they will probably only live another 24 to 48 hours
before the carbon dioxide building in the capsule will kill them,''
Oberg said in an interview with The Associated Press in Houston.
   Officials of the U.S. National Aeronautics and Space
Administration said NASA volunteered help but the Soviets declined,
saying ``they had a technical problem, but that no assistance was
needed.''
   The North American Aerospace Defense Command in Colorado said
the Soyuz had split into at least two parts, a normal procedure for
re-entry.
   ``We are tracking two pieces associated with TM-5,'' said Maj.
Alex Mondragon, a NORAD spokesman. The capsule was in an orbit 226
miles by 206 miles and the ship's living compartment was circling
Earth 234 miles at the highest point and 155 miles at the lowest.
   The Soyuz capsule is designed for trips to and from space, not
for long flights.
   Izvestia and Tass earlier reported that life support systems on
the globe-shaped capsule were designed to last two days, meaning
that had the cosmonauts not been able to descend, they would have
been in jeopardy by Thursday morning.
   According to the Soviet space official, however, the cosmonauts
could have stretched supplies of oxygen, water and food for up to a
week. After that the capsule would be like ``a lone boat in the
ocean,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He did not explain how the air supply could be extended.
   The capsule would have landed in China had the descent not been
aborted. The space official said contingency landing sites in
general were not desirable because no proper ground crews would be
there.
   An Izvestia article under the headline ``Anxious Hours in
Space'' reported this exchange between mission control and the
cosmonauts:
   ``How are things with food?'' a mission controller asked.
   ``There is no food,'' said Lyakhov.
   ``But in the accident reserves?'' the controller asked.
   ``There is some, but why touch it? We will endure,'' Lyakhov
said.
   Tass said the cosmonauts ``are in for difficult hours in orbit
until the designated time of landing.''
   Soviet television showed black-and-white videotape taken from
the Soyuz in which the Mir station, whose extended solar panels
gave it the shape of a T, grew steadily smaller as the capsule
pulled away.
   Television commentator Alexander Tikhomirov said later, in a
somber voice:
   ``We are already used to everything going smoothly in space, and
some forget about the danger which space research entails. And here
this once more convinces us how complex a matter it is and what a
huge amount of abnormal situations awaits cosmonauts in orbit.''
   Trouble began soon after the Soyuz left its dock on the Mir.
   An engine used to slow the capsule for entering Earth's
atmosphere fired automatically while the vehicle was out of radio
contact with ground control, Izvestia said.
   When contact was restored, Lyakhov gave his report that the
engine stopped after 60 seconds, far short of the 230 seconds
needed to brake the capsule for a safe re-entry, Soviet media said.
   Controllers decided to delay another attempt for three hours,
Izvestia reported. During that time, scientists found that sunlight
had interfered with a sensor in an infrared guidance system and a
computer automatically terminated the engine burn.
   Seven minutes later, the sensor locked onto its correct target
and the guidance system worked properly. The engine fired again,
but because the on-board computer had not been reprogrammed the
capsule was sent on a trajectory for a landing in China, the
reports said.
   The cosmonauts stopped the engine manually after three seconds
and tried again, but that time the engine stopped after six seconds
and the decision was made to wait until Wednesday.
   Valery Ryumin, a cosmonaut and the mission chief, told Izvestia:
   ``Don't worry, nothing terrible has happened yet. The life
support system will last for two days.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
