<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 0707EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-HongKong-Airport Adv13   09-06 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hong Kong-Airport, Adv 13,0716</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs Sept. 13 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Jetliner Crash Heats up Debate on Hong Kong's Airport</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fatal crash landing of a Chinese jetliner
has fired up debate on replacing Hong Kong's airport, known for its
harrowing flight path that skims the rooftops of crowded Kowloon
peninsula.
   The British-built Trident jetliner skidded off Hong Kong
International Airport's sole runway into the sea in a torrential
downpour Aug. 31, killing seven people in Hong Kong's worst air
accident in 21 years.
   The accident came at a time when the British colony is
considering construction of a new airport away from congested urban
areas. The government is funding three surveys to evaluate various
proposals.
   The colony's governor, Sir David Wilson, said immediately
following the crash that it should have no bearing on the future of
the existing airport, which is known as Kai Tak.
   The English-language South China Morning Post newspaper agreed,
but noted in an editorial that ``there is no doubt that the crash
will focus renewed attention on the apparently never-ending saga of
Hong Kong's need for expanded aviation facilities.''
   Kai Tak is squeezed between the sea and the impossibly crowded
neighborhoods of Kowloon, one of the colony's major urban areas.
The runway juts into Hong Kong's famed harbor and is surrounded on
three sides by water.
   Use of the airport has expanded rapidly. Last year, 12.7 million
passengers were handled, an increase of 20 percent from the year
before and nearly 50 percent from 1982. Movement of aircraft
reached 73,370 planes in 1986, an increase of 13.2 percent from the
previous year.
   ``The single runway, required to handle an aircraft every 180
seconds during peak hours, has exhausted its possibilities,'' the
Morning Post said. The government says the runway can handle up to
30 planes an hour.
   Victor Sit, a University of Hong Kong professor who studies
urban problems, expressed concern that the airport's enviable
safety record may run into trouble as traffic increases.
   ``We've been lucky,'' he said. ``So far, the accidents all
happened on the harbor side of the airport, not on the landward
side.'' Although the Chinese jetliner crashed while approaching the
runway from the harbor, flights typically make their final approach
over Kowloon.
   ``The approach of the airport obviously requires very careful
maneuvering by the pilots concerned and very precise control ... by
the airport,'' Sit said. Passengers rarely forget the final moments
before touchdown when planes come breathtakingly close to Kowloon's
buildings.
   Kai Tak critics note the airport becomes paralyzed whenever the
runway is disrupted, cutting the colony's main transportation link
to the outside world. The Chinese jetliner crash stopped traffic
for about six hours.
   They also argue that the airport's urban location makes life
miserable for many local residents. A recent study estimated 1
million people suffer unacceptable noise from Kai Tak.
   Government officials have been considering replacement
possibilities for years and are actively looking at two sites near
outlying Lantau Island for a new airport. A final decision has been
promised by the end of 1989.
   The most ambitious proposal is from a group led by Hopewell
Holdings Ltd. The massive $3.08 billion-plan would include an
airport, seaport, road and railway complex on reclaimed land off
the island's east coast near Hong Kong island.
   The tiny Portuguese territory of Macao, 40 miles southwest of
Hong Kong, also has proposed building its own international airport.
   And China, which regains sovereignty over Hong Kong in 1997,
plans to construct an airport in its Shenzhen special economic zone
just over the Hong Kong border. Sit said that airport would only
``help to ease our trouble a little bit.''
   He believes Kai Tak will reach capacity in three to five years,
around the time construction could be starting on a new airport,
unless the government bows to pressure to act faster.
   ``That would mean they only start construction when the airport
itself has exceeded capacity,'' Sit said. ``It would be fairly
difficult for Hong Kong to operate as an international financial
trading and tourist center, unless we have some other arrangement.'
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs Sept. 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880906-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 0708EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-HimalayanHealth Adv14   09-06 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Himalayan Health, Adv 14,0908</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs Sept. 14 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Mountainous Problems in Nepal's Quest for Better Health Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALAMBHU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oblivious to a pouring rain, Lokmaya
crouches beside a muddy rivulet and scrubs her children's clothes
with a bar of pink soap.
   Her two little girls, at her side, appear to be about 4 and 8
years old. But Lokmaya doesn't know their ages, or even her own.
   ``I don't keep track of such things,'' she says. But with a
proud smile, she adds that she also has a son and he is 6.
   Lokmaya gave birth to three other children but they did not
survive infancy. She doesn't know why and says her surviving
children are often sick with fevers.
   Health care is a battle of mountainous proportions in Nepal
where both man and nature are the enemy, creating what health
workers call ``the silent emergency.''
   An earthquake rumbled through the Himalayan mountains, foothills
and valleys Aug. 21, killing more than 700 people in Nepal and at
least 300 in neighboring India.
   However, Nepal's biggest killer is far less dramatic and strikes
every day. It is diarrhea, and it claims 45,000 lives a year,
according to figures compiled by the United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) and the Nepalese government. Nearly all the victims are
children.
   Eleven percent of all babies die before the age of a year. Two
out of three children under 5 suffer from malnutrition, further
decreasing their chances of avoiding _ or surviving _ diarrhea and
the six other most prevalent diseases: diphtheria, whooping cough,
tetanus, measles, tuberculosis and polio.
   ``Nearly 50 percent of the diseases could be controlled easily
if you could provide potable water to the people,'' said Shreebatsa
Prasad Shrestha, an undersecretary in the Ministry of Health.
   Nepal, the fabled kingdom in the sky, is a land of beauty and
mystery, luring adventurers to conquer the majestic heights of
Mount Everest, to search for the Abominable Snowman, to explore the
pagoda-like temples where Buddhism met Hinduism and spawned the
kind of architecture that belongs in fairy tales.
   It is a country where tourists are warned not to drink the
water, where Western embassies have their own doctors and are
poised to fly their citizens to Bangkok in Thailand, New York or
London for hospital treatment.
   The Nepalese have little choice but to drink the water, and only
25 percent of them get it from a tap or well, Shrestha said. The
rest fetch water from open streams where livestock wallow and
people bathe.
   The country has one doctor for every 26,000 people, in contrast
to one doctor per 5,000 people in India and one per 780 in the
United States.
   Lokmaya's village of Balambhu has better health care than most
in this nation of 17 million people. People can walk to the local
health post in a few minutes, and the village of 1,000 is less than
6 miles from Katmandu, the capital, where there are free doctors.
   In more remote areas, people must walk for days to reach a
health post, which may have up to four staffers: a midwife and as
many as three ``health assistants'' with first-aid kits.
   Even in Balambhu, the concept of water-borne diseases such as
diarrhea is rudimentary.
   Down the road from where Lokmaya was doing her laundry, women
washed their families' breakfast dishes, their children and
themselves in another tiny rivulet of water coursing through the
mud.
   A few yards away, a teen-age boy scrubbed a water buffalo. A
smaller boy wearing only a tattered brown shirt squatted nearby,
for the ground along the rivulet serves as a latrine.
   Plans for development in Nepal, where the per capita annual
income is $160 a year, anticipate that 18 percent of all homes will
have toilets by the year 2000, compared to an estimated 3 percent
now. Television, which started in Nepal only two years ago, has
already reached 13 percent of the people and is expected to reach
60 percent by the year 2000.
   Foreign health workers said they have found people quick to
learn health and hygiene precautions, once they understand why they
must change their habits.
   Joann Duffy, Katmandu director of Dooley Intermed, a New York
City-based foundation, said her staff is training Nepalese nurses
to conduct classes for menial workers in hospitals.
   ``We demonstrate how to sweep. We show them how to clean a
latrine. We show them how to dig a pit for trash. We show them how
to wash their hands,'' said Ms. Duffy, an infection control
practitioner from Torrance, Calif.
   The Nepalese terrain is harder to conquer. Many areas, even
those at lower altitudes, are far from roads that motor vehicles
can travel.
   Under a nationwide vaccination campaign aimed at combating
tuberculosis, measles and other diseases, UNICEF workers are hiking
up to four days to reach remote villages.
   The serum they carry in specially designed ``cold packs'' must
be kept below certain temperatures, and the packs can only maintain
that temperature for 48 hours, according to UNICEF's chief
representative in Katmandu, Lay Maung, a Burmese doctor.
   To maintain the correct temperature, relays of runners follow
them with blocks of ice to keep the serum cool.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs Sept. 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880906-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 0709EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-History adv11   09-06 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, adv11,0520</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 11</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, Sept. 11, the 255th day of 1988. There are 111
days left in the year. The Jewish New Year, Rosh Hashanah, begins
at sunset.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On Sept. 11, 1777, during the American Revolution, forces under
Gen. George Washington suffered defeat at the hands of the British
in the Battle of Brandywine near Wilmington, Del. Washington's
troops were forced back into Philadelphia, which fell to the
British.
   On this date:
   In 1789, Alexander Hamilton was appointed secretary of the
Treasury.
   In 1814, an American fleet scored a decisive victory over the
British in the Battle of Lake Champlain in the War of 1812.
   In 1850, the ``Swedish Nightingale'' _ Jenny Lind _ gave her
first concert in the United States, at Castle Garden in New York.
   In 1885, author D.H. Lawrence was born in Eastwood, England.
   In 1936, President Franklin D. Roosevelt dedicated Boulder Dam _
now known as Hoover Dam _ by pressing a key in Washington to signal
the startup of the dam's first hydroelectric generator in Nevada.
   In 1941, in Des Moines, aviation hero Charles A. Lindbergh
charged ``the British, the Jewish and the Roosevelt
administration'' were trying to involve the United States in World
War II.
   In 1944, President Franklin D. Roosevelt and British Prime
Minister Winston Churchill met in Canada at the second Quebec
Conference.
   In 1971, former Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev died of a heart
attack at the age of 77.
   In 1973, Chile's President, Salvador Allende, died in a violent
military coup that overthrew his government.
   In 1982, 46 people were killed in a U.S. Army helicopter crash
near Mannheim, West Germany.
   In 1985, Pete Rose of the Cincinnati Reds cracked career hit
number 4,192 off Eric Show of the San Diego Padres, eclipsing the
record held by Ty Cobb.
   Ten years ago: Georgi Markov, a Bulgarian defector, died at a
British hospital four days after he was stabbed by a man wielding a
poisoned umbrella tip. (Bulgarian authorities have denied their
agents killed Markov.)
   Five years ago: The State Department issued a revised transcript
of the monitored remarks of the Soviet pilot who shot down a Korean
jetliner Sept. 1. The transcript quoted the pilot as saying he had
fired ``cannon burst'' before shooting down the plane with 269
people aboard.
   One year ago: CBS anchorman Dan Rather, angered because coverage
of a tennis tournament had delayed the start of his 6:30 p.m.
newscast, walked off the set of ``The CBS Evening News,'' leaving
the network ``black'' for six minutes when the sports coverage
abruptly ended.
   Today's Birthdays: Former Philippines President Ferdinand Marcos
is 71. Football coach Tom Landry is 64. Actor Earl Holliman is 60.
Sen. Robert Packwood, R-Ore. is 56. Movie director Brian De Palma
(``The Untouchables'') is 48.
   Thought for Today: ``A bad cause requires many words.'' _ German
proverb.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sun Sept. 11</NOTE>
