<NOTE>$Adv12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday, Sept. 12</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, Sept. 12, the 256th day of 1988. There are 110
days left in the year. This is the Jewish New Year Rosh Hashanah.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On Sept. 12, 1609, English explorer Henry Hudson sailed into the
river that now bears his name.
   On this date:
   In 1814, the Battle of North Point was fought near Baltimore
during the War of 1812.
   In 1880, author and journalist H.L. Mencken was born in
Baltimore.
   In 1888, entertainer Maurice Chevalier was born in Paris.
   In 1913, Olympic legend Jesse Owens was born in Danville, Ala.
   In 1918, during World War I, U.S. forces led by Gen. John J.
Pershing launched an attack on the German-occupied St. Mihiel
salient north of Verdun, France.
   In 1938, in a speech in Nuremberg, Adolf Hitler demanded
self-determination for the Sudeten Germans in Czechoslovakia, a
demand that would lead to Nazi occupation of the Sudetenland.
   In 1943, during World War II, German paratroopers took Benito
Mussolini from the hotel where he was being held by the Italian
government.
   In 1953, Massachusetts Sen. John F. Kennedy married Jacqueline
Lee Bouvier in Newport, R.I.
   In 1960, Democratic presidential candidate John F. Kennedy
confronted the issue of his Roman Catholic faith by telling a
Protestant group in Houston, ``I do not speak for my church on
public matters, and the church does not speak for me.''
   In 1974, Emperor Haile Selassie was deposed by Ethiopia's
military, after ruling for 58 years.
   In 1977, South African black student leader Steven Biko died
while in police custody, triggering an international outcry.
   In 1986, the United States released Soviet physicist Gennadiy
Zakharov and the Soviet Union released American journalist Nicholas
Daniloff to the custody of their respective embassies.
   Ten years ago: During the Camp David summit, White House
spokesman Jody Powell reported President Jimmy Carter was making an
``even more intense effort'' to bridge differences between Egypt
and Israel. The situation comedy ``Taxi'' premiered on ABC
television.
   Five years ago: The Soviet Union vetoed a U.N. Security Council
resolution deploring the shooting-down of a Korean jetliner by a
Soviet jet fighter on Sept. 1.
   One year ago: Reports surfaced that Democratic presidential
candidate Joseph Biden had borrowed passages of a speech by British
Labor Party leader Neil Kinnock for one of his own campaign
speeches. (The Kinnock report, along with other damaging
revelations, prompted Biden to drop his White House bid.)
   Today's Birthdays: Actress Linda Gray is 48. Singer Maria
Muldaur is 45. Singer Barry White is 44.
   Thought for Today: ``If we would have new knowledge, we must get
a whole world of new questions.'' _ Susanne K. Langer, American
philosopher (1895-1985).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon Sept. 12</NOTE>
</DOC>
