<NOTE>For Release Thursday, Sept. 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Thursday, Sept. 15, the 259th day of 1988. There are
107 days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Twenty-five years ago, on Sept. 15, 1963, four children were
killed when a bomb went off during Sunday services at a black
Baptist church in Birmingham, Ala., that had been a rallying point
for civil rights demonstrations.
   On this date:
   In 1776, British forces occupied New York City during the
American Revolution.
   In 1789, the U.S. Department of Foreign Affairs was renamed the
Department of State.
   In 1821, independence was proclaimed for Costa Rica, Guatemala,
Honduras, Nicaragua and El Salvador.
   In 1857, William Howard Taft _ who served as president of the
United States and as chief justice _ was born in Cincinnati, Ohio.
   In 1887, the city of Philadelphia launched a three-day
celebration of the 100th anniversary of the Constitution of the
United States.
   In 1917, Russia was proclaimed a republic by Alexander Kerensky,
the head of the provisional government that came to power following
the abdication of Czar Nicholas II.
   In 1935, the Nuremberg Laws deprived German Jews of their
citizenship and made the swastika the official symbol of Nazi
Germany.
   In 1940, during the Battle of Britain in World War II, the tide
turned as Royal Air Force planes inflicted heavy losses against the
Luftwaffe.
   In 1950, during the Korean conflict, U.N. forces landed at
Inchon in the south and began their drive toward Seoul.
   In 1959, Soviet Premier Nikita S. Khrushchev arrived in the
United States to begin a 13-day visit.
   In 1982, Israeli forces began pouring into west Beirut following
the assassination of Lebanese president-elect Bashir Gemayel.
   In 1982, Iran's former foreign minister, Sadegh Ghotbzadeh, was
executed after he was convicted of plotting against the government.
   In 1982, the first issue of ``USA Today'' was published by
Gannett Co. Inc.
   
   Ten years ago: Muhammad Ali won a unanimous, 15-round decision
over World Boxing Association heavyweight champion Leon Spinks at
the Louisiana Superdome in New Orleans.
   Five years ago: Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin submitted
his formal resignation to President Chaim Herzog. The Senate joined
the House of Representatives in approving a resolution condemning
the Soviet Union for shooting down a Korean jetliner with 269
aboard.
   One year ago: On the opening day of his confirmation hearing,
Supreme Court nominee Robert Bork told members of the Senate
Judiciary Committee that his philosophy was ``neither liberal nor
conservative.''
   Today's Birthdays: Country music star Roy Acuff is 85.
Actor-director Jackie Cooper is 66. Comedian Norm Crosby is 61.
Former baseball player Gaylord Perry is 50. Actor-sportscaster
Merlin Olsen is 48. Actor Tommy Lee Jones is 42. Football
quarterback Dan Marino is 27. Britain's Prince Henry of Wales is 4.
   Thought for Today: ``Love, friendship, respect do not unite
people as much as a common hatred for something.'' _ Anton Chekhov,
Russian author and dramatist (1860-1904).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs Sept. 15</NOTE>
