<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv07   09-06 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 07 ,0712</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Wednesday, Sept. 7</NOTE>
<HEAD>To The Government: Butt Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As an authority on economic and business
productivity, C. Jackson Grayson Jr. watches in amazement as one
legislator after another thinks government has the answers.
   Having served in three administrations, Grayson knows how
limited are government's abilities to intervene in the marketplace
and correct its problems, specifically when they involve global
competitiveness.
   In that area, he says, there are important things that
government should not do, no matter how insistent and intense the
pressure. In keeping with that belief, he and associate Carla
O'Dell have issued some cautionary advice.
   Their views are in the form of a book titled, ``American
Business: A Two-Minute Warning,'' although it would take even the
most efficient and productive reader a lot longer than that to
digest their advice.
   Grayson, chairman of the American Productivity Center in
Houston, is well-grounded in his subject, having been President
Nixon's price commissioner, and a member of President Carter's
Commission on the Agenda for the 80s and President Reagan's
National Productivity Advisory Council.
   From such vantage points, says Grayson, he has observed growing
pressure on government to ``do something'' about America's
competitive posture, which is reflected in the balance of payments
deficit and other problems.
   Over the past five years, he says, there have been 112
recommendations for government action by 21 councils, commissions,
congressional hearings and study groups on productivity and
competitiveness.
   It is frightening, say Grayson and O'Dell, that the 99th
Congress had 108 committees and subcommittees in the Senate and 178
in the House, with 3,000 staffers ``feeling they must do something
to help American competitiveness.''
   Stating that such determination by Washington to do something
``keeps us awake at night,'' the authors name five things they feel
government must not do to ``help American competitiveness.''
   1. The single worst thing is to increase protection, say Grayson
and O'Dell. They say it invites reciprocity, lowers efficiency and
shrinks export-related jobs.
   Granting protection, they say, ``is like putting an industry on
a life-support system. It may prolong life for a while, but it
can't restore health.''
   2. Government should not establish industrial policies.
   Industrial policies are, in effect, attempts at centrally
directing the economy to specific national goals. Call it
``national planning'' and you might get an argument, but you would
also have material to defend yourself.
   Industrial policies have been resurrected under the labels of
``trade policies'' or ``competitiveness policies'' or ``living
standards acts.''
   Grayson and O'Dell maintain that government personnel are not,
by instinct or background, entrepreneurs or managers, and that
their allocation decisions would be worse than those of the private
sector.
   Furthermore, they observe, authors and administrators of
policies and laws tend to be lawyers or economists with little
knowledge of business operations. And, they ask, aren't we aware
that government cannot plan long range and cannot stay atop the
rapid, continuous adjustments of a dynamic market?
   3. The country should avoid currency devaluation as a
competitiveness strategy.
   Among other things, they argue, devaluing the dollar makes the
United States compete on the basis of a lower standard of living.
``Devaluation keeps knocking the dollar down until American wages
are cheap enough to compete.''
   4. Capital investment shouldn't be overemphasized.
   ``We stress that capital investment is not only important for
productivity improvement, it is essential,'' they say. ``What we
argue against is the overemphasis and wrong emphasis on capital
investment.''
   One of their reasons for so thinking is that ``merely calling
for more capital investment confuses the volume of capital
investment with the productivity of that investment.''
   5. More research and development is not necessarily better.
   ``The biggest competitive problem is not the amount spent on
R&D, but on what is spent, and what is done with the ideas and
techniques after discovery.''
   The United States, they point out, is still the world leader in
originating new ideas. But, ``while that is great for the good of
the world, what counts in competitiveness is rapid
commercialization of new knowledge.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday, Sept. 7.</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880906-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:Dafoe ADV12   09-06 0835</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Dafoe, ADV 12,0861</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Sept. 12, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Willem Dafoe Talks About ``That Movie''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willem Dafoe is a modest man, but he couldn't
help thinking the time was right to play the title role in ``The
Last Temptation of Christ.''
   ``It made all the sense in the world,'' he said. ``I thought,
`Yes, of course. Perfect. It's a good role. I feel right for it
right now.' I'm just at the point in my life where I'm concerned
with some of the things he's speaking about. The struggle between
the body and the spirit is something I'm interested in.''
   Few films have generated as much controversy as Martin
Scorsese's ``The Last Temptation of Christ.'' Based on the novel by
Nikos Kazantzakis, it depicts an angst-ridden Jesus, torn between
desires of the mind and body. In a dream sequence, he is spared the
cross, sleeps with Mary Magdalene and has children. The movie has
drawn fierce protests from some religious groups.
   ``I was a little surprised,'' Dafoe said. ``I knew there was
some resistance. ... I never thought it would be to this extent and
take this kind of shape.''
   However, the publicity generated from the protests has helped
the movie at the box office.
   ``It's always a terrific thing for a publicity campaign,'' Dafoe
said. ``But it colors everything in a negative light. Maybe that's
a trade-off to the publicity.''
   Dafoe was eager to work with Scorsese, the director of ``Mean
Streets,'' ``Taxi Driver'' and ``Raging Bull.''
   ``He just gave me a certain kind of confidence and authority. He
kept me on the track. He makes you feel comfortable; he gives you
that room. You feel totally unencumbered, free, yet you feel a
guiding hand.''
   Dafoe also enjoyed working with the cast, which included Barbara
Hershey as Mary Magdalene and David Bowie as Pontius Pilate.
   ``There was a real sense of purpose,'' he said. ``Marty commands
a lot of respect. There was very little money, and the actors were
doing it for scale. Everyone wanted to be there. A real ensemble
feel.''
   Although Dafoe had seen other biblical movies, he had no
interest in repeating others' performances.
   ``I really didn't concern myself with what kind of Jesus I was
going to be _ the responsibility of playing that role, all the
associations, all the information. I thought I would find a place
to scrub myself clean of all that and really start out from a
wonderfully innocent place.''
   Dafoe's confidence was helped by his faith in Scorsese: ``I
would not be cowed by the role. It was a very risky thing. If
you're going to be in a situation like that, you might as well be
with Martin Scorsese.''
   The intensity of his performance in ``Last Temptation'' can be
measured by his eyes, which rarely blink on camera.
   ``No matter what you do, it has mythic proportions,'' he said.
``When you're speaking, no matter the context, there is some kind
of concentration that's not of this world.
   ``The general tendency is to look as deeply as you can into the
back of someone's brain and deeply understand with every cell in
your body what you're saying.''
   The 33-year-old actor talked about his career at the Performing
Garage, home of the Wooster Group, an experimental theater company.
Dafoe is a member and does business there.
   He was born July 22, 1955, in Appleton, Wis., and was early
attracted to the stage. ``Simply moronic reasons,'' he said,
smiling. ``It's fun, it's enjoyable. I like pretending.''
   As he grew older, his feelings for acting deepened.
   ``In the end, it's for its own sake _ for beauty's sake. A lot
of professions, you're tracked. You do this, you get that. In
acting, you become the canvas. It totally goes back to you,'' he
said.
   ``You're constantly questioning why you do what you do. You're
constantly evolving. It's a healthy way to live, but very
difficult.''
   He became a full-time actor at 18, and in 1977, he saw the
Wooster Group give a performance of ``Rumstick Road.''
   ``It was just unlike anything I'd ever seen,'' he said. ``The
event was so extraordinary. It touched my heart. There's no
accounting for it. I couldn't identify it. It had that kind of
maniac energy and this really fluid transformation.''
   Dafoe joined the Wooster Group but also pursued a career in
film. After appearing in a few minor films in 1983, he began to
attract attention with ``Streets of Fire'' in 1984 and ``To Live
and Die in L.A.'' in 1985.
   His big breakthrough came the following year with ``Platoon,''
Oliver Stone's Academy Award-winning film about the Vietnam War.
Dafoe's portrayal of the sympathetic Sergeant Elias earned him an
Oscar nomination for supporting actor.
   Despite film work, he has continued his involvement with the
Wooster Group. ``The whole desire to play around with forms is a
liberating thing for an actor,'' he said..
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
