<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Young George, ADV 18-3 Takes,0865</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 18</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&w
photos.)</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential nominee George ``Poppy''
Bush went off to Phillips Academy in Andover, Mass., at age 13,
before the word ``preppy'' had been invented, and later attended
Yale. A reporter looking into the school days of both Bush and his
Democratic opponent, Michael Dukakis, talked with former classmates
and teachers who generally remember him as ``a real nice guy'' and
a good athlete. Dukakis' schoolmates will get their say in the next
story.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By HUGH A. MULLIGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANDOVER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush has shed the Ben Franklin
glasses, dropped his twangy voice a note or two and now eschews
button-down shirts _anything to get rid of the preppy image that
dogs his run for president against Michael Dukakis.
   ``There's a tendency to have you fit into a mold,'' the
Republican vice president complained recently. ``The mold for me is
a kind of Ivy League elitist, and I resist it.''
   Alas, Bush might have avoided the whole Eastern establishment
WASP wimp caricature had he been born in Columbus, Ohio, like his
father, or in St. Louis like his mother's clan or in Kingsport,
Tenn., like older brother Prescott Jr.
   Well, almost. Prescott Sr. did go to Yale, as did George, his
three brothers, four uncles and cousins by the half-dozens.
   Still, Dad was a Midwest hardware salesman before U.S. Rubber
absorbed his small firm and transferred him to Braintree, Mass.,
where George was born on June 12, 1924, in nearby Milton.
   A transfer to the New York office relocated the family in the
affluent commuter town of Greenwich, Conn., but they weren't
established Easterners until Dad turned to investment banking,
bought that 11-room Victorian house with a huge rolling lawn on
Grove Lane and became moderator of the town meeting.
   Later, years later, when George was out of Yale and wildcatting
for oil in Texas, his father twice won election to the U.S. Senate
and became a golfing partner of Dwight Eisenhower.
   George at age 5 went off to the Greenwich Country Day School.
From the start, he was a good athlete, thanks to Mom, Dorothy
Walker Bush, who had made it to the finals of the Girls National
Tennis Championship and is still going strong, riding her bike at
86, handing out campaign literature.
   ``Physically, she is a small woman, but she is made of mighty
stuff,'' George wrote in a Mother's Day salute three years ago for
the Greenwich Time newspaper. ``Nine months into her first
pregnancy she played baseball. Her last time up she hit a home run
and without missing a base continued right off the field to the
hospital to deliver Pres.''
   Sundays after Episcopal services at Christ Church, there was
always a baseball game on the Bush lawn with George, being
left-handed, holding down first base, a position he excelled at
when he captained the Yale nine into the national collegiate finals
and got to meet Babe Ruth.
   ``Poppy, as we called him, had good hand-to-eye coordination,''
recalls retired Time-Life executive Evan Ingels, a classmate at the
Country Day School. ``He was a running back on our football team,
good also at soccer, tennis and wrestling. We were both a year
younger than the others and rivals for head of the class.''
   George was nicknamed ``Little Pop,'' then ``Poppy,'' for his
hero worship of his maternal grandfather, George ``Pop'' Walker, a
fine athlete who donated the Walker Cup to golf. Grandpa Walker,
who presided over those blissful summers in the rambling
ocean-front house at Kennebunkport, Maine, that Bush now owns, was
``a staunch Democrat'' until Roosevelt came along. ``Roosevelt made
him see red,'' a friend recalls.
   Ingels remembers ``staying over'' at the Bush home on Halloween
and hiding out in the graveyard after ``squirting people with a
water pistol loaded with green ink and belting them with a sock
full of flour.''
   ``Poppy _ I never knew him as anything else _ was a real nice
guy, decent and honest, never a braggart. Maybe that's the trouble
with the world today. Suddenly a nice guy is a wimp. He was never a
wimp in my book. He's not the type to shake his fist at people, but
he's got plenty of strong fibers.''
   One day fifth-grade teacher Arthur Grant got them thinking about
the future: ``Some of you will go into business and be leaders.
Others may go into politics. Who knows, one of you might be
president of the United States.'' He had no one in mind then, but
at 89 he remembers Bush as ``a good athlete. He and his brothers
always had a real code of ethics.''
   Breakfast in the Bush household began with mother or father
reading a passage from the Bible. Both parents stressed values,
especially fairness, modesty and service to others, and were
pleased with George's report card evaluation: ``Claims no more than
his fair share of attention.''
</TEXT>
