<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Young George, ADV 18-2nd Add,0757</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 18</NOTE>
<HEAD>ANDOVER: of youth.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   On a recent visit to his alma mater, Bush remembered Pearl
Harbor Day, 1941, ``slouching across campus with my roommate. We
kept it on our minds that the Germans were invading Europe. We knew
exactly what we had to do. We had to beat Exeter at football.''
Which they did, 14-13, with the whole school singing and shouting
through the snowy night on that special train back from New
Hampshire.
   War was almost a curriculum elective by then. The boys sold war
bonds, donated their downtown treats money to the U.S.O., gathered
up magazines in the dorms every Thursday for the soldiers at nearby
Fort Devens, and Pot Pourri lost its slick cover to the wartime
paper shortage.
   The class historian noted that ``the whole school thrilled to an
address at morning chapel by Col. Henry L. Stimson, the Secretary
of War'' and an Andover trustee. George, as chairman of the student
deacons, got to escort the secretary to the podium, in addition to
his regular duties of checking attendance and taking up the
collection.
   Caught up in the patriotic fervor, George on his 18th birthday,
just a few days after graduation, took the train to Boston to
enlist in the Navy. In the yearbook poll of 193 graduates, he
ranked third behind varsity quarterback Elliott Vose as ``most
popular,'' ``handsomest'' ``most respected'' and ``best all-around
fellow.'' He rated second in ``most faculty drag'' and was out of
the running as ``most intelligent,'' ``most likely to succeed'' and
``ladies' man.''
   His name was read out in chapel on a September morning in 1944
when his carrier-based torpedo bomber was reported shot down in
flames in a raid on the Japanese airstrips on Chichi Jima and again
when word came that he had been plucked from a rubber raft in the
Pacific by a surfacing submarine, the USS Finback.
   For George Herbert Walker Bush, the preppy years were
essentially over. When he entered Yale in November l945, he was
hardly your Peter Arno cartoon caricature of a Yalie, although
typical of that first postwar term when three out of five were
veterans and gray flannels were beginning to replace officer pink
on the old campus.
   Bush was already married and soon to start a family. He and
Barbara first lived in a Quonset hut near the Payne Whitney gym,
then in a series of apartments, the last one, as he ad-libbed after
a recent campus speech, so close to President Charles Seymour's
house ``you could look in the window and see his wife taking a
bath.''
   Poppy, as he was still called, sailed though an accelerated
economics program in 2{ years, won the Francis Gordon Brown Prize
as the outstanding junior and went on to earn Phi Beta Kappa. He
also found time to burp baby George, play three years of varsity
baseball, letter in soccer and take part in an occcasional
fraternity beer bust at the Delta Kappa Epsilon house.
   His name didn't make the New Haven police blotter for that riot
after the pep rally on the eve of the Cornell football game. His
l948 classbook supplied some vivid details: ``Just how many heads
collided with billy sticks cannot accurately be counted nor how
many rolls of toilet paper flew out of dormitory windows, but there
is someone who claims he personally stopped 31 trolley cars.''
   Like his father before him, and such diverse luminaries as
William Howard Taft, Averell Harriman, Henry Luce, Archibald
MacLeish, Potter Stewart, William F. Buckley and William Sloane
Coffin, George was one of l5 juniors tapped for Skull and Bones,
the oldest and most secret of the societies anchoring Yale's old
boy network. He went through the rumored (Bonesmen never tell)
initiation of climbing into a coffin to confess his sins
(preferably erotic) in ``The Tomb,'' the windowless, brown
sandstone club house.
   Although Bush went 3 for 5, the big disappointment in his senior
year was the baseball team's loss to the University of California
in the national collegiate finals.
   As one who knew him well in the preppy days, has kept in touch
since the college years and ``will be rooting for him in the
Electoral College,'' old coach Deke DiClementi has a word of
caution for reporters on the Bush beat:
   ``Don't say he's a nice guy. He really IS a nice guy. That's
what's killing him.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
