<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WeekendTV-DiamondTrap ADV16-18   09-06 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV-Diamond Trap, ADV 16-18,0903</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16-18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 16-18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Story Behind `Diamond Trap' Almost as Intriguing as Mystery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Diamond Trap,'' which leads off the
season for the ``CBS Sunday Movie'' on Sept. 25, has career risks,
corporate intrigue, tragedy and triumph. And a lot of it took place
before the cameras rolled.
   The movie stars Brooke Shields, Twiggy, Howard Hesseman and Ed
Marinaro, but the gold stars for putting it all together go to the
executive producer, Jay Bernstein.
   Bernstein, a former publicist and top Hollywood agent who
boosted the careers of such performers as Linda Evans and Farrah
Fawcett, is not likely to produce ``The Mother Teresa Story.''
   It would be too easy. Big script, big stars, lots of easy
production money.
   Instead, Bernstein took a regulation thriller based on the novel
``The Great Diamond Robbery'' from mystery novelist John Minahan
and insisted on Miss Shields and Twiggy as the female leads for the
script, which had been revised eight times over 2{ years by writer
David Peckinpah.
   Bernstein claims one of the best industry records for television
movies, with the seven he has done so far averaging a 33 share, and
none lower than a 31 share, the term used by A.C. Nielsen to
describe the percentage of the overall TV audience viewing a
particular show.
   He knows how to hit the right audience buttons or, in his words,
``Put the sizzle in the steak.'' But wanting Miss Shields for the
part and getting her were two different things.
   He made a point of going to this year's ``People's Choice''
awards to put the script in her hand. The role for Miss Shields was
that of a gallery employee who is part of a plot to steal $12
million in jewels, but the police, including Twiggy as a Scotland
Yard detective, persuade her to help them foil the crime.
   The part of the sophisticated 30-year-old would be the first
adult role for Shields, a 23-year-old Princeton honors graduate.
She wanted it.
   But not everyone wanted her. She had to read for the role, for
Bernstein, for director Don Taylor, for CBS and for Columbia, an
unusual demand on someone who has already commanded major film
roles.
   ``Certain people involved in the production were so worried
about how to deal with a, quote, `movie star' on a 22-day shooting
schedule that the final compromise was to put part of my salary in
escrow,'' said Bernstein in an interview. ``If there was a problem,
the first money to be lost would be mine.
   ``I told Brooke I was going to do this and she said, `Don't
worry, I won't let you down,''' he said.
   ``Not only did she not let me down, she made me very proud. She
is one of those people ... who everybody waits for to fail. And
she's succeeded,'' said Bernstein. He called Miss Shields ``easy to
work with and able to turn in a fine performance, even with all
this pressure on her.''
   There were other perils. The project came to CBS just as the
network leadership was going through a shakeup, with CBS
Entertainment President Donald Grant leaving the network and Kim
LeMasters replacing him.
   ``It was about to be caught between the switches,'' said
Bernstein. ``There was something CBS wanted from me, and it was
hard to give, but I went in and gave it to them,'' said Bernstein.
He didn't identify the sacrifice, but most likely it was a
different movie or series project.
   ``And then I asked them for a favor afterward. `Please let me do
this and I won't let you down.' And now it's their leadoff movie,''
Bernstein said.
   But even after getting a green light, there was the matter of
financing..
   ``The problem was the picture was too expensive to make,''
Bernstein said. ``This picture was filmed in Los Angeles, New York,
Bristol, Bath, Wales and London, with four major stars, each of
whom could be star of their own TV movie.''
   In the midst of grappling with finances, Bernstein's father,
Jerome, died of complications from a heart condition April 17.
Bernstein has dedicated the movie to his father.
   ``At the time my father died, the picture was falling apart,''
Bernstein recalled. ``On the day of my father's funeral, a person
from CBS said to me, `Don't worry, it's going to work out.' And
another person from Columbia said the same thing. And they did it.
   ``That means there are people functioning in these corporations.
They don't get an opportunity very often to express their emotions,
because everything is the bottom line. But I've seen CBS and
Columbia come through big, twice,'' said Bernstein. He also got the
studio and the network to restore the ``Mike Hammer'' series to the
air after star Stacy Keach was imprisoned in England on cocaine
charges.
   ``The Diamond Trap'' faces the Olympics on NBC and probably a
broadcast of the movie ``Romancing the Stone'' on ABC, so Bernstein
knows he will not match the previous shares he has gained for
television movies.
   ``Whatever I get (in ratings share), I would have gotten only
half of it without these two women,'' Bernstein said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 16-18</NOTE>
