<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview ADV00   09-06 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Film Review, ADV 00,0530</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Eight Men Out''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   It seems unthinkable today that a major league baseball team
could conspire to throw the World Series. But it happened in 1919.
   ``Say it ain't so, Joe,'' were the words that echoed through
history when the infamous ``Black Sox Scandal'' was mentioned.
   Writer-director John Sayles takes his cue from that line spoken
by a young boy in fashioning ``Eight Men Out,'' a movie that is
incisive, touching and instructive without appearing to be a
history lesson.
   As the tragedy of the scandal unfolds, two young boys who
idolized the players and cadged dimes to buy tickets to games
become symbolic of the baseball fans whose dreams were tied to the
champion Chicago White Sox team that seemed a shoo-in to beat the
Cincinnati Reds in the World Series.
   We meet the players at the height of their success, a team with
the grace of ballet dancers, the naivete of children and the
winning force of a steamroller. Hailed by the media and worshiped
by fans, they are in constant conflict with the team's stingy
owner, Charles Comiskey, a fine bad guy portrayal by Clifton James.
   When sleazy gamblers including the infamous Arnold Rothstein
(Michael Lerner) propose ``fixing'' the World Series, most team
members are vulnerable. David Strathairn is a memorable example as
Eddie Cicotte, the aging pitcher who is denied a bonus and agonizes
over selling out for his family's sake.
   In true ensemble form, all of the performances are top rate.
D.B. Sweeney is touching as the talented country boy Shoeless Joe
Jackson whose inability to read or write makes him prey to
corrupting pressures. It is he who turns away sadly from the
child's plaint, ``Say it ain't so, Joe.''
   As the fix sets in, we see the expert players expertly losing
game after game. In the press box, journalist Ring Lardner, coolly
portrayed by John Sayles himself, and Hugh Fullerton, adeptly
played by Chicago writer Studs Terkel, become sadly aware that the
team, soon to be derisively tagged ``The Black Sox,'' has been
corrupted.
   The case leads to formation of the baseball commission and
appointment of the first commissioner, Judge Kenesaw Mountain
Landis (John Anderson) who punished all involved team members _
even those who didn't actively participate in the scam _ by barring
them from professional baseball forever.
   This is a must-see film for baseball fans and an instructive
entertainment for the rest of us. As writer, director and actor,
Sayles hits three home runs.
   ``Eight Men Out'' is rated PG.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
