<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews ADV00   09-06 0872</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, ADV 00,0913</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Just Before the Bullets Fly'' (Epic) _ The Gregg Allman Band
   
   Fans of the Allman Brothers won't be disappointed with founding
brother Gregg's latest solo effort, which echoes the patented
Southern sound of the original group and paints a lyrical portrait
of a rocker who has survived.
   Allman's bouts with various chemicals are well-known, and on
``Just Before the Bullets Fly'' he deals with that image right off
the bat. The first cut, ``Demons,'' has him singing, ``But oh, he's
got his demons@And they stay right by his side@Through his everyday
hell, yeah.''
   Later, on ``Oceans Awash the Gunwale,'' he credits the music
itself for saving him: ``Once more we're cheating on the
reaper@With all the gypsy still in our souls@Cause I know there's a
God up there somewhere@Who must love rock and roll.''
   And it's the music, particularly Allman's throaty blues vocals,
that keeps ``Just Before the Bullets Fly'' interesting.
   Guitarist Dan Toler, formerly of Dicky Betts' Great Southern
band, is the other major creative force here. His blues-rock licks
are predictable: lots of long, ringing guitar solos that recall
Gregg's late brother, Duane Allman. But it's become a classic sound
and Toler pays homage well.
   The title song, ``Demons,'' ``Can't Get Over You'' and a new
version of ``Every Hungry Woman'' are vintage Allman-style blues.
And Gregg sings with a power and range you won't find on anything
he's done since ``Eat a Peach.''
   A couple of other songs fail. An attempt at jazz-rock, ``Thorn
and a Wild Rose,'' sinks beneath the weight of its wash of
synthesizers and mushy metaphorical lyrics. And a pop song, ``Night
Games,'' forces Allman to try to sing bouncily _ and that's not his
strength.
   But the rollicking, guitar-piano-and-organ sound that fans of
the original Allmans know by heart, is alive and kicking on ``Just
Before the Bullets Fly.'' And so is a rock 'n' roll warrior, Gregg
Allman.
   _ By Curt Anderson, Associated Press writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Big Dreams in a Small Town'' (RCA) _ Restless Heart
   
   The problem with this kind of country-by-committee approach is
that by the time everyone gets through, the result is much like a
modern-day political platform _ it sounds nice enough, and it won't
offend anybody, but it's nothing to inspire the masses.
   With ``Big Dreams in a Small Town,'' Restless Heart gives us an
album with 12 songwriters, seven producers, five vocalists, nine
songs _ and, as a result, no focus.
   These five former Nashville session players have lodged
themselves firmly in the Alabama-Oak Ridge Boys league, with mellow
harmonies and professional musicianship. But while those groups
have managed to meld into a distinctive identity, Restless Heart
too often sounds like that staple of old-style country music shows
_ the band playing a couple of tunes before the star takes the
stage.
   ``The Bluest Eyes in Texas,'' the current hit off this
collection, is as good an example as any. What begins with a nice
piano introduction from the classically trained David Innis soon
enough settles into nice harmonies that eventually pull lead singer
Larry Stewart _ who really can sing _ into a nice vanilla morass.
   The first half has its moments: Innis with some crafty pop piano
on ``Say What's in Your Heart,'' reminiscent of the early Billy
Joel; and a solid group effort on the title cut, a quintessential
example of country pop.
   But things start to get a little adventurous in the second half,
and not to good effect, either: a crowded swamp-Western-Indian
air-of-mystery motif for ``Eldorado,'' and an unfortunate try at
funkiness in ``This Time.''
   With so many talented singers running around, Restless Heart
still needs to find its voice _ or at least a chairman of the board.
   _ By Robert Byrd, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Hits'' (Epic) _ REO Speedwagon
   
   REO Speedwagon has several strikes against it: banal lyrics,
bland musicianship, the lack of a distinctive band personality.
   But they are unpretentious about their abilities _ no concept
albums, no ``save the world'' singles, no 20-minute guitar solos.
They just try to make hit singles and have often succeeded.
   The songs on ``Greatest Hits'' are at worst, uninteresting, and
at best, instantly hummable. REO Speedwagon has lasted 20 years
with only a couple of personnel changes, and the songs on
``Greatest Hits'' date from 1973 to the present.
   The band's limitations and strengths are typified by lead singer
Kevin Cronin. He isn't terribly soulful, but Cronin doesn't pretend
to have a great voice and he handles fast songs and ballads equally
well.
   The three best songs come from 1980's best-selling ``Hi
Infidelity'': ``Keep on Loving You,'' ``Take It on the Run'' and
``Don't Let Him Go.'' All have strong melodies and plenty of
harmonies. They don't hold up under close listening but sound good
on the radio and the beach.
   Also included are the earlier singles, ``Time for Me to Fly''
and ``Roll With the Changes,'' and their most recent hits, ``Can't
Fight This Feeling,'' and ``That Ain't Love.''
   _ By Hillel Italie, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
