<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--StreetArt ADV16-18   09-06 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Street Art, ADV 16-18,0723</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16-18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug 16-18 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Harlem Comes to Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YOKOHAMA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harlem street artist Franco the Great
bebops a bit as he daubs the finishing touches on the belt of a
dancing woman gyrating across a construction site fence.
   As he brings his own brand of Harlem to Japan, Franco Gaskin is
completely oblivious to the trucks roaring past, the summer sun and
the sweat beads streaking the lenses of his glasses.
   ``Nothing you do for love or beauty gonna die,'' he says, his
arms spreading wide to take in a 100-foot mural of black men and
women caught in the motions of the samba, the jitterbug and the
bump.
   ``I know the Japanese have a different picture of blacks. I want
them to understand the black people and their world.''
   It's an intoxicating vision for a self-taught artist, a sailor's
son who spent his boyhood in silence after a fall rendered him mute
for 12 years.
   To fill the void, Gaskin turned to art. After he recovered his
speech he moved to Harlem, where a decade ago he decorated his
first storefront riot grate. The depiction of a magnolia _ his
``Japanese blossom tree'' _ was the germination of the kind of
greatness to which a lonely boy aspired.
   The work led to calls from other storekeepers _ more than 150 so
far _ and a sort of international following after foreign travelers
began touring Harlem's avenues. Gaskin has demonstrated his
technique before African art classes and painted murals for French
municipalities.
   In July, he arrived in this Pacific port city, summoned by
Japanese developers who liked his raw style. Le Grand, as his
paint-spattered coveralls proclaim, was charged with injecting
American-style verve into a neglected suburb selected as the site
for an international shopping district.
   ``We chose Franco because he's very good for wall paintings,''
said Tatsuo Nannichi, a publicist for the Honmoku Development
Project. ``He worked in France, Italy, also Africa, and he's a very
international person. I think he's the symbol of New York.''
   The Panamanian-born Gaskin has a theme he calls ``Harmony Among
the Races.'' It has been a dream to paint it in Japan, where he
hopes to find sponsors who will provide a more permanent backdrop.
   ``When we look at racism, in my world I'm dealing with black and
white, but never with yellow, never with brown people, red
people,'' he says.
   ``Black and white is a contrast. But it takes three or more
colors to make harmony. And since Japan is a most powerful nation,
I figure it takes Japan to link a lot of people around the world.''
   The project must wait until his next visit. For now, Gaskin is
happy that he's made a start.
   ``I planted a seed in Harlem and now the seed has grown into a
beautiful tree,'' he said. ``I wanted Japan to share a little bit
of the black culture.''
   After two weeks' work, Gaskin's charcoal outlines were filled
with browns, oranges and magentas set off by a sky-blue backdrop.
His section of corrugated steel canvas runs along a four-lane
thoroughfare, side by side with other temporary murals by Japanese
artists and art students.
   In Gaskin's painted world, everyone is smiling. Silver sparks
fly from tambourines, elbows jut, hands clap, a good bit of thigh
shows as a chubby lady twirls her skirt.
   ``I don't know art well, but I feel this is live New York modern
art. Fantastic,'' said Kazuhiko Kitagawa, a bank clerk and Franco
fan. ``I saw his art in Harlem last year, and I met him. He was
wearing the same clothes.''
   On a recent Sunday, Gaskin presented a Franco Award to one of
the Japanese art students. Standing on a cloth-covered box in his
coveralls, his 6-foot-5 frame crowned by a colorful straw hat from
a nearby festival, Gaskin read the proclamation in stumbling
Japanese to the student, who shook his hand and scurried away.
   ``Japanese artists will get incentive from his art,'' Kitagawa
said. ``If Japanese paint, it becomes imitation. He is real art.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Sept 16-18</NOTE>
