<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Armatrading ADV16-18   09-06 0816</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Armatrading, ADV 16-18,0839</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16-18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept 16-18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: The Personal Touch for Musical Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the musical gods were to
prophesize that a black woman who sang heart-tugging folk ballads
would top the charts in 1988, you'd figure it would be a very good
year for Joan Armatrading.
   After all, whoever heard of Tracy Chapman?
   But no one ever said the gods were fair. Armatrading, whose name
frequently comes up when critics talk about Chapman's work, is
still searching for that elusive hit 15 years and 13 albums into
her recording career.
   She quickly brushes off questions about the runaway success of
Chapman's debut record, saying she hasn't heard her music.
   A&M Records doesn't shy away, however. In advertisements for
Armatrading's new album, ``The Shouting Stage,'' the company says
that while hundreds of singers are compared to her, ``hundreds of
thousands of her fans knew she was there first.''
   The company is banking on the current mini-revival of the
singer-songwriter era to give Armatrading a long-sought boost to
stardom.
   ``Personally, I think it's unfair that Joan hasn't had the same
breaks that Tracy had,'' said Tom Corson, executive director of
product development for A&M. ``It's more of a question of timing.
Joan blazed the trails and Tracy's taken advantage of it.''
   Actually, there isn't much to the comparisons between
Armatrading and Chapman beyond the superficial similarities.
Chapman, in her debut album, features quiet, introspective folk
songs about love and society's treatment of the downtrodden.
   Armatrading sticks to personal politics, her emotionally intense
music an often exuberant mixture of rock, reggae, jazz and folk.
   The songs are so achingly personal that people often assume
they're all autobiographical, which would have given Armatrading a
pretty full emotional life over the past decade and a half.
   ``I think of it as a compliment, because the songs are written
to be believed,'' she said before one of the early dates in her
current U.S. tour. ``They're generally from something that's
happened. ... It's just that it's not necessarily from my things.
But I write it as if it's about me.''
   The new album's title cut comes from a magazine article that
theorizes every couple must go through a period of fighting to
achieve true intimacy, she said.
   The song is written in the voice of a woman addressing her lover
in the wake of this ``shouting stage,'' her tone veering between
resignation and vulnerability.
   More controversial is ``The Devil I Know,'' a searing indictment
of a ``wandering'' man from a woman trying to keep him close to
home that's already been taken to heart by many feminists.
   ``One chap said to me that the difference between men and women
is that men can distinguish between lust and love,'' she said. ``A
man can have a one-night stand or an affair that lasts a couple of
years and feel that he's being quite faithful to his real partner
because it's a purely sexual thing.
   ``It's women who have trouble thinking that if you go to bed
with someone you don't love them,'' she said. ``We'd like the two
to go together.''
   The song, she said, is about the age-old double standard that
seems to accept this behavior from men and condemn it from women.
   If someone thinks they've happened upon an album of men-bashing,
``The Devil I Know'' is immediately followed by the cheery ``Living
for You,'' about the happy side of being wrapped up in a
relationship.
   Armatrading's live show is packed with playful energy, almost
mocking the stereotypes of the singer-songwriter genre. She bounces
across the stage and trades some slightly choreographed dance steps
with saxophonist Jim Ross.
   The highlights come when she straps on an acoustic guitar for a
bluesy ``(I Love It When You) Call Me Names'' and a version of Van
Morrison's ``Moondance.''
   Her albums have become progressively harder-edged throughout the
1980s, but ``The Shouting Stage'' quiets things down a bit. It has
a highly produced, jazzy sound, benefitting from such studio stars
as Mark Knopfler and Alan Clark of Dire Straits.
   As much as she liked it at the time, Armatrading said she can't
listen to her 2-year-old album ``Sleight of Hand'' without pulling
the needle from the vinyl. Some of the songs, she admits, she finds
``irritable.''
   ``I was trying to write an album that I hope in a couple of
years' time people can sit and listen to just as much as they do
today,'' she said.
   Her record company will settle for people listening to it now.
Corson said he's encouraged by the company's sales performance in
the first few weeks of its release, though disappointed by radio's
continued reluctance.
   ``I think it's a time of opportunity for us,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Sept 16-18</NOTE>
