<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--VoiceoftheHeart ADV16-18   09-06 0969</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Voice of the Heart, ADV 16-18,0999</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16-18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept 16-18 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: Turning Best Sellers Into Hot TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the seventh floor of London's Mayfair Hotel,
actress Lindsay Wagner was preparing the climactic scene in the TV
movie ``Voice of the Heart.''
   The one-time ``Bionic Woman'' faced a difficult moment: She must
persuade her on-screen lover, Nick (Neil Dickson), that her past
actions are less hateful than they once seemed.
   ``Do you need holding?'' asked director Tony Wharmby. Wagner
nodded ``yes,'' and Wharmby walked over to bolster her confidence
by hugging her.
   The scene is a buildup to the confession on which hangs the plot
of Barbara Taylor Bradford's 1983 best-selling novel, whose TV
version will be aired in two 2-hour segments this winter over
Britain's Independent Television Network and in the United States
on a network that has not yet been announced.
   The $8 million movie promises all the ingredients of high-class
soap opera: a web of romance and deception, exotic foreign
locations, and an emotionally storm-tossed heroine named Katharine
Tempest, played by Wagner.
   ``Voice of the Heart'' is the third Bradford book to be adapted
for the screen.
   She began writing 40 years ago at the age of 12 when, as a
youngster in an upper middle-class family in Leeds, England, she
sold her first story about a girl and her horse to a children's
magazine.
   ``I think my destiny was sealed,'' she recalled in an interview.
   
   However, her writing was put on hold while she set out to
experience life. ``I don't think you can earn a living at the age
of 16 writing novels.''
   In her eagerness to gain that knowledge, she shunned college and
became a typist at the Yorkshire Evening Post. She was promoted to
cub reporter in six months. A year later, at age 18, she became
women's page editor and by age 20 moved to London's renowned
newspaper row, Fleet Street. She married American film producer
Robert Bradford in 1963 and moved to New York. At the time, she was
writing a syndicated column on interior design that ran in 185 U.S.
newspapers. However, the desire to write fiction began to nudge
her. She started her first novel in 1970, and had started three
others by 1975.
   Then came ``A Woman of Substance,'' which she called the story
of ``a strong woman who makes it in a man's world when women were
not doing that.''
   ``When I started to write those initial pages, I really felt
very excited because I somehow knew in my bones ... this was the
book I was going to finish and the book that would be right,'' she
said.
   The hardcover version has sold more than 11 million copies since
1979, and the paperback topped The New York Times best-seller list
for 43 weeks. It also was made into an acclaimed syndicated TV
miniseries.
   Her second, ``Voice of the Heart,'' sold 2.5 million copies in
the United States. Her third, ``Hold the Dream,'' was also a best
seller.
   ``Voice of the Heart'' co-stars James Brolin as the dashing
actor-director Victor Mason and Victoria Tennant as Francesca
Cunningham Avery, the historical biographer who vies with actress
Katharine for Victor's affections.
   ``There's a whole person in there, and the person's hurting,''
said the 39-year-old Wagner in an interview halfway through the
10-week shooting schedule.
   ``I've got to humanize her, to make her emotionally accessible
to people,'' she said, looking sleeker and more composed than she
would later that afternoon when she donned a bathrobe to play the
frazzled Katharine.
   ``She's a very exaggerated kind of character in the fact that
she's eccentric and neurotic. ... In the story, if we don't
sympathize with her, then there's no pay-off at the end.''
   Victoria Tennant said she was drawn to the premise of the film.
   ``The drama pivots on a white lie that is told that seems
harmless to the liar and yet devastates the lives of everyone
involved,'' said the soft-spoken English actress.
   ``I think it's quite telling,'' she said of the plot idea.
``When you think of all the information that is being thrown at you
and how you deal with it, you think, ``That's not impossible. You
could hear something and it could change your life.'''
   ``Voice of the Heart'' is a contemporary drama, said the
elegantly coiffed Bradford, whose ``A Woman of Substance'' and
``Hold the Dream'' also were made into TV movies. They dealt with
the department store dynasty of Emma Harte, and starred Deborah
Kerr.
   ``It's very up-to-date; it's got a touch of the present,'' she
said. ``Katharine is one of those strange, mixed-up weird women.''
   Like Wagner, Bradford insisted that Katharine arouse sympathy.
``She's not a bitch,'' the writer said. ``She's a complex and
complicated woman and a marvelous actress, who has this frigidity
which all goes back to the time when she was molested as a child.''
   Although her novels have been filmed and a fourth, ``Act of
Will,'' is to follow, Bradford said: ``If I wrote a book with the
ultimate goal of a TV or movie screen, I think I'd be cheating the
reader.
   ``I'm actually competing with TV because I want to hold the
reader. I don't want the reader saying, `Oh, This is just a lot of
dialogue. I can't visualize any of it; I'm going to turn on `War
and Remembrance.'''
   She insists on having her husband as executive producer on all
her TV adaptations.
   ``A lot of Hollywood producers buy a best seller, keep the title
and throw the contents away,'' she said. ``Bob believes you put
on-screen the story that's in between those two covers.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Sept. 16-18</NOTE>
