<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Ruscha ADV16-18   09-06 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Ruscha, ADV 16-18,0774</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16-18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 16-18 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Soviet Singers Spread Patriotic, Religious
Message</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DICKSON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Russian gospel singers are spreading a
message of Christianity and speaking out against communism, which
they say drove them from the Soviet Union.
   Nikolai Pankratz and his brother Peter are leaders of the
six-member, gospel-rock band Ruscha. The slick, hard-driving group
is on the road doing 150 concerts a year, playing mainly for
youngsters who hear 90 minutes of rousing music and then 15 minutes
of religious and patriotic messages.
   ``We are cruising across America, grabbing people by the neck
and saying, `Wake up. You've got it good but you are taking your
freedom for granted and you shouldn't do that. One day you may wake
up and be under persecution yourself,''' said 31-year-old Nikolai.
   ``People don't believe that will happen,'' he said. ``But we
grew up under communism, and we have a very great fear of it
spreading across the world.''
   The brothers said their family was persecuted in the Soviet
Union for being Christians and attending underground churches. In
1963, they said, the Soviet secret police came to their house and
took their grandfather away.
   ``He was dragged out in the deep snow in his pajamas,'' said
29-year-old Peter. ``He pointed toward heaven, meaning he'd see us
again. That's the last time we saw him. He arrived in a casket two
months later. He had frozen to death in Siberia.''
   The two said their family of eight, after four years of
negotiation, paid $3,000 a person to leave the country in 1974 and
relocate in Bonn, West Germany, where an aunt lived.
   ``There's no way to leave unless you sell everything you have,''
Peter said. ``We sold the only cow we had, the chickens we had, the
pigs we had. We sold our house and other people pitched in and
helped us financially.''
   From Germany, the brothers came to the United States on student
visas, Nikolai in 1978, Peter a year later. Learning English
without formal lessons, they studied at the Word of Life bible
institute in upstate New York for a year. They then enrolled at
Jerry Falwell's Liberty University in Lynchburg, Va., where they
received undergraduate degrees.
   ``He really helped us out,'' Nikolai said about Falwell. ``We
didn't know anything about America. He kind of took us under his
wing. Our whole life in this country started right there. We sang
in his church and on his TV show. He financed an album and got us
into his school.''
   The two have since decided to make their home in Dickson, about
40 miles west of Nashville.
   They first began performing under the name Russia but learned
that the name had a bad connotation in the United States. Because
of the name, their touring bus was vandalized several times.
   ``We got fed up and did something about it,'' Peter said.
``Americans don't realize there could be good Russians.''
   They changed the spelling to Ruscha.
   The two-year-old band now consists of the brothers plus
Americans Andy Denton, Michael Jackson, Billy Williams and Scott
Beck.
   Their debut album, ``Come Alive,'' was released earlier this
year. Their first single is ``Come Home,'' which has been No. 1 on
the gospel-rock charts in many cities.
   Their concerts are mostly in auditoriums and some in churches.
   ``We play some places no one else goes,'' Nikolai said. ``People
are getting to know us. That's pretty good.
   ``We want to get a message across through our music. It's a
vehicle. We try to tell the American people that people don't know
what it's like under communism. Also, we'd like to educate them
that it's a dangerous thing and that there is an answer to life:
God.
   ``What we are trying to do is what a lot of people of America
are failing to do: be able to grab kids' attention and say, `Don't
be a lazy bum. Support your government. Support your country. Stand
up for the rights of America.'
   ``If we're able to change the young people's attitude toward the
country, change their lifestyle away from drugs and alcohol and sex
and homosexuality, then I think we've done a whole lot more good
than 99 percent of the churches in America.''
   The brothers are not U.S. citizens, but this is a goal.
   ``We'd love that more than anything else,'' Peter said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Sept 16-18</NOTE>
