<NOTE>For release Thursday, Sept. 8, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Human Safety Trials Underway For AIDS Decoy Drug</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first human trials have begun to test
the safety and proper dose of an experimental drug that may act as
a decoy to attract the deadly AIDS virus and prevent it from
invading human blood cells.
   About 50 patients with acquired immune deficiency syndrome or
the less severe AIDS-related complex are participating in the
six-month studies of the drug, called rCD4, that began last month
at San Francisco General Hospital, New England Deaconess Hospital
and the National Cancer Institute.
   Tests of the drug's effectiveness against AIDS will begin only
after the safety and dosage trials are complete, the researchers
said.
   The drug is a manufactured version of CD4, a protein on the
surface of white blood cells, the main targets of the AIDS virus.
The virus infects white blood cells by latching onto the CD4
protein. Scientists hope injected rCD4 molecules might act as
decoys so AIDS virus particles in a patient's blood latch onto the
rCD4 instead of real CD4 on white blood cells.
   In that way, the drug might slow the virus' ability to spread
from cell to cell, thereby slowing or halting the progression of
AIDS in an infected person. It also might prevent white blood cells
from being infected if it is given immediately after a person has
gotten the virus in the bloodstream.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Aerial, Satellite Photos Can Locate Homes For Endangered Birds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Satellite images and aerial
photographs can provide a cheap way of finding South Pacific
islands suitable as new homes for endangered birds, a researcher
says.
   Janet Franklin, a graduate student in geography at the
University of California, Santa Barbara, said by using aerial
photos and computer-processed satellite images of the Cook Islands
she could distinguish tropical forest, swamp, brushland, fern
thickets and cultivated areas.
   Such information can be used to determine which isolated,
uninhabited islands are suitable for reintroduction and successful
reproduction of endangered birds, Franklin said.
   Habitat information is prohibitvely expensive to obtain from
field studies because because islands are spread over millions of
square miles of the western Pacific, she said. Aerial photos of the
Cook Islands can be bought for $2,500.
   Where aerial photos don't exist, satellite images can be bought
for about 10 times that amount, but that's still cheaper than
conducting on-the-ground field studies or new aerial surveys, she
said.
   In the past 2,000 years, Polynesian hunters eliminated or
sharply reduced populations of many land birds from many islands in
the South Pacific.
   ``That is no longer a problem, but the remaining birds are
threatened by habitat destruction as well as introduced predators,
particularly cats, rats and mongeese,'' said Franklin, who hopes to
protect endangered species by reintroducing them on uninhabited
islands where they once thrived.
   Franklin outlined her study Aug. 16 at an American Institute of
Biological Sciences meeting.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Permanent Voice Damage Can Result If Minor Laryngeal Injuries</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Untreated
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experiments on voice boxes removed from
cadavers suggest that minor injuries to the larnyx may cause
permanent damage to the voice if left untreated.
   Car crashes, chokeholds, strangleholds and other blunt-force
injuries often cause minor fractures to the cartilage framework of
the larynx, or voice box, which contains the vocal cords.
   Such fractures usually aren't treated unless they interefere
with breathing, said Dr. Robert Stanley, an assistant professor at
the University of Southern California School of Medicine.
   However, Stanley said his study suggests such fractures can
``cause long-term hoarseness or limit the range of pitch and pitch
control.''
   The fractures, while difficult to diagnose, can be detected by
CAT scans and treated by intricate surgery in which wires are
inserted into the voice box to restore proper alignment of
cartilage, Stanley said.
   In the USC study, voice boxes were removed from five dead people
and mounted on a special apparatus, both in their normal condition
and after minor injuries were simulated. Warm, humid air was passed
through the voice boxes in a manner similar to that in which a
person speaks.
   Analysis showed that even minor fractures reduced the efficiency
of each larynx in regulating air flow during the production of
sound, suggesting more laryngeal fractures should be treated than
is customary, Stanley said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 8</NOTE>
