<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Belgium-SocieteGenerale     09-06 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Belgium-Societe Generale,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Societe Generale Names New Board Members After Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carlo de Benedetti, the Italian
financier who earlier this year tried to take over Belgium's
largest holding company, was one of 20 new board members elected to
the company's board Tuesday.
   Shareholders of Societe Generale de Belgique SA endorsed the new
board during a special meeting called to set up a new management
structure for the company following its bitter takeover battle
earlier this year.
   In addition to De Benedetti, three of his allies were named to
the board: Peter Cohen, chairman of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. of
the United States, Rene Thomas, chairman of Banque Nationale de
Paris, and Alain Minc, the chief of Cerus SA, de Benedetti's French
holding company.
   Societe Generale's Chairman Rene Lamy said he would remain until
the spring shareholders meeting. He will be succeeded by Etienne
Davignon, a former European Economic Community Commissioner, who is
expected to play a major role in the company's restructuring.
   The new board met after the vote to set in motion a major
restructuring of the giant company that has stakes in some 1,300
companies worldwide involved in, among others things, mining,
energy, financial services, chemicals and engineering.
   Analysts have said Societe Generale badly needed to be shaken
up. They said its status as Belgium's largest holding company had
allowed it to retain an antiquated management structure that had
changed little since its founding in 1822.
   The 166-year-old company was the target of a highly public
takeover battle earlier this year between De Benedetti and a
consortium of Belgian and French companies, led by Compagnie
Financiere de Suez. Financiere, a French financial group and the
single largest Societe Generale stockholder, had joined with Groupe
AG, a Belgian insurance group, to oppose De Benedetti's takeover
bid.
   In the end, the two camps struck a compromise power sharing deal
after neither could gain an outright majority stake.
   As part of the deal, de Benedetti was to be named vice chairman
of Societe Generale de Belgique and given control of three other
board seats.
   Shearson had played a major role in De Benedetti's attempt to
take over Societe Generale.
   The 203 shareholders at Tuesday's meeting represented some 40.5
million of Societe Generale's 42.7 million shares. Cohen's Shearson
Lehman became an investor last spring in Europe 1992, a company set
up and controlled by De Benedetti to hold shares in Societe
Generale.
   The new board said 1988 dividend should ``at least'' equal the
1987 payout of 115 Belgian francs per ordinary share ($2.90).
   It said it would raise 1988 dividends on AFV shares, a special
type of share issued under a Belgian tax plan that allows higher
dividends.
   The 1987 payout for Societe Generale AFV stock was 143.65 francs
($3.60) a share, down from 187.55 francs ($4.69) in 1986.
   Societe Generale's net profit fell 22 percent in 1987 to 4.14
billion francs ($103.5 million) from 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
