<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crop futures prices opened mostly higher today on
the Chicago Board of Trade amid continuing optimism that exports of
U.S. grain and soybeans are on the rise.
   Wheat futures have been quietly rallying for about two weeks and
opened today near the highs set earlier this summer. The near-month
wheat contract, for September delivery, was above $4 a bushel in
early trading. Near-month wheat reached $4.07 a bushel on July 5.
   Soybean futures were higher in reaction to strong European
markets while corn prices were little changed.
   Although rainfall was in short supply this summer, farmers
increasingly are hoping for dry weather as the corn and soybean
harvests advance, analysts said.
   ``Especially in Iowa and Illinois, where they've got a lot of
weak plants, winds, rains, anything like that probably will knock
those yields down,'' said Steve Freed, grain market analyst with
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 2 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.03 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 1} cents lower with September at $2.90{ a bushel; oats
were 1{ cents to 3 cents higher with September at $2.62 a bushel;
soybeans were 5{ cents to 8 cents higher with September at $8.79 a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .63 cent lower with October at
71.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .18 cent to .72 cent lower
with September at 81.15 cents a pound; hogs were .87 cent lower to
.60 cent higher with October at 37.65 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .20 cent to 1.80 cents lower with February at 46.85
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher on Friday while pork futures were
lower. The markets were closed Monday for the Labor Day holiday.
</TEXT>
