   The stock market strengthened slightly this
morning in what brokers called post-Labor Day buying interest
caused largely by the big runup of the previous session, but
trading remained light.
   ``All the big boys are back from the beach with lots of cash,
but I think they're still waiting to see what's going on,'' said
Robert O'Toole, manager of over-the-counter trading at Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York. ``This is just a carryover from
Friday's nice rush.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which surged
52.28 points Friday in the biggest one-day gain in three months,
was up another 3.02 to 2,057.61 by noon EDT.
   Among broader indicators, the New York Stock Exchange's
composite index of all listed issues rose 0.24 to 149.90. The
American Stock Exchange's market-value index rose 0.39 to 296.01.
   Gaining issues outnumbered declines by about 6-to-5 on the NYSE,
with 658 up, 578 down and 518 unchanged. Big Board volume totaled
61.54 million shares in the morning session, vs. 73.06 million
Friday morning.
   Brokers said stocks attracted some interest because of the rally
Friday, when the government reported rising unemployment in August.
That was interpreted as a sign the economy is slowing down.
   Financial markets tend to respond positively to such news since
it implies eased pressure on interest rates.
   Among the most-active NYSE issues, IBM fell 1] to 112|. There
were reports that rivals of the computer giant plan to announce a
new personal computer system that will challenge IBM's Personal
System-2.
