<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BassAcquisitions Bjt   09-06 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bass Acquisitions, Bjt,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fortune Stems From Texas Oil Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The acquisition of American Savings and
Loan Association by the Robert M. Bass Group is the latest in a
flurry of activity this year by a billionaire whose family fortune
traces back to Texas oil money.
   Bass, 40, has agreed to put up $550 million in cash to acquire
the Stockton, Calif.-based thrift, the nation's largest insolvent
savings and loan, while the Federal Home Loan Bank Board will
provide $2 billion in assitance over the next 10 years.
   ``This is obviously one of the biggest deals that they've
done,'' said Bruce Benteman, a research analyst for Wealth
Monitors, an investment advice firm in Kansas City, Mo. ``It shows
the pockets of Bob Bass and his affiliates _ it shows how deep they
are.''
   Bass's personal wealth is estimated at more than $1 billion. The
wealth of the Bass family, including Robert's brothers Sid R., Lee
M. and Edward P., is estimated at $5 billion to $6 billion.
   The family has a history of buying troubled businesses and then
waiting for a turnaround and the profit that follows.
   Their fortune dates back to Texas wildcatter Sid Richardson, who
made a series of successful oil strikes. Richardson never married
and left some of his millions to his partner and nephew, Perry Bass.
   Perry's four sons each inherited $2.8 million, and they combined
assets to form Bass Brothers Enterprises, which built up the family
wealth through shrewd investments. In 1968, Perry, a competitive
sailor, handed over the business to son Sid.
   All educated at Yale University, the Bass brothers have been
described as atypical Texas tycoons with a conservative style and
quiet manner.
   After starting his business career with Wells Fargo Bank, Robert
M. Bass returned to Texas in 1974 to a spot at Bass Brothers
Enterprises.
   Tales of rivalries among the four brothers surfaced in recent
years, and in 1983 Robert broke away and formed Robert M. Bass
Group to pursue deals on his own.
   The savings and loan deal announced Monday is just the latest in
a series for Bass in recent months.
   He bought the Westin Hotel chain from Allegis Corp. for $1.53
billion, then in March sold the Plaza Hotel in Manhattan for $410
million to developer Donald Trump.
   On May 17, Bass reached an agreement to pay $702 million to
acquire Bell & Howell Co., the publishing and information services
company in Skokie, Ill.
   In a further foray into the publishing field, Bass has been
pursuing a $1.9 billion takeover bid for Macmillan Inc., another
publishing and information company. Macmillan is negotiating a
possible deal with Maxwell Communication Corp. of Britain, which
has made a rival $2.3 billion tender offer.
   Benteman, the analyst, predicts that consistent with past
involvement in acquired companies, the Bass group will not become
heavily involved in managing the newly acquired savings and loan.
   ``He's not a hands-on manager,'' Benteman said. ``He hires the
people to do it, and he gives them the direction.''
   Although this is the first time Bass has acquired a savings and
loan, the move was not unexpected. ``We know they've looked before
at other S&Ls in the Texas area,'' Benteman said.
   ``I think they see a situation where they get a lot of assets
and lot of potential assets at bargain-basement prices,'' he added.
   Aside from their financial coups, Bass and his brothers are
well-known in Fort Worth for civic activities.
   They have provided money for schoolteacher improvement projects,
established a Main Street beautification project, paid for a study
of the needs of a minority neighborhood, renovated buildings,
contributed to hospitals and clinics, financed museums and given to
local high schools and universities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880906-0215 </DOCNO>
