<HEAD>London Shares Close Up Slightly</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed slightly higher Tuesday but
sharply off their peak levels as the market slid in late trading in
the wake of declining New York prices.
   However, volume levels remained low, making it difficult to draw
any firm conclusions about market sentiment, analysts said.
   At the end of trading, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index was up 3.5 points, or 0.2 percent, at 1,768.0. The
index opened at 1,766.9 and rose as much as 10.2 points by midday
to its best level of the day.
   The narrower Financial Times 30-share index was up 5.5 points at
1,426.0. A volume of 326.7 million shares changed hands, compared
with 284.8 million Monday.
   The Financial Times ``500'' share index was 1,003.69, up 3.06
points.
   ``It's difficult to see where the good news is going to come
from, if not from Wall Street,'' said one analyst on London's late
afternoon slide. ``Cash-rich institutions are thinking, `why invest
money now when we're not convinced that good news is on the way.'''
   Other analysts said the U.S. Labor Department report Friday that
U.S. unemployment rose to 5.6 percent in August was seen as a
summer aberration and not indicative of a trend.
</TEXT>
