<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   09-06 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Hit 2-Month High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices closed sharply higher at
two-month highs Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade on a variety
of signs construed as bullish for export sales. Other grains and
soybeans also gained.
   The Canadian government's estimate that Canada would harvest
15.4 million metric tons of wheat, the smallest crop in 13 years,
helped spur the wheat market, which had been rallying quietly for
about two weeks, analysts said.
   The wheat production estimate issued Friday by Statistics Canada
compares with the U.S. Agriculture Department's latest estimate
that the Canadians would harvest 18 million bushels of wheat this
year. The report prompted concerns that Canada may be forced to
reduce its wheat exports.
   New bids for U.S. wheat from Jordan and Iraq and expectations of
new demand from other countries _ including the Soviet Union _ also
supported wheat futures, said Katharina Zimmer, a grain analyst
with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets in New York.
   ``There is something afoot with the Russians,'' she said.
``Apparently there are some Russian visitors in Washington. We
don't know who they are or what they're doing but the fact is it
was a lot more bullish on the wheat market than the corn market.''
   Wheat futures closed at their highest levels since July 5, when
the year's highs were set.
   At the close, wheat was 6 cents to 10{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.10 a bushel; corn was 3
cents to 5\ cents higher with September at $2.93{ a bushel; oats
were 8 cents to 11{ cents higher with September at $2.71 a bushel;
soybeans were 8{ cents to 17 cents higher with September at $8.89 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
