<HEAD>Wardair To Purchase Planes From Fokker</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graph to include dollar figures. Picks up 3rd graf
Wardair president George D. Curley ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wardair Canada will purchase 24 Fokker
100 jet aircraft from the Dutch manufacturer, it was announced
Tuesday.
   Financial details of the deal were not disclosed, Robert Hawk,
spokesman for the Dutch manufacturer's U.S. subsidiary, said.
However, each aircraft sells for between $21 million and $22
million, Hawk said, placing the potential deal at about $500
million.
   Wardair president George D. Curley said the purchase will allow
the company to strengthen its route network and expand medium-haul
flights.
   The aircraft, powered by twin Rolls-Royce engines, seats between
84 and 107 passengers, depending on how the seats are configured,
Hawk said.
   The final eight aircraft in the order may be treated as options,
the Fokker announcement said. Delivery is scheduled to begin in
late 1990.
   The Fokker 100 entered airline service with Swissair in April.
Wardair's purchase brings to 110 the number of Fokker 100s ordered
to date. Several airlines hold options on another 91 aircraft. KLM,
USAir and Braniff also have purchased the aircraft which has an
operating range of 1,750 miles.
</TEXT>
