<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1609EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     09-06 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0243</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market strengthened slightly today
because of post-Labor Day buying interest in the aftermath of the
big runup during the previous session, although trading remained
slow.
   Brokers said many of the large institutional investors that are
crucial for substantial rallies remained out of the market,
reflecting an underlying caution about committing money to stocks
without more information on the direction of the economy and
interest rates.
   ``A lot of guys are sitting with flat positions, because taking
positions could kill you in this market,'' said Robert O'Toole,
manager of over-the-counter trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
But he said that ``if the institutions come in, this market will
roar on the upside.''
   The market's strong gains on Friday stemmed largely from
increased optimism about stocks and bonds based on evidence that
the economy is slowing down, easing upward pressure on interest
rates. The most potent evidence was a rise in August unemployment
reported by the Labor Department.
   While some stock strategists were disappointed by the market's
weak volume today, others said they were encouraged because prices
didn't retreat on profit-taking, regarded as a sign of increased
confidence.
   ``Despite the fact that volume hasn't accelerated dramatically,
the underlining bias is distinctly positive,'' said Eugene Peroni,
a technical analyst at the Philadelphia investment firm Janney
Montgomery Scott Inc. ``Most stocks are behaving well.''
</TEXT>
