<HEAD>Griffin Extends $36-a-Share Tender Offer for Casino Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Merv Griffin has extended his
$205 million offer to buy the common stock of Resorts International
until Friday because the deal has not been approved by New Jersey
gaming authorities.
   In announcing the extension of the $36-a-share tender offer
Tuesday, Griffin's Griffco Acquisition Corp. said holders of 81
percent of Resorts' Class A common stock had offered to sell their
shares.
   Griffco said it was awaiting a ruling from the New Jersey Casino
Control Commission on the purchase of the Atlantic City-based
casino and hotel company.
   Also extended was Griffco's agreement with New York financier
Donald Trump, who is to receive $96 million for his share of
Resorts International plus $63 million to break his management
contract with the company. Trump is to buy Resorts International's
unfinished Taj Mahal casino for $255 million as part of the deal.
