<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   09-06 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0567</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market advanced Tuesday because of
increased buying interest from a pre-Labor Day surge, but the
trading level remained slow and signaled cautious behavior by large
influential investors.
   ``I don't see any brand new money rushing in,'' said Robert
O'Toole, manager of over-the-counter trading at Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. in New York. ``All the big boys are back from the beach
with lots of cash, but I think they're still waiting to see what's
going on.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which jumped
52.28 points Friday for the biggest one-day advance in three
months, added another 10.67 to close at 2,065.26. Broader market
indicators also rose.
   But New York Stock Exchange volume totaled only 122.25 million
shares, considerably less than the 159.84 million traded in the
Friday session, when the Labor Department's report that
unemployment rose in August incited some enthusiasm in the markets
because it eased fear of inflation.
   The weaker volume Tuesday disheartened some strategists who had
been hoping for a more substantial boost in buying interest by
large institutional investors following the three-day Labor Day
break.
   ``I'm disappointed,'' said Gordon Smith, head of institutional
trading at the Baltimore firm of Alex. Brown & Sons Inc. On the
other hand, he said, ``People coming back from vacation aren't
going to spend the first day buying and selling stocks. It doesn't
surprise me, the volume as light as it is.''
   Others said they were encouraged because the market didn't
retreat on profit-taking, historically a sign of anxiety about the
short-term direction of stocks.
   ``Despite the fact volume hasn't accelerated dramatically, the
underlining bias is distinctly positive,'' said Eugene Peroni,
technical analyst at Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. in Philadelphia.
``Most stocks are behaving well.''
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4-to-3 in
nationwide trading of NYSE-listed stocks, with 808 up, 626 down and
505 unchanged.
   Among the most prominent issues, IBM slumped 1[ to 112~ on
reports that a group of smaller computer makers planned to
introduce a rival to the Personal System-2. IBM's decline helped
drag down some other big-name technology stocks, notably Digital,
which fell 2 to 92{, and Compaq, down 1{ to 52|.
   A plunge in oil prices depressed petroleum stocks although it
helped transportation issues. Chevron fell | to 44{, Schlumberger
fell { to 32{ and Occidental fell ] to 25~. AMR rose 1| to 44~,
Delta rose ~ to 47} and UAL rose 1] to 91.
   Waste Management gained 1\ to 38~. The Wall Street Journal's
``Heard on the Street'' column Tuesday said the company could
benefit from tightened state regulations on trash disposal.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market,
totaled 147.26 million shares.
   The Wilshire Associates Equity Index, the market value of NYSE,
American and OTC issues, rose $8.58 billion.
   The NYSE composite index of all listed issues rose 0.54 to 150.20
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 1.27 to 304.62, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index rose 1.11 to 265.59.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index rose 0.97
to 296.56. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 377.33, up 0.82.
</TEXT>
