<HEAD>Dollar Declines In Moderate Trading; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: PRECEDE LONDON, BC</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar declined against most major
currencies Tuesday pushed down by a wave of selling after the U.S.
currency market reopened following the Labor Day weekend.
   Gold prices also fell after a mixed performance overseas.
Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $426.60 a
troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $429 late Friday.
   Currency brokers said activity in the foreign-exchange market
slowed with the dollar trading in a narrow range following Friday's
selloff in advance of the holiday weekend. Friday's activity was
sparked by a higher-than-expected unemployment figure that showed
the U.S. economy may be weakening.
   The Labor Department reported unemployment rose 5.6 percent in
August, from 5.4 percent in July.
   Friday's selloff was followed by a further weakening of the
dollar in foreign markets Monday, while U.S. currency markets were
closed.
   Analysts said after last week's activity, investors were turning
their attention to this week's report on the Producer Price Index,
an important measure of inflation, and next Wednesday's U.S. trade
deficit figures.
   ``The dollar market will be a side market until then,'' said
Jack Barbanel, first vice president with Gruntal & Co. Inc. in New
York.
   Traders said the markets are likely to remain cautious in
advance of the fresh data.
   In Tokyo, where the trading day begins, the dollar fell 0.43 yen
to a closing 135.60 yen. Later, in London, it was quoted at 135.68
yen. At the end of the trading day in New York, the dollar was down
0.85 yen at 134.925 yen.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7035 to buy one pound, almost two cents more than $1.6860 late
Monday. Later in New York, the pound fetched $1.70365, compared
with $1.6850 late Friday.
   Other late-dollar rates in New York compared with levels late
Friday included: 1.84015 West German marks, down from 1.8524;
1.5530 Swiss francs, down from 1.5567; 1.23405 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.2355; 6.2695 French francs, down from 6.2915; 1,378.00
Italian lire, down from 1,381.50.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday:
1.8425 West German marks, down from 1.8555; 1.5525 Swiss francs,
down from 1.5625; 6.2715 French francs, down from 6.3124; 2.0820
Dutch guilders, down from 2.0957; 1,377.65 Italian lire, down from
1,380.50; 1.2340 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2338.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $428.10 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $427.50 per ounce. In Zurich, gold
closed at a bid $428.00 an ounce compared with $427.50 late Monday.
Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 23 cents to close at a bid $429.15
an ounce.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold closed at $426.70 a
troy ounce compared with $429.30 late Friday.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.56 a troy ounce, compared
with Monday's $6.50.
   On the New York Comex, silver for current delivery fell to
$6.485 per troy ounce, compared with Friday's $6.518.
</TEXT>
