<1ST_LINE>u f AM-PCRivals     09-06 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PC Rivals,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rivals To Launch Alternative To IBM's New PC Line, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   IBM's top rivals in personal computers have
called a news conference for next Tuesday at which they are
expected to announce an alternative design for the way information
flows inside a personal computer.
   The new design would make it possible for the companies to build
personal computers that rival IBM's 1{-year-old Personal System-2
line without departing so far from the older standard, analysts
said Tuesday.
   Compaq Computer Corp. of Houston is leading the challenge, which
may eventually include as many as 30 companies that make personal
computers or related products, said Jim Weil, an analyst for
Gartner Securities Corp.
   Calling the news conference for Tuesday in New York are Compaq,
Japanese-owned Epson America and NEC Corp., Hewlett-Packard Co.,
NEC Corp., Italy's Ing. C. Olivetti, Tandy Corp., Wyse Technology
and Zenith Data Systems.
   The joint project could put additional competitive pressure on
IBM, but it might also help IBM by serving as an acknowledgement
that its new Personal System-2 line has features that are worth
duplicating, Weil said.
   IBM could benefit if the delay in bringing the new computers to
market gives IBM a chance to get its line better established, said
George Colony, president of Forrester Research Inc. in Cambridge,
Mass.
   Colony said he thought creating a new standard was a bad idea
because, ``There would be further confusion on the part of the
users, and that would translate into slower sales.''
   The new standard is for a ``bus,'' something which controls the
way information flows through a computer. The more advanced models
of IBM's Personal System-2 line use a new bus called Micro Channel.
IBM's rivals use the older bus that was used in IBM's PC AT.
   Weil said IBM's rivals will claim that their new bus offers all
the power of IBM's Micro Channel but allows people to continue
using their older add-on equipment, such as circuit cards. IBM's
Micro Channel requires users to buy all new add-on equipment.
   Compaq declined comment on the reports. Weil said that in
addition to the companies calling the news conference, Intel Corp.
and Microsoft Corp. have played a role in developing the new
standard.
   The story was broken by PC Week, a trade newspaper, in this
week's editions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880906-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 2019EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Britain-Cocoa     09-06 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Cocoa,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cocoa Consumers Ask Producers To Pay Debts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nations that consume cocoa appealed Tuesday to
countries that produce it to pay their debts to the International
Cocoa Organization's fund to stabilize falling world prices.
   The organization, composed of 37 cocoa consuming and producing
nations, faces a shortfall in covering operating costs in the cocoa
year that runs from October 1988 to September 1989, said delegates
to the cartel's two-week conference, which opened Monday.
   Cocoa-producing nations owe almost $70 million to the group's
price-stabilization fund. The biggest debtor is the Ivory Coast,
which owes $48 million. Brazil owes $9 million. Other debtors
include Cameroon, Ghana and Nigeria.
   Brazil on Tuesday paid a separate $146,700 it owed to the
group's administrative fund, said its chief delegate Lindenberg
Sette.
   The shortfall in the price-stabilization fund would also leave
the organization unable to finance a proposed new stockpiling
scheme aimed at supporting prices, now at their lowest for seven
years.
   Operating costs for 1988-89 are estimated at $23 million. The
organization estimates it will have only $10 million to $12 million
on hand when the new cocoa year starts Oct. 1.
   The organization may sell cocoa from its current stockpile of
250,000 metric tons to meet the budget shortfall. The
organization's secretariat has drawn up plans to sell 10,000 tons
in 1989 and 15,000 in 1989-90.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
