<DOCNO> AP880906-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 1847EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   09-06 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car and Truck Sales Fall 10.7 Percent, Incentives Why</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Edd in 5th graf is correct.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car and truck sales fell 10.7 percent in August,
compared with the same month last year when incentives called for
quicker buying decisions by consumers, the automakers and analysts
said Tuesday.
   Foreign and domestic vehicle makers, except Japan's Toyota Motor
Sales USA Inc. and South Korea's Hyundai Motor Co., said they sold
1.25 million cars and trucks last month, compared with 1.35 million
during the same month last year.
   For the 10-day period ending Aug. 31, Chrysler Corp. said its
sales of U.S.-made cars inched up 2.6 percent compared with the
same period last year. Ford Motor Co., meantime, said its car sales
for the period fell 1.4 percent and General Motors Corp. reported a
13.9 percent drop.
   Each of the Big Three reported increases in car sales so far
this calendar year.
   Toyota spokesman Edd Snyder said a dealer incentive program that
stretched through the Labor Day weekend delayed computation of the
company's monthly figures. Hyundai's Ted Kade said Tuesday that
figures for the month hadn't been calculated.
   Both automakers said their sales figures would be announced
Wednesday.
   ``The kinds of incentives that are on this year are normal
run-of-the-mill incentives that have been on the cars for a long
time,'' said auto analyst Donald DeScenza of Nomura Securities Inc.
of New York City.
   ``There's no incentive to buy now to take advantage of current
incentives,'' he said.
   A year ago, car makers offered attractive incentives, including
cut-rate financing as low as 1.9 percent for GM vehicles, to lure
customers into showrooms and shrink inventories with just one month
left in the model year.
   Those incentives frequently involved short-term offers such as
low financing and cash-back deals. This year the incentives are
different.
   ``The incentives are sustainable kinds of things,'' DeScenza
said. ``Incentives have a big impact when it's clear to the car
buyer that they are not going to be around very long.
   ``Everybody knew (last year) they were temporary,'' he added,
``that they wouldn't last forever. Everybody knew that the models
that qualified for them were in limited supply and dwindling
rapidly.''
   Tom O'Grady, president of Integrated Automotive Resources Inc.
of Wayne, Pa., agreed, saying last year's incentives colored the
sales figures this year.
   ``Certainly we're going to be down (in sales) from last year,''
he said. ``These are certainly very strong sales.''
   GM and Ford showed declines in late-August and monthly sales
while Chrysler showed increases during the two periods. There were
nine selling days in both late-August periods and 27 sales days in
August of this year, compared with 26 in August of 1987.
   For the Aug. 21-31 period this year, Chrysler said it sold
32,214 cars made in the United States, 2.6 percent higher than the
31,388 it sold during the same period last year. Ford sold 65,600
U.S.-made cars during the period, a 1.4 percent decrease from the
66,515 cars it sold during the same time last year.
   GM's late-August sales fell from 126,629 last year to 108,986
this year, a drop of 13.9 percent.
   For the month, the No. 1 automaker sold 284,056 cars, off 20.7
percent from 345,098 in August 1987. Ford's monthly sales dropped
6.2 percent from 182,824 in August 1987 to 178,023 last month.
   Chrysler showed the only monthly gain among the Big Three,
rising from 75,156 U.S.-made cars in August of last year to 82,366
cars last month _ a 5.5 percent increase.
   ``Chrysler has been more aggressive than the other two in using
incentives to stimulate sales ...'' DeScenza said. ``There's an
implication that they're buying the sales (with incentives).''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880906-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-06-88 2024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Britain-Distillers     09-06 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Distillers,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Setback For Pernod In Fight For Irish Distillers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A multimillion-dollar merger battle over the
whiskey giant, Irish Distillers Group PLC, was in the balance
Tuesday night after a watchdog body for London's City financial
district rejected an appeal by European bidders.
   The British Panel on Takeovers and Mergers threw out an appeal
by France's Pernod Ricard SA against a panel decision allowing
British rival hotel and leisure group, Grand Metropolitan PLC, to
sweeten its hostile bid by launching a ``knockout'' bid offer.
   The fight is three-cornered as British brewers, Watney Mann and
Truman Holdings, are also seeking to control the Irish company.
   On Wednesday, the legal battle shifts to Dublin, where Pernod is
trying to stop a key shareholder selling its stake to Grand Met.
   After days of suspense, Pernod formally made a 244 million
pounds sterling ($415 million) bid for Irish Distillers on Monday,
but Grand Met raised its original 180 million pounds ($306 million)
offer to 284 million pounds ($483 million).
   The Grand Met offer amounts to 525 Irish pence a share from an
earlier 400 Irish pence a share. The Pernod bid is worth only 450
Irish pence a share.
   On Sunday, the executive of the takeover panel ruled that was
acceptable for Grand Met because it gave shareholders the
opportunity to decide the best offer. This was despite an earlier
pledge from Grand Met not to change its offer in the absence of a
rival bid.
   The full panel on Tuesday ended a day of deliberation by backing
the executive's decision and rejecting the Pernod appeal.
   Meanwhile, Pernod had said it would not be prepared to act as a
``white knight'' to save Irish Distillers from Grand Met. unless it
was pledged the support of 50 percent of Irish Distillers shares.
   At the weekend it believed it had this support, holding pledges
that included one from fruit and vegetable group FII Fyffes PLC, a
Dublin fruit and vegetable merchant, which holds 20 percent of
Irish Distillers.
   But fears that Fyffes was about to change its mind and go for
the higher English offer led Pernod to seek a temporary injunction
from the Dublin High Court preventing Fyffes from selling to Grand
Met.
   A full hearing of the case will take place Wednesday. Pernod
says it admits the Fyffes promise was not in writing, but believes
it to be legally enforceable.
   Irish Distillers products include Irish whiskey brands Jamesons,
Powers, Paddy and Tullamore.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
